deck_excerpt: KrasherV's 1st place SPYRAL HERO DM decklist
deck_description: What deck did you play and why?  SPYRAL HERO DM. I played it because it was the last list I sent to Pandor from the previous tournament I played (a locals) and I didn't have the time to build a deck for the Cup. Oddly, I lost both matches I played on that locals with this deck, while I finished undefeated the YTC.  What tech choices did you play?  I decided to play Apprentice Illusion Magician and Dark Magician as my secondary Soul targets. I also played Magicalized Fusion with the intention of using DM and any Spellcaster from GY to make The Dark Magicians, but the idea did't work and I ended up siding out the card every match (I made TDM a few times with Polymerization, tho). I also played SPYRAL MISSION - Recapture because I think it's actually good, since it both protects the Sleeper Summon from some common backrow cards like Torrential Tribite or Bottomless Trap Hole and the effect to take control of a monster is not that rare with all the revival I was playing.  How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?  I'll 100% cut Magicalized for Oasis of Dragon Souls. I would also cut Apprentice since 2 Soul targets are enough. Also, with current proposed hits in mind, I would remove either Sleeper or Sleeper+Last Resort and Sunrise+Miracle Fusion, while going for 55 cards to keep Liquid Soldier.  How were your matchups?  Round 1 I played against Labcoat's Unchained Traptrix. It was very difficult because the Unchained big guy has non-targeting destruction, to the point I thought I was going to lose, but I managed to win since Sleeper is that strong. Round 2 was against Jmax's Machines. Sleeper did most of the work here. Round 3 vs WTrain's Unchained Shaddoll HERO. Opened really good both games. Won G1 thanks to Sleeper and G2 thanks to Fully Armed banishing both Construct and Winda. Round 4 my opponent was Tactic Lu. They oppened badly both games. Round 5 vs GuiltyGearxx's Chaos HERO Shaddoll. G1 I open badly and he opens really good so I lose. G2 I win thanks to Fully armed banishing Winda. G3 I summon Sleeper on my 1st turn and enters unninterrupted. Top 8 was vs Spiderking on Synchro Traptrix. G1 I went for a T1 Sleeper that got BTH'd, but since I was ahead on resources and I had enough responses I managed to summon Sleeper a second time. G2 he opened badly and I opened Vyon. Top 4 was vs Wtrain again. G1 I lose since he has more responses than I had starters. G2 I manage to outresource him. G3 it's literally Super Agent Beatdown, since he bricked and I summoned both Super Agent and Tough to use their effects and attacked. Finals was vs Tactic Lu. G1 I summoned Sleeper but got outed, and in the end my opponent attacking with Sera into Tough (It was set to avoid the trap Holes) and equipping Fully armed to him won me the game. G2 I could play through the interruptions my opponent had and I negated his Vyon. In the end I won by attacking into a timelord and activating Forbidden Chalice on it for Exact lethal damage.

What deck did you play and why?  Hero and Shaddoll are both very strong fusion decks at the moment with good consistentcy to search out fusion spells and the ability to easily trigger graveyard effects in both archetypes. Chaos Dragons are a powerful reward for using fusion plays to place cards in the GY and send cards like eclipse wyvern and brotaur to search big rewarding monsters. Neos fusion serves as an additional way to get to important play starters.  What tech choices did you play?  Added more light monsters since just a light with a fusion spell and shaddoll monster can enable access to the loop of recurring construct and other shaddoll fusions with the revival trap. For this reason I added seyfert and extra neos, though they were pretty unexceptional outside of fusion material. I tried to main as many consistency cards as possible knowing that targeted negations and handtraps would probably only come in from my opponent past game 1. After game 1 I can rely less on consistency and more on side cards. Hero lives was pretty questionable though and I didn't feel great about it.  How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?  The main deck out values most decks, In subsequent games I tried to gain an advantage by siding handtraps that dealt with the vyon combo turn 1 and removal for traptrix, also some gy hate for spirits. That's pretty much it.  How were your matchups?  My side behaved extremely well this month. Mainly I only lost to sleeper and disruption. Ariel is extremely good vs spirits. Otherwise I just pretty much had the proper removal to deal with threats until top 8. I need more interaction I think, because I was always scared of aggro.

What deck did you play and why?  I decided to play dinos, because I’d always really enjoyed them and the last time I was going to play them, I changed decks at the last second. That’s about it  What tech choices did you play?  For tech choices, I was running Sales Pitch in the maindeck and Big Burn in the sideboard, along with the classic Pacifis cards. Sales Pitch is an amazing card, just due to the fact that its capable of searching any card in your deck. Combine that with the fact that most decks that were being played searched multiple times each duel, and the card has a good-fair chance of being live when drawn. Big Burn is my special anti-GY card. When it resolves, every monster in the GY is banished. Due to the fact that I’m playing dinos, I’m carrying a couple ways of recovering/playing around that (Giant Rex and Overtex Qoatlus), while a deck like Dark Spirit Unchained will become severely crippled upon resolution. Pacifis was included simply because Kabazauls and MegalosmasherX are the best cards in the deck, so why would I not want to play around them?  How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?  Due to the meta being rather GY oriented and floaty (floating on destruction/sending), I ran a number of cards in the Main Deck and Sideboard geared to counteract that (D.D. Crow, Called by the Grave, Big Burn, Jelly Cannon, Karma Cut, Paleozoic Dinomischus, Storming Mirror Force.) Was also maining Sales Pitch due to the level of searching that I expected to be occurring. Lastly, due to how Extra Deck focused most of the decks appeared to be, I was siding Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag in order to steal their monsters from the Extra Monster Zone and use them against my opponent.  How were your matchups?  Most of the matchups were fine. The only difficult matchups I had were vs Chaos HERO Dolls and Dark Spirit Unchained. Both decks have incredible recover and are capable of going extremely positive in card advantage, so it’s rather difficult for Dinos to deal with them without niche options.  How would you change the deck going forwards?  In the future, I’m looking forward to ETCO introducing Jewel Beast – Argosaurus which is an incredible card for dinos, due to it being able to search Double Evolution Pill, D.D. Crow and Masked Chameleon. I would aim to shift the deck from 60-card pacifis to lower decksize with more combos and easier access to specific cards.

What deck did you play and why?  I played Shaddoll HERO Traptrix Cyber Dragon, a kind of 4-way meta mash. I played it because HEROdolls were not hit since last cup and they were clearly best deck and I did pretty well last cup for my standards. Additionally Traptrix added another engine that wouldn't allow me to run out of gas. The general idea was to add a goal for all the HEROdoll advantage, and Traptrix gave them interruption, if my opponent didn't play into the Traptrix stuff, then I could play HEROdolls with extra backrow. Cydra were just a light engine to send off of Shaddoll Fusion for Construct since I heard not abusing Construct was playing the deck wrong but it was mostly useless.  What tech choices did you play?  I mostly picked my tech choices from an article/decklist Mika made on the most impactful side-deck and tech cards for this format, most of the spice is on the side deck, different Trap Holes for different decks. I guess running 3 Myrmelio is kind of a tech, mostly because I didn't want to run the other bad Traptrix.  How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?  I didn't prepare for the meta more than reading the article mentioned above and implementing Traptrix as another way to never lose momentum. I don't think any of the big components of this deck will survive the next banlist, but in retrospect, 1 of the Myrmelio I was running could have been another Shadow Mist so I could play with the HERO part of the deck more often.  How were your matchups?  First game was against an illegal decklist. Second game was Mekk HERO which was really strong. Third game was pure-ish Traptrix, match was fun but since I was playing Traptrix too, I managed to steal Myrmelio and make Sera, game was always in my hand tho. Forth game was Spyral HERO and I got completely and utterly destroyed, Sleeper destroys this deck single handedly, beats over Wynda, pops Construct/Sunriser, immune to Absolute Zero and nobody would summon it to a Sera board. 5th game was against Traptrix Synchro and it was a tug of war, really fun but again was never in a losing position due to my advantage.  In the top 8 I rematched Mekk HERO and got a win via a topdeck war, which this deck seems to be adept at, then I played vs Gem-Knight which were sadly demolished by convinient hand traps, and lastly was defeated by Spyral in a way more interactive duel than I was expecting.  Most of these games I was safety netted by my deck just being strong and my luck being incredibly generous, except for the Spyral games.

deck_excerpt: The Eldlich archetype from secret slayers offers an insanely strong resource management game and can put up a stupid amount of damage on board after n
deck_description: The Eldlich archetype is one of the strongest decks we've seen from a deck-building set in a long while. With strong resource management and cards that offer heavy disruption and utility on your opponent's turn, Eldlich is definitely going to be a strong rogue-option moving forward in the yugioh meta. Though the TCG lacks a few of the cards that make the stun build of Eldlich more deadly, adding handtraps is always a solid way to make sure your opponent can't really play the game. Eldlich The Golden Lord makes going second or recovering from previous turns more bearable by offering additional removal and pushing for game.

Strong archetype made more consistent with Gallant Granite, able to set multiple negations, OTK with Utopia Double, and able to recover because it's a
deck_description: Going first, we need our negation online (by searching it from Zefraniu or Zefra Providence), so Zefraath is our best starter here. Zefraath as pendulum scale can send Zefraniu to extra deck face-up, then we link it off + another monster for Verte (if you searched Nine Pillars, you gotta keep Zefraniu on field), make Dragun as another negation to strengthen our board.  Going second, we can focus on Utopia Double if we have the opportunity to one shot our opponent.  Pros: Easy and simple combo, great first turn board, can OTK going second, can include handtraps, very recursive because its pendulum, consistency is boosted because Gallant Granite can search Zefraath or Zefra Core.  Cons: Needs multiple Zefra monster to pop off, hard time breaking established board if they know your strategy (so far most people didnt generally know Zefra with xyz strategy).

deck_excerpt: A simple Unchained deck that I've seen good success at the local level with. Might have regional potential with the right format and pilot.
deck_description: The main point of this deck is to control your opponent by linking of their important materials and popping their cards before they are able to capitalize on them. The deck takes practice and requires you learn the balance of popping your own cards versus popping your opponent's cards. There are a lot of times where you intentionally die by battle just to proc effects and extend plays. This deck also has a lot of battle phase shenanigans with Rakea, Abominable, and Escape of the Unchained.  A few explanations:  Interrupted Kaiju Slumber: Dark Hole that gives both players Kaijus. Notably this allows you to use Unchained Soul of Disaster to link with the Kaiju given to your opponent. 4 Kaijus is a good ratio I believe. You can certainly run more, but I don't think the field spell is a great inclusion because it isn't searchable and doesn't always give you the value you would like. Opening Kaiju Slumber, any twin, and the field spell however can end on Soul of Rage backed by multiple negates, so if you can find a consistent way to do so, run wild with it.  Dark Spirit of Banishment/Malice: Self-recurring handtraps that summon your level 8 unchaineds out of grave, with Banishment also redirecting an attack in the process. Note that they negate the effect of the summoned monster so you can't then use Abominable to pop or Disaster to link off opponent's monsters, but if Disaster is destroyed his grave effect will still fire.  Witch's strike: Popping backrow against Unchained is just a bad idea. I'm doing that myself half the time anyway. This is a very nice power trap that blows out the opponent. Helps a lot in the Guru matchup. This can be replaced with any 3 cards of your choice.  The extra deck: You pretty much just need the Unchained links, the other stuff is really just utility. Unicorn is nice because you can make it on the opponent's turn to get that additional shuffle. BLS link is pretty easy to make with a level 7 or higher. Dingirsu allows you to handle things you can't normally. Borrelsword exists for the sole purpose of outing Ultimate Falcon, you typically don't OTK or when you are in a position where you could you're probably locked into summoning Fiends. Masterking is really only made when you have a Dark Spirit summoned off of Tour Guide you need to put in grave. There is so much flex space in this extra deck. Everything in here has come up once or twice at least, but there's probably better situational links/rank 8s.

deck_excerpt: Gladiator Beasts, Special Summons, Contact Fusion, Possible OTK.
deck_description: This is my first uploaded deck, so I hope my review sounds alright.  Better to go second deck.  Best starting hand would be: 1 Rescue Rabbit, 1 G.B. Comeback, and the third and possibly a neccessary fourth card can be a few different card(s), but your first main goal is to get Test Panther and one Gladiator Beast on the field, along with having two other Gladiator Beasts that are in your hand and/or your GY with the GY being more preferable.  The best way to OTK:  Use a rescue animal to get two Andal's/Samnite's on your field and either use double summon, instant fusion an Essedarii/Thousand Keys (Definitely the least preferable option.  You'll understand why later.), Unexpected Dai an Andal (before the rescue animal), etc. to get three monsters total on the field.  If you used Rescue Rabbit and get just one Andal in your hand as well, you can link summon Link Spider with one of the Rabbit's Andal's and then use Link Spider's ability to Special Summon the Andal in your hand.  There are quite a few possible ways to do this, some scenarios can even get four or more monsters on your side of the field before the next step, but if you have enough Gladiator Beast monsters in your hand to pull off the next few steps efficiently, the best option is to use Mind Control on an opponent's monster and use it to link summon in the next step.  Your first goal is to link summon Test Panther with two of your three monsters and have one G. Beast leftover on the field.  So, if one of your three monsters isn't a Gladiator Beast, make sure you use it in the link summon.  Once you link summon Test Panther, you can add G.B. United to your hand from the deck.  When using the other ability of Test Panther, swap out the Gladiator Beast on the field with Test Pather, with Attorix from your deck and use its ability to send an Augustus to the GY from your deck.  By doing this, Attorix is considered Augustus in both name and level for the rest of the turn.  If you have G.B. Comeback, use it to special summon the Augustus in the GY to the field (This step can, if possible, can be done anytime before the battle phase).  Then special summon Andabata with G.B. United.  For the three monsters you use, if you can special summon Augustus from the GY with G.B. Comeback, use the Attorix that had it's named changed when you sent Augustus to the GY as a substitute for Augustus, and leave Augustus on the field.  And then use two other monsters, besides Augustus, from your GY, field, and/or hand, preferably the GY.  If you can't special summon Augustus from the GY, leave Attorix on the field when special summoning Andabata.  Do not use both the Attorix on the field and Augustus, if possible, when using the G.B. United.  Andabata can special summon Gyzarus who can then destroy 2 cards on the field.  Destroy all your opponents monsters with this ability if you can.  Next, use Andabata and Gyzarus to contact fuse and summon Tamer Editor.  Tamer Editor can then special summon another fusion Gladiator Beast, so pick either Heraklinos or Domitianus.  If there aren't any monsters on your opponent's field by this point, Heraklinos is preferable to destroy any possible spells/traps, and if you can get Augustus on the field, you'll have exactly 8000 attack points between Augustus, Tamer Editor, and Heraklinos.  Keep in mind, because of G.B. United, Test Panther can't attack the turn you use it.  (If you have Instant Fusion in your hand when you summon Tamer Editor, you can have Tamer Editor special summon Gyzarus instead, destroy two more of your opponent's cards, and then you can use Instant Fusion to special summon Essedarii.  Gyzarus and Essedarii can contact fusion into your second Tamer Editor and use it to special summon a Heraklinos or Domitianus.  A great alternate if you don't have Comeback.)  If everything goes right you'll have 8000+ attack points between all your monsters by the time you enter your battle phase, and hopefully no monsters on your opponent's field, so you can OTK.  And if that's not possible, you have many options to hold your own.  There are other slightly altered ways to do it besides what was just stated.  For example, if you get 1 Augustus in your hand at the start, instead of Attorix, you can use Test Panther to special summon the Augustus in your deck, who can then special summon the Augustus in your hand to the field.  I would only do this if you don't have G.B. Comeback, because if you go the Heraklinos route, you'll want to have as many cards in your hand as you can spare.  If you get the optimal hand, and there are more than a few different combinations to accomplish it in this deck's setup, you can OTK your opponent if you go second.  And between the main and extra deck, the only card in this deck that is selling for more than $4 is Evenly Matched, which many could do without.  This deck isn't very expensive considering how effective it is.
Deck Strategy: Pretty Simple NGL, you'll figure it out :)

deck_excerpt: A Combo Control deck that abuses Denglong to generate card advantage.
deck_description: Tenyi Yang Zing (TYZ) is a deck that's main focus is on card advantage. Card advantage is how TYZ is able to get a leg up on other decks and overwhelm them Non-effect monsters and synchros. The main play of the deck is to use one of the 3 one card starters (Souleating Oviraptor, Draconnet, Mathematican) to synchro summon Denglong and search Nine Pillars (Pro tip don't set backrow until you search Nine Pillars to ensure your opponent doesn't know where you set it). Then afterwords, use Denglong's effect to send a Tenyi from deck to GY (the best one to send, most of the time, is Ashuna) (BTW the level change isn't that important). Then on the opponent's turn negate something with Pillars and off of denlong being sent to GY summon Bi'an, then you revive Denlong with either Buddy Force or Back to the Front, use denlong to search Yang Zing Path (for card advantage), and when you see an opportunity use Bi'an to synchro with Denlong into Baxia and shuffle 2 cards on the opponent's field (Pro tip don't chain Bi'an to a card effect because if you do Baxia will miss timing, also Bi'an gives Baxia battle protection). That's the main bread and butter combo of the Deck that's a +2 in card advantage and gives you a way to recycle the Yang Zings (and draw 2) and puts a Tenyi in the GY. Trinitys: Trap Trick & Draco Masters, Denglong & Vessel, and Nine Pillars

deck_excerpt: ABC, VW, XYZ, A-to-Z, VWXYZ, and ADCC
deck_description: Perfect Opening 5 - ADCC: Ojamatch Ojamagic Ojamassimilation Ojamassimilation Level Up!   You will need to draw at least one Ojama monster during this combo line in order to summon ADCC. There are a bunch of them in the deck though; the odds are pretty good.   The Combo: During your Draw Phase, play Ojamatch, discarding Ojamagic. Get Armed Dragon LV3 and Ojama Red. Normal Summon Armed Dragon LV3. After Ojamatch resolves, you grab Ojama Black, Ojama Green, and Ojama Yellow off of Ojamagic's effect. Draw for turn. During your Standby Phase, Armed Dragon LV3's effect activates. Special summon Armed Dragon LV5. During your First Main, normal summon Ojama Red, bringing out Ojama Black, Ojama Green, and Ojama Yellow with its effect. Use the four Ojamas to Link Summon Saryuja Skull Dread. Draw 4 cards, then put 3 cards from your hand on the bottom of the deck. Play Level Up!, upgrading Armed Dragon LV5 to Armed Dragon LV7. Play Ojamassimilation. Reveal XYZ-Dragon Cannon; banish three Ojama's from your graveyard; and special summon X-Head Cannon, Y-Dragon Head, and Z-Metal Tank. Banish X-Head Cannon, Y-Dragon Head, and Z-Metal Tank to Fusion Summon XYZ-Dragon Cannon. Activate the Ojamassimilation in your graveyard to return the three banished Ojamas to your deck, shuffle, and draw a card. Play Ojamassimilation. Reveal VW-Tiger Catapult, banish the Ojama in your graveyard and an Ojama in your hand, and special summon V-Tiger Jet and W-Wing Catapult. Banish V-Tiger Jet and W-Wing Catapult to Fusion Summon VW-Tiger Jet. Banish VW-Tiger Catapult and XYZ-Dragon Cannon to Fusion Summon VWXYZ-Dragon Catapult Cannon. Banish Armed Dragon LV7 and VWXYZ-Dragon Catapult Cannon to Fusion Summon Armed Dragon Catapult Cannon.   End State: Saryuja Skull Dread (2800 ATK) and Armed Dragon Catapult Cannon (3800 ATK) on the field and 3 cards in hand.     Perfect Opening 5 - A-to-Z: Ojamatch Ojamagic Ojamassimilation Ojamassimilation any Ojama monster   You will need to draw at least one more Ojama monster during this combo line in order to summon A-to-Z. There are a bunch of them in the deck though; the odds are pretty good.   The Combo: During your Draw Phase, play Ojamatch, discarding Ojamagic. Get Armed Dragon LV3 and Ojama Red. Normal Summon Armed Dragon LV3. After Ojamatch resolves, you grab Ojama Black, Ojama Green, and Ojama Yellow off of Ojamagic's effect. Draw for turn. During your Standby Phase, Armed Dragon LV3's effect activates. Special summon Armed Dragon LV5. Draw for turn. During your First Main, normal summon Ojama Red, bringing out Ojama Black, Ojama Green, and Ojama Yellow with its effect. Use the four Ojamas to Link Summon Saryuja Skull Dread. Draw 4 cards, then put 3 cards from your hand on the bottom of the deck. Play Ojamassimilation. Reveal ABC-Dragon Buster; banish 3 Ojamas from your graveyard; and special summon A-Assault Core, B-Buster Drake, and C-Crush Wyvern. Use Armed Dragon LV5, A-Assault Core, B-Buster Drake, and C-Crush Wyvern to Link Summon a second Saryuja Skull Dread. Draw 4 cards, then put 3 cards from your hand on the bottom of the deck. Banish A-Assault Core, B-Buster Drake, and C-Crush Wyvern from your Graveyard to Fusion Summon ABC-Dragon Buster. Activate the Ojamassimilation in your graveyard to return the three banished Ojamas to your deck, shuffle, and draw a card. Play Ojamassimilation. Reveal XYZ-Dragon Cannon; banish the Ojama in your graveyard and the two in your hand; Special Summon X-Head Cannon, Y-Dragon Head, and Z-Metal Tank. Banish X-Head Cannon, Y-Dragon Head, and Z-Metal Tank to Fusion Summon XYZ-Dragon Cannon. Activate the Ojamassimilation in your graveyard to return the three banished Ojamas to your deck, shuffle, and draw a card. Banish ABC-Dragon Buster and XYZ-Dragon Cannon to Fusion Summon A-to-Z Dragon Buster Cannon.   End State: Saryuja Skull Dread (2800), Saryuja Skull Dread (3100), A-to-Z Dragon Buster Cannon (4300), and 4 cards in hand.   You can get fancy with some of the combo lines (summoning XYZ before ABC lets you use the Ojamas in your hand to blow up your opponent's stuff) so there's no reason to stick to them religiously. Just have fun, sequence your plays to the best of your abilities, and remember to Chazz it up!

If you like field nukes, you will love this deck. It's about as field-nukey as field nuking can get. The original Demise is not once per turn, so you can keep blowing the field up if your opponents has floaters, as long as you have the life points. Big Demise is a nuke with no cost most of the time. Ruin is okay, she's mainly there for OTKing, especially the big one. It is a ritual deck, so it's about as consistent as any deck can get (that's a joke, by the way. Rituals have never been consistent without being broken, look at Gishki and Nekroz). The two normal monsters are there for Advanced Ritual Art. Since there's no real way to summon them, I just picked two that I like. There's no extra deck, because this deck doesn't really keep up enough field presence to have one. It's an absolute blast to play, because who doesn't like blowing up a field your opponent spent five minutes making?

deck_excerpt: This is a blind going second deck which doesnt require using the extra deck to play around such strategies as Shaddoll and Infernoid. It is a beatdown
deck_description: Hello,  I have been playing Ancient Warriors since they were released in IGAS and have put many hours in to playing them in locals and online games. This is what I believe to be the most consistent way to play the deck at the moment.  I will do a basic overview on the main goal of the deck - you very much have to play with the hand you get and work out which path is the best to take. It can struggle going first but as most decks do, it you get the right cards you will be able to set up a bit of a headache for your opponent.  So it is a blind second deck with the focus on getting multiple AW's on the field. Three Visits is the card you want to see in your hand every time as this really allows you to play. Going second this combined with Loyal Guan Yun gets you a beater with a pop on to the field and the ability to search for another AW.  If you are still outnumbered by the opponent Virtuous Liu Xuan will gain you further advantage by being able to special summon out another AW - usually this will be Masterful Sun Mou.  Sun Mou in my opinion is the best monster in this deck. His search ability sends as cost so combined with Three Visits and an AW in hand, even if you dont get to search you should get the special summon. More often than not off Sun Mou's search you will be adding Valiant Zhang De as by this point you should have 2 AW's on field to make use of his ss ability.  Zhang De summon can be used to trigger Sun Mou's bounce effect which really starts giving some pressure. Speaking of Mou's bounce effect, in the battle phase with Liu Xuan in play, you can attack with Mou to trigger Xuan, draw 1, then trigger Mou to bounce before the attack goes through (if you haven't already bounced this turn).  Graceful Zhou Gong is ok. He is very situational but does allow the deck to OTK by using his search effect to get Ancient Warrior Saga - Sun-Liu Alliance to hand. If you are taking this route you will have most likely gone second and be out numbered by your opponent and either special summoned it with Xuan or by popping Three visits to special summon it from hand. I never find it worth while to normal summon him unless you have Three Visits and need the search for a second AW.  With Gong and hopefully 2 other AW's on field you will be able special summon Zhang De to trigger some effects including Alliance which will give them all a 1200 atk boost and should give the OTK.     The Draco engine in this deck really gives it the consistency it needs and the ability to cause more problems to the opponent. Not only does it have great synergy with the AW's ability to send cards to the graveyard, the added backrow and monster removal its a great equaliser and the search from Heritage and Disciples comes up more than you would expect. Also being able to summon Dinomight and Ignis on your opponents turn and pop a monster with Apocalypse is very handy.  Nibiru and Gameciel are musts in most going second decks and with the amount of combo and break my board decks they are really handy. A great interaction between Sun Mou and Gameciel is that you can use Gameciel to tribute a troublesome card, Mou effect to bounce it back to hand and then use Gameciel once more to get rid of a second card.  Metaverse and Mystic Mine are insanely helpful especially when you are waiting on one more piece to allow you to push for game. With many cards in deck that will allow you to get rid of your own mine, it is just an added level of protection incase you dont get the cards you needed.  Many decks you will see will run Fire Formation - Tensu for the extra normal summon, personally i found this card to be a brick / do nothing card most of the time so chose to run Gyokkou instead. The ability to shut down a backrow spot and force your opponent to use resorces to deal with it is insane and when anti spell is sided in you can lock down important combo starters ect. I know this is a point people will disagree with me on, but if you feel strongly about it then you can always side it for going first, however it is a brick when you cant use it.  I hope this helps anyway, once the new support comes out a pure version might be more conisitent and powerful than this, but I will continue to play test and deck build and hopefully will post another one once the cards are released and I have had time to play with it all.

deck_excerpt: The most degenerate going first and best going 2nd trap deck of all time... thanks to handy floodgates, generic board breaking cards, handtraps, and t
deck_description: B.R.O.K.E.N. Broken control, broken recovery, broken general support, broken generic cards... This deck is by far one of the most degenerate and evil decks I have ever played. It was only a matter of time before people figured out how to secure this deck a spot in the meta... and it turns out that embracing the fact Eldlich is a trap deck is the way to do it. After studying and mastering this not so difficult to play deck, I have realized just how easy and fun it is to watch your opponent squirm and rage trying to get rid of the incredible recursion offered by this archetype's spells and traps. The fact that this deck doesn't require a normal summon adds further insult to injury in the fact that you can run 3 more mini-skill drains in the form of inspector boarder, which also happens to have 2000 attack which can come in handy when you're grinding your opponent into submission, oh by the way, did I mention the deck doesn't require a normal summon? Because going second you can just side in lava golems and sphere modes and let your opponent kiss their 30 minute board setup goodbye.  P.S. This deck is reallllllyyyy easy to play, but if you can't figure it out on your own feel free to reply and I'll see what I can do or like this post and give me clout and I might make a tutorial video. (It might be pretty boring and short considering this isn't exactly a combo deck)
can't play without a deck or graveyard this is supposed to be an anti-meta deck but is like, not a very good one, still tho you might just pull it off who knows.

deck_excerpt: Diviner of the Heralds is coming to TCG and to be nobody's surprise, it's a 1 card True King of All Calamities. With that combo alive, it makes Valkyr
deck_description: Should this site change to EDOPRODECK? Hmm. Anyway the recent EDOPRO (previously YGOPRO Percy) simulator now can work with Mischief of the Time Goddess, making playtesting full power Valkyrie with future/prereleased cards possible. Basic combo is to OTK your opponent using Time Goddess (double battle phase) or Borrelsword Dragon for easier setup. Going first, we can make Apollousa or True King of All Calamities from Diviner of the Heralds. The combo is normal summon Diviner, dump Trias Hierarchia, use Trias tribute Diviner ss Trias, use Diviner ss Sechste, use Sechste ss Sigrun, overlay Trias and Sigrun for True King of All Calamities. The Valkyrie cards ratio is medium because most of them are not too good, only some you wanna see the most, also we dont rely on Ride of the Valkyries that much as it makes our monsters shuffled to the deck going first (doesnt even worth the no damage taken for 2 turns). One copy of Time Goddess because its searchable and mostly a dead card (we can OTK with Borrelsword anyway). The supports: Hecatrice + Valhalla, Hall of the Fallen (free fairy, triggers our Sechste too), Galaxy Cyclone and Night Beam (backrow pops, work with Vierte as both are normal spell, similar to D-Hero Diamond Dude but faster), One for One (for Sechste, Vierte target), Raigeki and Herald of the Abyss (monster pops, Vierte target, we didnt play Lightning Storm as it conflicts with Valhalla), double Dark Ruler No More (only 2 cus while we can do 2 battle phase, this card makes us unable to OTK cus no damage on first battle phase), Reasoning (mainly for Sechste, our Valkyries have different level too), Pots (can be Desires, Extrav, or anything, Valkyrie deck needs so many draw/search cards as much as possible), Monster Reborn and World Legacy Succession (extender, possibly triggering our Valkyries from GY), Tuner's High (Diviner searcher by using Sechste as fodder). Can put Utopia Double if you want but it will be very dependent on our hand. Extra deck: We're using Extravagance, means multiple copies of our important cards. Pros: Going first is much stronger than previous build, have multiple ways of OTK (more if with Utopia Double), bunch of removal/breaking board cards, can put in handtraps. Cons: Only has Diviner as great starter (other ways we might need extenders), Ride of the Valkyries is very bad on first turn (it means drawing multiple Valkyries going first is kinda bricky sometimes). Cards to think of: Honest (great card but dead going first and we can just remove opponents monster anyway), other Valkyrie related spells (some arent that good and some only provides small advantage), Parshath supports (the link 3, the level 9, and the continuous spell can be good in recycling our Valkyries if we play grindy games)

deck_excerpt: A deck of dark spell-casters and fiend type monsters, set up for quick summons and supported by powerful buffs/traps
deck_description:
Quickly summon powerful monsters, with enough spell and trap cards to keep them safe from harm and buffed to take on even the most challenging opponents. The first strategy allows for the summoning of a 'Dark Magician' or 'Dark Eradicator Warlock' within 1 or 2 turns:
  1. Summon 'Skilled Dark Magician'
  2. Play 'Pot of Greed' (+1 spell counter for 'Skilled Dark Magician')
  3. Play 'Double Summon' (+1 spell counter for 'Skilled Dark Magician')
  4. Summon 'Apprentice Magician' (use 'Apprentice Magicians' effect to +1 spell counter for 'Skilled Dark Magician')
  5. Special summon 'Dark Magician' (using the effect from 'Skilled Dark Magician')
  6. Play 'Mystic Plasma Zone'
  7. Play 'Field Barrier'
Or Summon 'The Dark Magicians' with ease:
  1. With 'Dark Magician' or 'Dark Magician Girl' already on the field
  2. Summon (or use if already on the field) 'Apprentice Magician'
  3. Play 'Magical Dimension'
  4. Tribute 'Apprentice Magician'
  5. Special Summon 'Dark Magician Girl' or 'Dark Magician' (using 'Magical Dimension')
  6. Play 'Polymerization'
  7. Fusion Summon 'The Dark Magicians'
with the field card 'Mystical Plasma Zone' on the field all monsters in this deck receive +500 ATK and +400 DEF, 'The Dark Magicians' will have a new 3300 ATK and 2700 DEF... more than enough firepower to stay ahead of the game

deck_excerpt: Infernity meets Flame Noble Igknights, Arma Loops are still very much alive infact destrudo was for casuals. 2 Igknights = full combo, the deck is sup
deck_description:
Deck Notes below deck showcase > https://youtu.be/i8a9ivdcL_I
  •  23 Igknights - (No space for the 24th, 3rd Margrave) - 2 ignights lead to full wombo combo which creates lowkey unbreakable board.
  • 3x Summoner's art - nvm there are actually 26 Igknights.
  • 3x Painful decision - nvm 29 igknights, sending an igknight to the grave matters due to new Flame Noble arms equip and for phoenix blade (my fav scale).
  • Rota - ah I see where this is going but this rarely searches a scale.
Cards you search off 2 Igknights
  • 2x Sublime Knight - You never wanna open 2 so just 2, he is the most searched Fire Warrior of Igknights so it makes sense to run more then 1 atleast.
  • 1x Squeaknight - So In a nutshell Sublime knight is a 1 card Isolde due to SqueaKnight.
  • 1x Super Quantum Red Layer - I mean why not he is a free drop, you actually rarely search him off Igknights this days but there is nothing wrong with him, atleast he can out inspector boarder, can help you reach knightmare phoenix before you do Isolde etc.
  • 1x Flame Noble Knight Renaud - This is lowkey the second most important card in a deck after Armageddon Knight, a fire warrior Kizan if you will which pluses.
  • 1x Flame Noble Knight Olivier - This card helps you make needlefiber at the end of the most combos, it can also help you make Isolde in some hands.
  • 1x God Phoenix Gearfried - can be revived off Ferocious Flame Swordsman. Searched of Igknights, with scythe running around you better have non extra deck wincon, fantastic removal to, just a freaking backup boss monster really which often finds its way to the main combo board
The dark warrior side
  • Armageddon Knight - I am not explaining this bad boy
  • Plaguespeader zombie - Destrudo replacement, You linkross the Isolde.
  • Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite - standard Arma Knight looper
  • Summoner Monk - This is why you do all this loops in the first place, to summon Monk and abuse him twice due to Selene
Summoner Monk & Infernity toolbox
  • Rescue Ferret (I am not playing extra bricks for this, its just 2 monsters into leviar into resseting non HOPT plague)
  • Infernity Archfiend - on summon off monk he searches infernity card
  • Infernity Necromancer - (You usually Saryuja him) - what you search of Archfiend, then you revive the same archfiend and search launcher
  • Infernity Break - I didnt want double barrier in the end, Atleast break gives me something to handle Megaclops
  • Infernity Barrier - Fk Dark ruler no more in particular (JK it fks up everything but ruler no more is the reason for this Infernity engine
  • Infernity Launcher - Gouki (Double) Reborn for Infernities which aren't HOPT,
Equips
  • Cursed Bamboo Sword - chain blocks arma but that doesnt matter you just want to make plague free really
  • Broken Bamboo Sword - you need to offset plaguespreader zombie, only a fking crazy person would put back something of value
  • Divine Sword phoenix blade - I bet OCG is jelly, there are like 10 uses of this card in a deck figure em out by watching a vid tbh
  • "Flame Noble Arms - Joyeuse" - adds back a fire warrior from the graveyard not to shabby
  • "Flame Noble Arms - Durendal"- there are actually 31 Igknights in this deck
  • 3X D.D.R. - Different Dimension Reincarnation - The deck can somewhat loop the Arma without powertool sometimes (just bounce him with zephyros, pend him sending monk) but Overall D.D.R makes the deck more resiliant and fixes your bad hands
Other Isolde turbo cards
  • 3x Neo Space Connector - Its the best 1 card Isolde after Sublime knight in this deck
  • Aqua Dolphin - CBTG on crack, you can pendulum summon as with most of the deck, sometimes you can leviar this back
Extra deck
  • 2x Isolde - even the first effect is busted because you get a scale / half a search
  • Ferocious Flame Swordsman - Another way to loop the arma, this card has many mini implications I wouldnt touch Igknights without it
  • Knightmare Phoenix - purely for going second (well you can APP colink but you get what I mean)
  • Knightmare Unicorn - purely for going second
  • Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians - Aka Double Summoner Monk
  • Saryuja Skull Dread - Aka summon necromancer (tho sometimes you can normal / pend him), also gets you the other Igknight (extreme chance)
  • Linkross - Aka if he gets banned I ll have to update this deck, free token helps you reach the lvl 7 for powertool
  • Number 60: Dugares the Timeless - revives the monk
  • Power Tool Dragon - nearly always live as this deck has 1 more equip then my usual igknight decks due to bamboo engine (searches d.d.r.)
  • Leviar the Sea Dragon - not to relevant as I really never needed plague (not hopt) hand declog, this can be a borrelsword once we get Dragun, but it has some implications tho
  • Desert Locust - handloop, they choose, but this card made me choose Fiber over Herald
  • Borreload Savage Dragon - Omni negate, bit atk
  • Appolousa - plz ban this card (3-4 monster negates on avg), not that Gryphon would be much healthier
  • Needlefiber - if he gets banned dragster x herald in its place

deck_excerpt: New Fluffal support gives a huge boost to Fluffal decks!
deck_description:
Combos
  1.  Summon Frightfur Whale, 2 times, and then summon True king of all calamities. Use Ultra Polymerization to speed up things.
  2. Then we go for Toadally Awesome, and to summon it we use Bahamut Shark, which can be summoned with Fluffal Penguin and Fluffal Dolphin, or if possible Mudswamp Dragon.
  3. Try to use Toy Vendor as a mean to use Fusion Plant (and gain Polymerization) or Eldilch the Golden Lord (to destroy enemy cards), and also to summon the latter from GY.
  4. Use Frightfur Whale summon effect on a Special summoned Eldlich Golden Lord (cannot be destroyed by effects) to gain advantage
  5. Fluffal Dolphin restore used Toy Vendors and discards Fluffal Wings.
  6. As a lot of WATER monsters should be used, we put Adamancipator Risen - Dragite, summoned with Adamancipator Analyzer. In order to exploit its first effect let's keep Nibiru in the deck.
  7. Use Super Polymerization to summon Starving Venom Fusion Dragon or Mudswamp Dragon using your opponents' cards.
  8. Summon Union Carrier to equip Frightfur Saber-Tooth (summoned with 3+ monsters) with Dragon Buster Destruction Sword and prevent special summons from extra deck
  9. Bonus: Artifact Dagda and Artifact Scythe
Enjoy ;)
Xyz spam, possible OTK.

Void imagination is, of course, the strongest card in the deck. You always want to resolve it because you can mill three elder entitys with tierra to pop three cards and you send a lot of infernoids to gy as materials. However you have to side them out, maybe for void feasts, against decks that don't use the extra deck.

deck_name: Shaddoll HERO ABC Chaos Top-4 (Trinity, March 2020)
deck_excerpt: Wuh Train's Shaddoll HERO ABC Chaos Top-4 decklist
deck_description: What deck did you play and why?  I played Shaddoll Hero ABC Chaos. I wanted to play Shaddoll Heroes this month cause the deck seemed broken. I hadn't played trinity in a bit but, luckily my friend, Anim7ed, had an amazing list that he gave me.  What tech choices did you play? Two tweaks I made to Anim7ed's deck were to add in Danger! Bigfoot and Abominable Unchained Soul. Danger! Bigfoot worked out pretty well since this deck has a lot of discard and Bigfoot often was the best discard since you get to destroy a card. Abominable Unchained was amazing. He was easy to summon and whenever he was summoned, he swung the game in my favor.  How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward? I did not prep for the meta but, the deck made by Anim7ed was so strong that it plowed through other decks. There are two things I would change about the deck. The first change is I would add more chaos elements to the deck to which would trigger Eclipse Wyvern more. The second change would be to take out the equip sub-theme. The only good equip in the deck was premature burial and it wasn't good enough to warrant 2 bad equips and 2 equip searchers.  How were your matchups?  The insane value that the deck generated beat most decks. The two decks I struggled with were Mika's Zoodiacs and KrasherV's Spyrals. Mika's Zoos banished a lot of my cards with Whiptail's effect which hurt my recursion and had a lot of disruption. KrasherV's Spyrals establishes threats early and then ends the game when he sets up Sleeper + Last Resort which never leaves room for the dawdling of my deck.

Basically use the new dragmas to use there broken effects, sending extra deck monsters to graveyard and ritual summon to push for game  here is the list  Monster: Adin the Dragma Oracle x2 Theo the Dragma Iron Hammer x3 Ecclesia the Dragma Saint x3 Fleur de Lis the Dragma Knight x2 Maximus Dragma x2 Cardinal of Dogma Tetradragmatton x2 Albus the Nullius Filius x1 Demise, Supreme King of Armageddon x2 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3 Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning x2  Spell: Dogmatic Nation Dragma x3 Disciple of the Nadir x3 Cycle of the World x3 Upstart Goblin x1 Terraforming x1  Trap: Dragma Punishment x3 Dragma Encounter x3 Metaverse x1  Extra: Bastard the Ashen Dragon x2 Elder Entity N'tss x3 Herald of the Arc Light x3 Starving Venom Fusion Dragon x2 PSY-Framelord Omega x3 Linkuriboh x2

What deck did you play and why? I played a variant of Traptrix i call Synchro Traptrix, i played it due to my liking of the Traptrix playstyle with its high consistency and access to powerful trap holes and advantage loops with Sera. However, i felt the deck lacked a strong finisher and method to pressure the opponent so i added several 1 card synchro and XYZ engines, like Oviraptor and Assault to summon strong boss monsters.  What tech choices did you play?  The Lefty and Righty Driver package to make Herald of the Arc Light, Red Blossoms from Underroot and Treacherous Trap Hole were my main tech choices  How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?  I prepared by including a range of tech options strong against meta decks such as the above techs to counter Hero Shaddoll by preventing Shaddoll Fusion or Vyon by banishing cards or by banishing shaddoll fusion or a fusion monster by Blossom, plus Treacherous to serve as a powerful turn 1 option to blow up unprepared boards. I would definitely cut the Drivers, they felt very underpowered with Arc Light being too small to stop the opponent simply running it over before committing, and reallocate some traps to include new cards such as Snowflower Sheet.  How were your matchups? A had a range of good and bad matchups, most notably Unchained which i could counter with the wide assortment of GY hate and banishing methods to limit their recursion, however, i eventually got knocked out by the winning Spyral deck where i was unable to deal with the constant destruction a Sleeper offered. However, even in bad matchups, i could grab wins through Utopia Double granting me some wins i very much did not deserve. Also please send us your decklist
The creator of this deck was unavailable for comment.

deck_excerpt: Based On the new structure deck: Sacred Beasts, This deck uses the new support to OTK your opponent with a Huge Atk point monster in Raviel, Lord of P
deck_description: *Note: This Deck is currently only playable in the OCG, and will be Released on July 10, 2020 for the TCG. Raviel OTK This is a going Second deck based on getting out Raviel and OTK'ing using the new "Raviel, Lord of Phantasms - Heaven Crushing Fist" monster to work as an "honest" effect, doubling your attack points and attacking all monsters your opponent controls. This deck is pretty consistent as most of the cards search each other and can summon Raviel in many ways. Dark Beckoning Beast plus "The Seven Spirit Gates Unleashed" is a two card combo that will end on Raviel on field with Fallen Paradise as well as a link-2. Pentestag for piercing, and Knightmare phoenix for board clearing. Phantom Skyblaster plus any special summoned monster will get you a Saryuja Skulldread which will allow you to extend even further. Card Choice Card choice is highly interchangeable, in order to fit the current meta. The most notable "upgrade" would be replacing Twin Twisters with Lightning Storm adding more versatility to clearing boards while going second. This deck suffers pretty greatly from hand traps/Search negates. The evil hero isn't the most useful card in the deck and the spells are searchable you can consider cutting 1 of the field spell as well as the Seven Gates to add in 3 Called by the grave if you're worried about getting hit with disruption. Alternatively you could replace one of the evil hero's with a Danger!? Jackalope? for some more consistency. The danger package here seems odd at first glance, but it is meant to give more fiend materials on board as well as add draw power to the deck. Nessie! will allow you to add a Chupacabra to hand if it is hit with its own effect. Additionally, adding jackalope will allow you to summon a Chupacabra from deck if you wish to add that as well. Super Polymerization is essential for clearing opponents monsters that will prevent you from searching or using other card effects. That along with Predaplant Dragostepalia clears The Mechaba Winda Lock with ease. This is also run with 2 Starving venom fusion dragon to help clear the abundance of dark monsters in the game.   Side Deck The side deck has been construced for going first in game 2 or 3 in matches Since Hamon uses essentially the same engine as Raviel, you can switch up your strategy to a control variant on the fly. If you choose to, you can also use the sacred beast trap card that works as a one sided skill drain if you have 2 different beasts on the field, however this can be a little less consistent to pull off so I opted for solemn judgement instead. Artifact package should also be able to shut down most opponents who attempt to break your board using the extra deck. Note* This side deck is totally optional, removing The Hamon package can make your side deck more potent for specific threats in the meta.

The deck is centred around the swarming ability of Blackwings and hitting hard with its Synchros, which can easily access when going second to perform OTKs.  When going first, it has access to half the combo of the Infinite Negates build (Simorgh, Infinity, Apex Avian) which makes a very good 2-Negate 1st turn board.  It is fairly consistent and its easy access to Black Whirldwind and Allure of Darkness helps the situation a lot.  The Deck rarely bricks, but when it does it's an instant loss (the majority of the times).  And it's fragile playstyle does not help either when the player draws bad hands.  Overall, the deck is extremely fun to play but besides the most versatile build, it is definitely not a top contender.     If you want to see what the deck can do in action, check out the video:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eXqjVQu53Ws&t=712s

deck_excerpt: A Sacred Beast deck that is able to shut off opponents monster effects on the field, negate spell/traps and divert their attack targets while still be
deck_description: Hello! Welcome to Hamon Control. This deck will be based on the new support in the sacred beast structure deck coming to the tcg on July 10, 2020.   This deck aims to go first and set up Hamon and Raviel with the field spell and New trap card that works as a One sided skill drain! (This is an early build and can still likely be made more consistent) The new "Dark Beckoning Beast" is your bread and butter! Seeing that plus any other of your summoning beasts OR the New search spell "Seven Spirit Gates Unleashed"  is a two card combo that will end you on both Sacred Beasts and the field spell at the very least, meaning you will often have 3 other cards in your hand plus a draw 2 to continue your plays. If you want more consistency over stun capability you can try removing the artifact engine and adding in a few more dangers, as well as foolish burial goods to the deck. Personally, I add level 8 dangers so I can also utilize Trade-in. Foolish burial goods is used to send your "Cerulean Skyfire" to the grave so that Your searcher can bring it back to hand. When being forced to go second in games 2 and 3 it may be wise to drop the artifact package as well as the solemns for some more board clearing capabilities. Evenly Matched, Lightning Storm, and Super Polymerization are your big equalizers. Despite having to give up your battle-phase to resolve evenly matched it will more often than not result in you being able to build a full board while making it almost impossible for your opponent to recur those banished cards. As a reminder for going second, after activating dark summoning beast's ability to summon from hand/deck you will not be able to attack for the rest of the turn. However, if you are able to mount a board presence you may still use your battle phase Before you use this effect. Since all of the cards in the archetype are searchable it may not be necessary to have them run at 3, however they can be easily disrupted by the likes of Infinite impermanence and other hand traps, so be weary and bring along some called by the graves if you find it too troublesome. Good Luck, and have fun!

e presence of melanin.[34] Unlike brown eyes, blue eyes have low concentrations of melanin in the stroma of the iris, which lies in front of the dark epithelium. Longer wavelengths of light tend to be absorbed by the dark underlying epithelium, while shorter wavelengths are reflected and undergo Rayleigh scattering in the turbid medium of the stroma.[4] This is the same frequency-dependence of scattering that accounts for the blue appearance of the sky.[3]:9[6] The result is a "Tyndall blue" structural color that varies with external lighting conditions.

deck_excerpt: The real chaos dragon is returning with this new synchro and Chaos Support. Halfway between a Dragon Link and a Chaos Lightsworn, it has an identity o
deck_description:
Introduction:  Main Level Monsters:4 Main Summons: Hand and Graveyard  ||  Extra Summons: Link, Xyz and Synchro Key cards: Lightsworn Cards, Striker Dragon, Guardragon, Chaos Space. Tier Meta: Rogue Difficulty to use: 4/5
COMBO

I want to premise that it is a complicated combo and above all that it's not always the same, the key moments are the beginning, and in fixing the final board. For these reasons I am not writing the combo step by step, it would be useless, if you want a visual proof as an example, look at the video you find just above the decklist.

The Beginning:

With the new additions, the combo start is very similar to a Dragon Link deck, subsequently our intent is to summon the Guardragon and then Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, after that our aim is to summon Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon (doesn't necessarily have to be summoned at this very moment) to send cards to the graveyard and add a light/dark in hand.

We summon Saryuja Skull Dread 2 times (sometimes only 1 is enough) to draw cards, and in the meantime send as many cards as possible to the graveyard. This is the preparation for the final board which varies according to the cards in hand and the graveyard.

Final Board:

Usually with the second Saryuja Skull Dread I like to summon Lumina, Twilightsworn Shaman from the hand while continuing with it. If you have enough monsters you could adopt to summon Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess in addition to the other usual negate.

Make sure you have Galactic Spiral Dragon at the graveyard to summon Monster rank 8.

Usually the final board is:

Borreload Savage Dragon, Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy, Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord + Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres or Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess.

Tips and Tricks: Initially if you can start with the dragon link combo, try not to send too many cards to the graveyard from Lightsworn effects so as not to risk sending to the gy cards we need to complete the combo, fill the graveyard then that, be careful not to remove too many cards from the game, there must always be several monsters in the graveyard. If you need a monster in your hand but you haven't drawn it so far, you can summon Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon to try to find it among those 5 cards. If we have Starliege Seyfert and Absorouter Dragon in hand we can discard it by cost, triggering its effect, to add Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended, Noctovision Dragon or Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay in hand. Chaos Emperor, the Dragon of Armageddon is essential to recover the removed cards, especially when they are banned from Allure of Darkness.
CONSIDERATIONS
The Deck: As much as it is a particular deck it's quite balanced, even when you have bad hands, you still manage to get away with it. The deck if it's not interrupted by negations really manages to put the opponent in difficulty, but we know it's almost impossible. Well, if it manages to send cards to the graveyard even with negations, this deck doesn't have too many problems to go on. Since the deck sends many cards to the graveyard it's not safe to play many spells,also because those spells in the gy have no use, instead you need light and dark monsters to be removed from the game, to summon our dragons from the hand. The Cards:
  • Lightsworn's cards are fundamental to send as many cards to the graveyard as possible and thanks to Solar Recharge we can also draw 2 cards
  • Chaos Space, maybe is the best card of the deck, manages to give the deck a lot of stability, ensuring that you have some main cards in your hand, as well as letting you discard a card and then draw another.
  • Lightpulsar Dragon is very important not only to summon Chaos Ruler with the help of Plaguespreader zombie and Galaxy Serpent ,but with this card u and you can take advantage of its 3 effects.You can easily summon it and use it to send cards to the graveyard ,moreover you can Summon Hieratic Dragon King of Atum.
  • Starliege Seyfert, it's an excellent card because you can search for practically all the dragons you need, and when it is in your Gy u can banish it to add to your hand Chaos Dragon Levianeer or Chaos Emperor, The Dragon of Armageddon.
  • Chaos Dragon Levianeer, this is a really good card, i normally use it to destroy 2 cards on the field and above all to special summon Monsters from the graveyard like Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, Noctovision Dragon, Omni Dragon Brotaur or 1 of 3 tuner Monsters. If u start for first u can use it to shuffle 1 card from your opponent's hand into the deck.
  • Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Demonic Dragon, The new support that has improved the deck a lot. Even if the first thing to do is to fill the graveyard, try to summon it after the main combo or in any case after having already a good number of cards in the graveyard. The card is not difficult to summon and when it drops on the field in addition to sending cards to the gy it allows you to choose one of those monsters and add it to your hand. Also when you recall it from the gy with its own effect, use it to summon a rank 8 xyz.

So... Have you to start for first or for second?

You can do both very well, obviously having cards with a high attack value is could start for seconds, but you are more likely to be annoyed by your opponent. And if you start first you can play the part of the annoying opponent. Usually is better start for first in this meta.
SIDE DECK

Must Have:

Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju is the only dark Kaiju monster can be used. Its use is obviously very basic, you can easily get rid of an opposing monster, as well as summon it if there is already a Kaiju on the opposing field. We usually prefer its against decks that have 1 major monster boss, like Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. or Nibiru, the Primal Being it's a really strong card against combo decks, if he can't get negation before 5 summon, our opponent most of the time, will pass the turn immediately after. Artifact Lancea is a really strong ht in this meta, it hurts Dino, Invoked, Virtual World, Eldlich, Dragon Link, Infernoble Knight and other . It is also light, which is important. Galaxy Cyclone is excellent because in addition to Chaos Dragon Levianeer, the deck has difficulty breaking opposing spells or traps, and the effect is also activated from the graveyard. It also has a beautiful interaction with Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord which, through its effect in the opponent's turn, allows us to choose a Galaxy card from the deck and add it in hand or attach it as material to it. World Legacy Guardragon we use it to go first having more stability, especially if we are afraid of a possible opponent's Artifact Lancea ,with this card we can advance the combo a minimum, without having to ban cards.

Other cards that may be useful:

Denko Sekka together with Galaxy Cyclone helps us against control decks, in fact if we manage to summon it our opponent will not be able to set cards nor activete s/t that are set on the field. Let's try to protect it with cards like Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy or Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres. Pot of Avarice is an excellent card that allows us, to return resources to the deck as well as to draw 2 cards. It can be played in a version of the deck, that doesn't focus too much on the otk but tries to play for more turns. Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos is an excellent beatdown monster, that is easily summoned even by using most of the high level to make it not targetable.

deck_name: A look at COMPETETIVE LIGHTSWORN feat. SHADDOLL
deck_excerpt: A synchro-focused LIGHTSWORN Deck with SHADDOLL and DRAGON Engine. If the TCG banlist now unbanned Snow and Grass, LIGHTSWORN easily would wreck the M
deck_description:
The Lightsworns are a group who seek to save those who pray for help, crossing time and space in order to help them. By consuming vast quantities of magical energy, they appear on the material plane and challenge those evildoers who threaten the era they appear in. Once their job is done and the evil has been stopped, they return to their home plane, disappearing without a trace. Their founder, Michael, the Arch-Lightsworn, is responsible for enlisting the souls of heroes worthy of joining the Lightsworns. As they travel in order to fight evil, they also recruit the heroes of that time.
Resource: Lore -> https://ygorganization.com/geargia-lightsworn-lore/   Lightsworn: The Deck's History And Strategy Who hasn't heard of them before? Lightsworn Decks aim to send cards from the top of the Deck to the Graveyard and then benefit from sending them there. All Lightsworn monsters (except Wulf, Jenis and Rinyan) mill cards from the top of the Deck to pay the cost for skills or as a requirement at the End Phase. Their monster's effects trigger by either being sent to the graveyard or sending cards to the graveyard - so their GY can basically be seen as their second hand. The usage of Spells and Traps vary in Lightsworn; many play the 'main starter' spells like Solar Recharge (Discard 1 ''Lightsworn'' monster; draw 2 cards, then send the top 2 cards of your Deck to the GY) and Charge Of The Light Brigade (Send the top 3 cards of your Deck to the GY; add one 4-✰ ''Lightsworn'' monster from your Deck to your hand) - other builds integrate the trap Lightsworn Judgment, which acts as a searcher for Judgment Dragon.
The success of the Lightsworn-Decks can be traced back to many different time periods and took many different forms.
Back then, Chaos-Lightsworn and That Grass Looks Greener-Turbo-Milling-Decks completely wrecked the meta (despite bricking every second game) with Judgement Dragon being an easily-summoned monster with integretated spot removal (paying 1000 Life Points to destroy all other cards on the field) and high ATK. They synergize with many other archetypes; (Chaos, Twilightsworn, Shaddolls, Lighttray, Dinosaurs, Dragons, e.t.c.) making them capable of uniting all attributes and a lot of different monster types.
In the history of YGO, The Lightsworn have been hit badly many times - examples of that being the bans of Fairy Tail - Snow, Black Dragon Collapserpent, Destrudo The Lost Dragon's Frisson, Glow-Up-Bulb, That Grass Looks Greener, Soul Charge, Brilliant Fusion, and Sixth Sense, e.t.c.
While the TCG-banlist still holds the Lightsworn-players back, the OCG slowly integrated some of Lightsworn's keycards back into the game. Finally, Snow has been unbanned in the recent banlist (OCG, 2020.04) and That Grass Looks Greener is now semi-limited.  Lightsworn lately haven't seen a lot of competetive play though, due to their vulnerability to negating effects - and undeniablely, this is the current meta's top priority.
To summarise: With great risk often comes great reward.
Lightsworn Decks are capable of a very fast OTK - so they easily can push for game with their powerful Boss Monsters - and going through your whole Extra Deck, (in this deck version mainly Synchro-cards like Borreload Savage Dragon or F.A. Dawn Dragster with negating capabilities). There are failures, setbacks and even complete start-over's along the way; decking out could be a problem for Lightsworns due to milling being your main mechanism. Additionally, Lightsworn Decks rely (sometimes) on the heart of card's (imagine the feeling of bricking with three copies of Wulf, Lightsworn Beast in your starting hand) and are vulnerable to negating effects such as Skill Drain.   An Explanation Of The Card Ratios - (TCG-version) Here I'll explain why I chose certain card ratios and how I use them. In this variant, you have a Dragon- and Shaddoll-engine, combined with some Dangers; improving the draw power (bricking in Lightsworn sucks, sometimes resulting in an immediate game loss) and consistency. Sometimes, the Shaddoll-Fusion-Cards (El Shaddoll Winda) rescue your life going first, limiting your opponent's special summons. First, let's look at the most obvious part: The Lightsworn Monsters.
  • 3x Wulf, 3x Raiden, 2x Lumina, 1x Felis, 1x Garoth, 1x Lyla, 1x Minerva, 1x Judgment Dragon
Raiden and Lumina are the most powerful of the monsters named above: Raiden is a 4-✰ Tuner, milling up to twice per turn and enabling synchro plays. Lumina discards one card in your hand and let's you special summon another Lightsworn in your GY, preferably Raiden to use his milling effect, (or an additional copy of Lumina to revive another Lightsworn monster - it's not a hard once per turn effect).  That's why commonly players play both cards at 3. I agree with Raiden being at his highest ratio, because he's our common normal summon, starts combo-plays, and we want t0 see him as often as possible in our starting hand. If we would put Lumina at the same ratio, there's a problem with 'wasting' a normal summon for her and not milling anything in our Main Phase with her effect. We can search her via Charge Of Light Brigade as well, so she's okay at 2 copies. The Lightsworn cards we want to mill are Wulf, Felis and Minerva. Wulf is a 2,1K Beatstick without ability to mill, and is special summoned if it's sent from your Deck to your GY - an unquestionable 3-of. 'A 4th copy of Wulf', you could say, is Felis. She's a 4-✰ Tuner and special summoned when sent from the Deck to the GY by a monster effect. The last restriction sucks, (that's why I only play one copy), but her spot removal and milling effect outweighs the bad. Both cards can help you go into Synchro, XYZ- and Link-monsters. One card, which rarely sees play in Lightsworn Engines is Minerva. She is a 3-✰ Tuner, who adds you 1 Light Dragon Monster from your Deck to your hand, (whose Level is less than or equal to the toal number of Lightsworn monsters with different names in your GY), when normal summoned. I understand why Minerva doesn't see a lot of play: Minerva's effect requires you to normal summon her and play a lot of Lightsworn monsters (and them to be in the GY)- and she only mills 2 cards at your End Phase. But her additional effect (...If this card is sent from the hand or Deck to the Graveyard: Send the top card of your Deck to the Graveyard ...) helps us mill faster and she helps us with bringing out our Judgment Dragon. Garoth, Lyla and Judgment Dragon are solid monsters, but I only play each of them at 1 copy to avoid bricking.
  • 2x Shaddoll Beast, 2x Dragon, 2x Hedhehog, 2x Falco, 1x Squamata, 1x Reeshaddoll Wendi
The effects of the Lightsworn often trigger a variety of other archtepyes (like Shaddoll cards), but always be aware that milling as a cost does not trigger the Shaddoll cards! Except that, Shaddolls are best friends with Lightsworn (and Dangers). They are perfect targets for Allure Of Darkness, give us draw power, and restrict our opponent. Good thing to mention: Their monsters, traps and spells can be revived from the GY.
  • 1x Wyverbuster, 1x Collapserpent, 2x Starliege Seyfert, 1x Omni Dragon Brotaur, 1x Levianeer
A Dragon-Engine, which enables more Extra-Deck plays, especially Links, and brings our beloved Judgment Dragon to our field. Especially Seyfert acts as decent normal summon and searcher, and can banish itself to add 1 Level 8 Light or Dark Dragon from our GY to our hand. Play them, it's worth the money. The other monster cards in this Deck Build are Dangers, Handtraps (and Gizmek Orochi). One thing to mention about the spells that might surprise you is that I play Solar Recharge just at 2 copies. I don't play a lot of Lightsworn to justify it's highest ratio, and I am fine with using Allure Of Darkness. Extra Spice / Deck Ideas In the OCG, there's a card named Chaos Ruler the Chaotic Demonic Dragon. It's the BEST Synchro-monster for Lightsworn in a while, because it adds you 1 card to your hand and mills 4 cards. It can revive itself via banishing one Light or Dark monster from your hand or GY - again a perfect opportunity to introduce the next card ... Nemesys Keystone. Another interesting card to try would be Nemesys Keystone (OCG). It special summons itself from your hand when you shuffle back 1 of your banished monsters - and if this card gets banished, you can add this card to your hand. Nemesys Keystone would be AT LEAST a 1 of for sure. Maybe I would trade it for Minerva. Thank you for reading! If you liked this build or just want to comment how to improve this deck, feel free to do it. 04/12/2020
Fun deck

deck_excerpt: Spellbooks 2020. Stick Jowgen with protection, or grind the game to a halt with Mystic Mine.
deck_description: Spellbook deck for April 2020. The goal is to turbo Jowgen the Spiritualist to lock opponents out of special Summoning, equip him with battle protection from Power of the Guardians, and grind games to a halt.  There's a very small package of monsters, with the vast majority of the deck being spells. 3 Magicians' Souls serve as draw power, this deck is pretty good at taking advantage of Spellbooks in the GY, but more importantly, this lets you filter through cards you don't need to dig to your floodgates, which are how you win the game. You have the advantage of naturally wanting to run 1 High Priestess of Prophecy anyways, which you can send off of this and reanimate with Spellbook of Life. High Priestess is a beater with a half-decent removal. It's a good way to pop backrow and it gives you some sort of way to beat over bigger monsters your opponent might normal summon.  There are, of course, 3 Jowgen. Since you can't search this card, the goal is to dig for him. The deck has a lot of filtering and drawing that you can pull off all in one turn, and it's not unusual to see half of your deck in the first turn, meaning you have reasonably good odds of drawing him. His board wipe ability is icing that makes him less dead going second.  We've got a full playset of Blue Boy, Spellbook Magician of Prophecy. This card has the spellbook name, which is relevant for some spellbook effects, and also searches any of your spellbook cards. This can search for Secrets, and secrets can search for this, giving you a lot of deck thinning abilities. It does suck using your normal summon for him, since it locks you out of Jowgen for the turn, but the set up with this card is real and it's an obvious 3 of.  The deck runs several field spells. 2 copies of Mystic Mine are super clutch. Since this deck wins by grinding games to a halt, you have a good go second option when things are protected from Jowgen's field wipe ability. The deck also runs 2 Demise of the Land and 1 Metaverse, so you can drop Mystic Mine on your opponent after they've summoned their second monster to basically end their turn. Those searchers can also find out other field spells, 1 Secret Village of Spellcasters and 1 Grand Spellbook Tower. Secret Village of Spellcasters is super deadly against any deck reliant on spells, such as fusion decks (Shaddolls, HERO) or spell-spam decks (True Draco, Skystriker). You have to decide which floodgate is better, but having extra field spells to use to turn your Mine off is also helpful. The Spellbook Tower is... fine. It recycles Spellbook cards and can let you draw an extra card per turn, which is nice, especially for a grindy deck, but we've got better field spells in most matchups.  We've got a single copy of One Day of Peace and a single Upstart Goblin. One Day of Peace just gives you that one turn to set up, while also increasing the consistency of the deck, which Upstart is solely a small consistency boost. The deck is geared towards drawing 4 each turn with the spellbook combo, so the more card draw I could add to that the more consistently I could stick a Jowgen. The One Day of Peace has seriously impressed me, it really takes the pressure off and lets me use Blue Boy to search.  For spellbooks, We've got 3 Secrets, 3 Knowledge, and 2 Master. If you use Knowledge first and then the Master you can draw 4 - its also possible to use Blue Boy to find Secrets (or vice versa), find Master, search Knowledge, and then draw 2, getting an extra search out of it. This plus Magicians' Souls is the deck's bread and butter.  We've also got 2 copies of Spellbook of Eternity, to recycle our spellbooks (works sort of like a combo extender in the deck) and 3 copies of Spellbook of Fate. Spellbook of Fate banishes 1 card without targeting, which is its primary purpose, but I have on occasion used all 3 of its abilities. Good removal is good - using a quickplay spell to banish without targeting is unreal.  We also have the single copies of Spellbook of Life, which helps resurrect either Jowgen or High Priestess, and one copy of Spellbook of Power, which can be copied with Spellbook of the Master to give a creature 2000 Atk points. This can be crucial to help Jowgen beat over bigger normal summoned monsters while searching twice.  For the last maindeck slot we have 3 Solemn Judgement. Half of your life points is nothing compared to stopping that Lightning Storm or other key effect/creature that would out Jowgen.  In the extra deck we have... some stuff. We have every Super Poly target, including a couple weird ones I felt I had space for (super polying 2 Dark Dragons to make Furious might seem on the face of it weaker than Starving Venom, but I like the flexibility). Then we have 2 Crowley, which can work with Blue Boy and Souls to grab another spellbook. We have one of each Link 2 Knightmare for a spot of extra deck removal, and 1 Verte Anaconda to use Super Poly as extra deck removal.  The Side Deck are a bunch of options to break boards in different matchups, so that going second isn't a death sentence.
