deck_excerpt: A deck that aims to display full power of the Sacred Beasts
deck_description: The main objective of this deck is gathering two Sacred Beasts (Hamon and Raviel), Cerulean Sky Fire, Fallen Paradise and Sacred Beast Awakening on board. Cerulean Sky Fire can  negate the effect of a Spell/Trap card of your opponent. Sacred Beast Awakening's second effect negates all activated effects of your opponent's monsters. Two Sacred Beasts with their total of 8000 attack points are impeccable in terms of offense and defence. Fallen Paradise offers protection and card draw. Gathering all these cards on board can be achieved even in the first turn depending on your starting hand. I aimed to make it consistent as possible. Even partially completing this combo is pretty strong. If all fails, you can resort Armityle the Chaos Phantom to deal a huge blow to your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Eldlich with a Dogmatika Engine, for going first or second
deck_description: *I have updated this list pretty significantly since I initially posted it 3 months prior. The general game-plan is much the same (so the tips below are still valid), but I feel the current list is a bit more appropriate for actual competitive play.   This deck is designed to have a great deal of versatility whether going first or second, although ideally you will go first. Going first your goal is to get Eldlich on the field backed by some backrow, as well as to hopefully get the Dogmatika Saint on the field with Fleur in hand and Punishment set. To accomplish this, Nadir lets you mill the Bastard dragon to search out Saint, who you then normal summon to search Punishment. In the end phase, Bastard triggers to get you Fleur in hand, allowing you to set up multiple disruptions with a single card at no cost. Eldlich is then either searched, milled or summoned off of Black Awakening to make your Golden Land traps live. If you can't get Eldlich out instantly, sitting on Scarlet Sanguine is acceptable since you can just summon Eldlich instantly on your opponent's turn with that anyway. In order to make the best use of Scarlet Sanguine and a Golden Land trap, be sure to chain Scarlet Sanguine to the desired Golden Land (for instance, activate Conquistador then Scarlet, thus making Conquistador's "destroy a face-up card" effect live on resolution). Going first is ideal since the deck is largely trap-based, but thanks to Eldlich's hand effect and the board-breaking utility of Dogmatika, going second is also a solid option for the deck even without siding. For going second, getting Eldlich into your hand is a priority since he sets up your GY while also removing threats. Nadir allows you to both pop a card with N'tss and search out Saint, who searches out Fleur for additional negation and beatdown power. Impermanence is present to serve as a potential disruption during turn 1 and can be replaced with basically any hand trap, but the utility of Impermanence makes it stronger against the plethora of Ash Blossom-resistant decks that now exist. Thanks to Eldlich being a level 10, you also have fairly easy access to notable Rank 10s such as Gustav Max and Liebe to help with OTKing (though be aware Disciple and Saint lock you out of the Extra Deck for the turn after you use them). All in all this deck has incredible resource management, solid disruption and good damage output. Thanks to Eldlich the deck is overall quite resistant to hand traps and board wipes. The Dogmatika engine is a bit more fragile, but offers additional disruption for essentially no cost and helps tremendously with board-breaking and OTKing.

deck_excerpt: Rikka actually works! With the new rank 4 addition really makes the deck flows and super consistent on spewing Teardrop the Rikka Queen + its double o
deck_description: I think Konami plays YGO online simulator too, knowing the fact that this specific rank 4, Strenae the Rikka Queen, works so good in this deck. Anyway, I will explain this deck basic core and strategy. It uses Auroradon-001 combo (idk know which one is busted Halqifibrax or Auroradon) for summoning Strenae and at the same time provides us 2 draws for our 9 Rikka extenders (9 out of 40 cards is kinda big chance): 3 Snowdrop, 3 Mudan, 3 Glamour (Mudan searches Glamour then searches Snowdrop, so basically we need Snowdrop). There is 2 version combo as our starters are mainly on the semi/limited list. First, I will explain the longer version since it is our main goal and better disruption. The starter is Tour Guide/Scorpio. Tour Guide ss Sangan, make Cherubini, use Chrubini dump Naturia Rosewhip, use Sangan add Arboria, ss Arboria make Halqifibrax. The Predap Scorpio one, use Scorpio ss Cobra, use Cobra add Instant Fusion, use Instant Fusion ss tuner make Halqifibrax. From both route use Halqifibrax ss Deskbot 001 (basically just regular Auroradon combo) make Auroradon, ss 3 tokens, use 001 ss itself make Cthugua, use Auroradon tribute 2 tokens ss Mecha Phantom Beast Coltwing, use Coltwing ss 2 tokens, use 001 ss itself again make another Cthugua, make Strenae using 2 Cthugua and draw for 2, use Strenae add Rosewhip from GY. From here Snowdrop can tribute Strenae to ss itself and Rosewhip, then Strenae will trigger and summoning Teardrop with plant material. Then we can synchro summon the lv3 token + Rosewhip (depends on you, since Rosewhip is a Winda for s/t which is kinda good) for Marjoram, use Marjoram add Blessed Winds as disruption and recovery card. The shorter version is basically if we cant Cherubini before Halqifibrax, meaning we wont have access to Rosewhip, so after summoning Snowdrop together with other plant, we use Snowdrop and targeting itself making all plant lv8, resulting us with 2 Teardrops which isnt very bad (maybe). Since the engine takes space and Rikka has summoning restriction, we only play the good Rikka (in my opinion), being the 9 cards I mentioned + Rikka Tranquility (can summon Rikka or Rosewhip from GY, only tribute monster after we used its disruption tho) and Rikka Sheet (kinda bad but searchable, just a bootleg Impermanence or Widow Anchor). The combo lineup: 2 Cobra and 2 Coltwing (we need our combo to succeed, cus if it fails its just zero board presence, also Cobra is a plant target for Snowdrop despite being a once per duel effect), 3 Sangan (1 card Halqifbrax by searching Arboria or handtrap if we have Arboria), 3 Arboria (most of our low level can go to Almiraj, playing 3 Arboria makes them less bricky), Naturia Rosewhip (thank God Konami printed level 3 tuner plant with good effect), Spore (just there, bootleg Glow-up Bulb), and the remaining combo pieces is self explanatory. The rest of main deck is just Crossout package which can function as handtrap or prevention getting handtrapped. The extra deck: Just combo pieces with some breaking board follow-up plays. PK Break Sword (as we can recycle our level 3 engine with Blessed Winds, this one I think is a good choice), Borreload Dragon (non-targeting non-destruction monster removal), Accesscode (easy access from our leftover like Auroradon), Knightmares (deck is tight, you can try switching). Expected end board: Replay: https://bit.ly/2Vora6r (trigger warning: the Eldlich doenst read Accescode, for some reason I entered a room with only 4 cards in starting hand like wtf) Pros: Super consistent with one card starter, fresh first turn board, able to go second thanks to Crossout package and Rikka xyz, great recursion thanks to Marjoram/Blessed winds, easier access to handtrap thanks to 2 draws from Chtugua and Sangan search. Cons: Not very strong board, our recursion source is very fragile (face-up and a backrow too).

deck_excerpt: HERO deck with an Isolde package
deck_description: I took the 52 card version, and cut the fat. It means losing interaction, as well as the Fusion Destiny package, but frees up space in the extra deck and main deck, and increases consistency. You're a blind going second deck, with a bunch of options going first.  I'm going to start in a weird place. HEROES have many appeals, but I think a big one is the ROTAS. In addition to Reinforcement of the Army searching most of your starters, namely Stratos, Solid Soldier, and Liquid Soldier, and sometimes Shadow Mist, but E Emergency Call searches all of these as well as Honest Neos. A Hero Lives is the best of them all, starting you with a Stratos on the field without using a normal summon - your most insane hand is actually these 5 cards.  One thing to mention about A Hero Lives alongside Isolde, is that its a 1 card combo that ends on your choice of Darklaw + Absolute Zero + Sunrise + Mask Change, or Dread Decimator pointing to three Monsters. You can even end on Plasma + Sunrise + 1, off of just this one card. Thanks Isolde! You do this by going Stratos into Stratos, Stratos into Faris, then both Stratos into Isolde. From here there are a lot of lines you can take, and any other extenders or Rotas makes this way more powerful.  3 Stratos serve as the most important starter in your deck. These search any other creature in the deck off of a normal or special summon, which is pretty sweet, and the spell and trap removal is clutch too. 3 Faris is the other starter - this one card basically becomes 3 monsters, which is pretty good. You need 2 Increase and Vyon to search off of Faris.  Shadow Mist is the key searcher in the deck when forced to go first, and you need a way to special her to make Dark Law. The deck has plenty, from both of Solid Soldier's effects to one of Liquid Soldier's effects to Isolde in the extra deck. The searching effect is useful in pulling off OTKs with big boards full of monsters going second as well. It's either or on this card.  Solid Soldier and Liquid Soldier are both super-valuable cards, for different reasons. I'd run 2 Liquid easily if I has space, and I'd run 3 Solid, but the thing is with 5 Rotas you don't really need to. Solid Soldier can use both effects, and alongside Stratos can search Faris, make Isolde, find a monster to discard for Faris, and then use Isolde to summon either another Stratos or Shadow Mist. This is without other extenders. If you have something to discard to Faris, that's when the combo gets crazy - make Cross Crusader the usual way to extend combos as normal, and when you Fusion Summon Sunrise, you can special a monster from your GY, such as a Stratos to search a monster or a Shadow Mist to get a Mask Change. Liquid Soldier is super key as fusion material - the card draw is very valuable, while its summon effect is more icing, that-works well summoning Shadow Mist or Stratos. Sometimes I grab this with Isolde just to use as material, despite having its effects turned off for the turn.  2 Malicious are obligatory, even at 2 it's still pretty essential to the combo. 1 Plasma is the only other Destiny Hero to make the cut in the 40 card version. Shutting off Monster Effects is good, and the deck has ways to increase his mediocre power aplenty. This just adds to the potential going first plays.  Honest Neos is a searchable hand trap that helps with Trinity OTKS. We also have one Evil Hero Adusted Gold and one Dark Calling, to make Malicious Bane when needed.  For fusions Spells, we have 1 Poly to search off of Vyon, 1 Miracle Fusion to search off of Sunrise, 1 aforementioned Dark Calling, and 3 Mask Change.  We needed 5 equip spells to really get reliable summons off of Isolde, especially since sometimes you want to summon Faris off of her. Favorite Hero has become my favourite of them - it can help you pump Trinity up to 10000 ATK points with Honest Neos while also finding your mystic mine. Phoenix Blade is (funnily enough) sometimes useful just to banish E Heroes in you GY for The Shining, and is also just an equip you can get back for low cost. Axe of Fools hard negates effects on cards. This is good Omni-Negate bait at the least, and a nasty thing to put on Apollousa or Winda ect. Horn of the Unicorn and Malevolent Nuzzler aren't amazing, but they put in just enough work getting Dark Law above 3000 Atk points. They are primarily here so that if we see 2 equip spells, so long as one of them is one of these we can put them back into our deck.  Side deck is split into 2 parts - about half deals with backrow decks, while a little over half deals with monster decks (with Evenly Matched overlapping a bit). This lets you cut the Equip spells when you know you aren't going first for whichever interaction is appropriate in your matchup. The reason for the weird split on the spell and trap card removal is that against the Mystic Mine Burn decks it gives them more outs to name, making it harder to get a lock.

deck_excerpt: A very fun, cheap and explosive casual/semi-competitive SUPERHEAVY SAMURAI deck
deck_description: "Superheavy samurai" really is my favorite casual deck to play if you just want to ignore the meta and play against friends. Don't get me wrong, with the right circumstances this deck can be crazy and just OTK even competitive decks. This deck mainly resolves around going second, spamming your superheavy samurai synchro's on the board (wich is very easily done with your main deck monsters) and eventually OTK'ing your opponent with very big beatsticks that can attack over almost anything in battle. Superheavy samurai's don't play spell and trap cards because most effects won't go off if there is a spell/trap card in the graveyard, this is very much one of the biggest weaknesses of the deck and really prevents the deck from playing staple going second cards (like "lightning storm" or "Evenly matched"). The other gimmick is that the big superheavy samurai's can attack while in defense mode and apply their DEF for damage calculation, this is why all the strong cards have a very low ATK but a very big DEF. Here I will quickly go over a few cards and why they are important; "Superheavy Samurai Big Benkei" This big boy is the main deck boss monster and is just an easy to bring out strong beatstick that allows all your samurai's to attack whilein defense mode. Usually you just cheat him out the deck by the effect of "Superheavy Samurai Soulpeacemaker" or by tributing "Superheavy Samurai Big Waraji".   "Superheavy Samurai Thief" "Superheavy Samurai Thief" together with Superheavy Samurai "Big Waraji", "Transporter", "Scales" and "Magnet" all special summon themselves or other samurai's to the field to easily go into your synchro monsters.   "Superheavy Samurai Trumpeter" This card is in my opinion one of the strongest cards in the deck and allow it to function much better than it should be. It is a free special summon if you don't have any spell and trap cards in the GY AND it special summons itself from the GY if it was used for the tribute summon of an Superheavy Samurai monster (mainly "big benkei").   "Superheavy Samurai Battleball" Ball boy is another very strong tuner and really is one of the reasons why the deck is so fun. This card, once per turn, allows you to target any of your opponents monsters that has a level and immediatly synchro summon a Superheavy Samurai synchro monster with the targeted monster and battleball. A great piece of removal that directly benefits you by giving you a strong monster. This card is also the reason why I play "Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju" and "Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju" because if targeted by battleballs effect you can summon "Superheavy Samurai Steam Train King" and "Superheavy Samurai Warlord Susanowo" respectivly.   "Superheavy Samurai Soulpeacemaker" "Soulpeacemaker", "Soulpiercer" and "Soulhorns" all serve as the equip spell cards of the deck. "Soulpeacemaker" special summons a Superheavy Samurai from the deck by tributing the equiped monster,"Soulpiercer" adds a Superheavy Samurai from the deck when sent to the GY and "Soulhorns" allows the equiped monster to attack twice and can special summon itself when equiped. One of your better opening hands is opening "Soulpeacemaker" and "Soulpiercer", normal summoning Soulpiercer, equiping Soulpeacemaker, activating the effect of Soulpeacemaker and tributing Soulpiercer, now you can special summon a Samurai from your deck with peacemakers effect and add a Samurai with piercers effect (these cards depend a little bit on your hand but most of the time is is gonna be an tuner and something else).   "Soulbuster Gauntlet" This single flying arm is a handtrap that doubles the DEF of an battling Superheavy Samurai monster until the end of the turn, this is your biggest OTK enablre and really helps you taking games.   "Sekka's Light" I know I said we can't play spells with Superheavy Samurai's but this card is the only exception. It allows you to draw 2 cards with the negative effect that you can't use any other spells for the rest of the duel, this is no problem since we don't play any other spell cards. You can also banish this card from your GY to shuffle a card from your hand back into the deck and draw a new card. This last effect makes it so that we don't have any spell or traps in the GY and doesn't prevent us from activating he effects of Superheavy Samurai monsters.   Extra deck In the extra deck we mostly play Superheavy Samurai Synchro's (duh) from different levels that help with different hands. The most important are "Superheavy Samurai Steam Train King" (your strongest monster and the one you want to play when trying to OTK) "Superheavy Samurai Stealth Ninja" (probaly the card you will summon very often because you play a lot of easy to bring out lvl5 monsters and lvl2 tuners) and "Superheavy Samurai Ogre Shutendoji" (wich is basically a "Harpie's Feather Duster" on summon and a very strong pick against strong backrow decks)   Side Deck Yea, you can put anything you want in your sidedeck, I just putin a lot of handtraps that can help against certain matchups.   In summary, "Superheavy Samurai" is a very fun, cheap and explosive deck that is a perfect beginners/casual deck BUT can aslo become very strong in a semi- competitive setting with theright circumstances. Any questions or unclear things feel free to ask! (please konami bring scarecrow, musashi and daihachi to the TCG)

deck_excerpt: Aromages with a little bit of an oomph...
deck_description: Just like any Aroma deck, this deck focuses around getting in front of you opponent quickly on life points all the while trying to control the Field with both Aromas (Monsters/Traps) and Synchros. Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram (aka Big Momma Marj) along with Aromaseraphy Jasmine are your key cards and both need to be summoned as quickly as possible in order to move the strategy along. These two cards will allow you to bring out you "Winds" Traps cards, focusing on Blessed Winds, in order to control the field.  The update comes from the addition of Gigaplant, Fallen Angel of Roses, and Rose Bell. With these cards, I believe, the deck is given some need "oomph" and extra deck summoning boost. I believe this to be true because I was always searching form a monster to bring out with my Lonefire after I set up my early game board of Sweet Marjoram and both Jasmines. I also added Relinquished Anima to help the going second game, along with my Thousand-Eyes Restrict (love taking those monsters off my opponents side).  As a side, I included Gizmek Yata in this build in order to take advantage of the second normal summon it provides along with its LP boost, which is always greatly appreciated in an Aroma deck. The second normal summon can be used to help bring out your other plant monsters.  I have tried to build the Main Deck in order to fulfill the requirements for either going first or second in the first game.  This includes the card selections in the Extra deck as well.

deck_excerpt: This deck is evil. Allowing the opponent to do nothing while their LP ticks away.
deck_description: This deck is effectively a deck where when your opponent makes a move you can counter it if necessary, and if you play the percentages right (meaning negating only what is necessary and not everything they do). You will find yourself with weak monsters on the board but your opponent has no cards in play or in their hands so you can just peck them down to O LP and win. The artifacts in this deck are used to take out nasty cards, lockdown your opponent farther, or just to continue knocking down their LP.  notes  if you have the chance early on to take out multifaker you might want to wait until they have their boss monster to take out multifaker and then silquitous or kunquery to return it to the hand (or extra deck) or just negate its affects so you can run over it next turn.  if possible make your big moves during the opponents battle phase so your moves have a lesser chance of being negated.  in general all your moves depend on your opponent so be smart based on the archetype you are up against. If you are an experienced player you can take advantage  of this and read them like the back of your hand and plan for common combo's associated with the archetype

deck_excerpt: Make a decent board on your turn, then make an even better one during your opponent's
deck_description:
Alright, this is a combo deck, so I will just be describing the main combo. You can build several variants of this as well. Check out this video to learn what the "core" of the deck is. You are going to be looking for four cards to know if you have full combo: Necro Slime, Swirl Slime, Lamia, and a monster you can normal summon (preferably Kepler because he searches Gate for you). The deck gets destroyed by hand traps for now sadly, but going first helps this a bit. If you have Kepler start here Otherwise start at step 3.
  1. Normal summon Kepler in the far left zone. Activate his effect to search Gate.
  2. Activate Gate to search whichever of the other three you might be missing. If you have all of them, search what you feel.
  3. Activate Swirl sending Necro from hand. Fusion summons small Ghenghis to the second to left zone.
  4. Activate Swirl in the grave to special summon Lamia from hand.
  5. Ghenghis' effect can trigger to special summon Necro from the grave. (I know it sounds weird, but wait.)
  6. Synchro summon Alexander using lamia and Genghis.
  7. Send Alexander and Necro Slime to make Cross-Sheep.
  8. Now, activate Necro sending small Ghenghis to fusion summon big Gengis to the far-right zone.
  9. Trigger Crosssheep to special summon back Alexander to the middle zone.
  10. Trigger Ghengis to special summon Lamia back.
  11. Link Summon Crystron Halqiifibrax in big Genghis' spot (Needlefiber) using lamia and big Genghis.
  12. Needlefiber's effect can special summon ghost from the deck to the left of alexander
  13. Trigger alexander to summon lamia from the grave.
  14. Synchro summon Crystal Wing using lamia and Alexander
  15. Then normal summon your monster for the turn if you haven't already to the furthest left zone.
  16. Link summon Gilgamesh using Ghost and the normal summoned monster.
    1. Optionally chain-link Ghengis then ghost to send another necro slime to the grave and protect the Gilgamesh trigger.
  17. Ghenghis effect to set your scales with Ragnarok and Apocalypse
  18. Apocalypse pendulum effect to banish ghost and big Genghis.
  19. When ghost is banished, add small Genghis to your grave again.
  20. Now, use Lamia's effect to special summon it to the far left zone from grave by popping Gilgamesh.
  21. Ragnarok's pendulum effect triggers letting you special summon small Genghis to Cross-sheep's other zone.
  22. Lastly, synchro into Siegfried using Apocalypse and lamia.
At this point, the combo ends for your turn. It isn't a powerful board, but you have a spell/trap negate and a monster negate. However, the combo continues on your opponent's turn.
  1. Use your Siegfried negate
  2. Use your Crystal Wing negate (You may decide you do not need to do either of these steps before step 3. Your call)
  3. Needlefiber's effect to "tag-out" for formula synchro (same zone)
  4. Chain its synchro effect and draw effect in either order
  5. Synchro Siegfried and Formula Synchron into Satellite Warrior.
  6. You should be able to destroy 3 cards.
  7. Cross-sheep's effect lets you revive formula again.
  8. Activate Formula Synchron's effect to synchro Borreload Savage Dragon.
  9. Borreload Savage adds Gilgamesh and gives you another negate.
Now we have a pretty nasty board overall. We severely hurt our opponent and may have won the game from this alone. Now, the draw spells and combo extenders may need explanation:
  • Copernicus: let's you send a necro slime to the grave. You do not need it to start in hand if you can still fusion Genghis without using Lamia as material
  • Where arf thou? If you have lamia, it is not as helpful. If you have Kepler, it lets you search the lamia to end
There we have it. As I said, my build is already tailored. You may find another variation like Dave's Artifact engine to be better.

deck_excerpt: Was bored on a rainy day, so I decided to mess around with Weather Painters outside of there typical style. Found the Psychic duo and started Synchro
deck_description: I tried to think outside the box and see if I could do anything with Painters outside of their typical play style. They're infamously slow to get going and don't have much in the way of swarming, so I tried looking for new ways to speed them up a bit.  I tried mashing a mostly typical Painter build up with the Psychic duo for some additional play variety and swarming. Admittedly it is pretty fun and does allow for some nice creativity in a very linear archetype that typically does have that many options early on. Brionic or Coral Dragon for instant spot removal, Barkion for stopping Evenly Matched (by far the biggest bane of Painters in general), making Rank 3's like Leviair or Grampulse, or with a bit more investment Trishula/Quariongandrax for triple banish. Not to mention Trackers's attack boost or Wheelder's pop effect when used as Synchro material.  However the deck is still a massive brick fest. Playing Extravagance is out in this case if you want a varied extra deck, so your best means of draw is purely Magicians' Souls or Upstart Golbin. The duo can also contribute to clogging up your hand if you don't open well, which painters are infamous for.  While it is fun, I definitely would call the standard painter builds "better" as they're a bit more consistent and the variety of Floodgates that they work with over combo pieces can give them a fighting chance against more competitive decks - this build currently doesn't do that nearly as well on a consistent basis.  This list is more of a casual skeleton if anything right now. If anyone would like to take this idea and expand upon it, or has any suggestions for making this build better: I'm all ears.

deck_excerpt: So the Dragma spell Disciple of the Nadir is a 1 card El Shaddoll Winda, THAT IS SPLASHABLE INTO EVERYTHING! Add that with Verte-Dragoon, boom every d
deck_description: Konami never learn, from Knightmare Mermaid, Predaplant Verte Anaconda, and now this. Disciple of the Nadir is 1 card combo for El Shaddoll Winda, combined with Red-Eyes Dragoon, you can literally play anything now and win. The Nadir combo is simple (almost everyone knows it), use Nadir dump Apkallone search Albus Nullius (you can search the other if you have dark fodder in GY), use Apkallone add Shaddoll Ruq discard Albus Nullius, now we have Ruq in hand, and Winda material in GY (Apkallone+Albus Nullius/any dark). But remember, Nadir needs to be used at the last of your plays (even Verte has to resolve before Nadir). End board is Winda and Red-Eyes Dragoon (if you play combo deck it will be better).  The Dragma lineup: 3 Nadir (1 card Winda), 1 Albus Nullius (dark fodder, a super poly with body and non-targeting too), 1 Ecclesia (another target if you already have dark in GY or Nullius is drawn, searches the trap card), 1 Dragma Punishment (destroy monster and another card if you sent N'tss). That's pretty much it, mybe people will figure things more after a while.  Shaddoll lineup: 1 Apkallone (searches Ruq or recycles itself but with discarding), 1 Winda (great floodgate, can even be replaced with any Shaddol depends on the material in GY), 1 Ruq (searchable, fusion using your field and/or GY as material, a non-targeting non-destruction removal too, the monster fusion summoned cant atk directly).  Dark Magician lineup: Standard, but I dont play Magician Navigation as its requirement is kinda hard. I prefer the searchers and draws, but most only 2 because they dont accompolish anything alone (not 1 card combo). Magicians' Souls are the best, free monster, draw, and dumps Dark Magician too. Dark Magic Attack is just searchable Harpies Feather Duster. Apprentice Illusion Magician is our atk booster (from hand/field) for Dragoon and Winda. And lastly, 1 Eternal Soul cus its searchable.  Other support: Eye of Timaeus (I prefer this than Secrets of Dark Magic cus it doesnt eat many resource to fusion summon as Dragoon needs hand as fodder), Magicalized Fusion (can be easy Dragoon or other fusion, cus DM can turn itself into Imduk which is a dragon for easy material), Spellbook engine (1 each, cus hopt and blue boy eats normal summon), Super Poly (yall know the reason), and the rest are just handtraps (can be turned into Almiraj for the Dragma, also Veiler is a spellcaster, can run D.D. Crow too as it is a dark).  Extra deck: Fusion pieces with generic links.  Pros: Winda + Dragoon are legit board, bunch of draws/searches, has handtraps and super poly, possible disruption with Dark Magical Circle too.  Cons: Other combo deck can utilize Dragma-Winda and Verte-Dragoon with more busted board, weak to D.D. Crow or similar cards like that.  Cards to think of: Other Dragma cards (can be put in, but the engine above is enough imo), Other Shaddoll fusion monsters (depends on what attribute you played, as El Shaddoll Construct is still a good card), Allure of Darkness (can be put in, but it banishes dark, it means no fusion material and we only play a few dark), Borreload (can be put in as non-targeting removal, but after testing I never have the resource to summon it).

deck_excerpt: My new and improved Timelord deck...
deck_description:
Well since the release of Ignition Assault, new cards have been added to the deck I created back in November 2019 in the form of a new and improved Timelord Deck that is more versatile and flexible than ever. Just like my old Timelord deck, the strategy has not changed that much, you still finish the match with Gustav Max( given that you choose so) to acquire either a FTK or an OTK.
  • You normal summon a Timelord monster( I recommend Michion)
  • You use Celestial Transformation to special summon another Timelord monster in your hand( I still recommend Michion)
  • After battle, They activate their effects and if you started the battle at 8000 LP, your opponent will have 2000 LP left if the effects aren't negated by other means.
  • And then Xyz summon Gustax Max and end the duel.
  I added a couple of cards that really make this deck more in control than ever. Sales Pitch is a card that makes your add 1 card to your hand when your opponent adds a card to their hand, this makes it much more easier to search out Celestial Transformation to attempt a FTK/OTK or search other essential cards. But you can't use them in the same turn you searched the card out. Lightning Storm is a game changer here, since the deck doesn't use many face up monsters at once, it will be easy to pull off its effects, simply clear out your opponent's backrow so you can avoid "unwanted twists" and proceed to annihilate them. The decks becomes much more difficult to counter it due to its destructive capabilities, and since Timelords can't be destroyed it becomes more depressing to be facing a deck like this with a deck that can't counter Timelords's effects. And of course some decks can get away easily with Timelords by either banishing them, tribute them, or just cancel out their effects and make them sitting ducks, But only a few are capable of doing that. So there it is, my timelord deck, feel free to use it. And as always, let me know what you think about it, Timelords don't get the recognition they deserve because they are "indestructable" which is not true. Timelords need some love too.
The point of the deck is to summon El Shaddoll Winda on one of Cherubini's arrow using Anaconda. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0W4VxnK44Xk
Snowflower

deck_excerpt: This exodia build has 2 win conditions built in with either getting all 5 exodia pieces or making use of Final Countdown! Exodia pieces not there yet?
deck_description: One of my go to decks on ygopro is my Exodia Final Countdown build. Basically, you'll have two win conditions:  Win Condition #1: Draw all 5 Exodia Pieces  Win Condition #2: Use Final Countdown and after 20 turns you auto-win the duel  You'll be making use of Mystic Mine of course to stall while you get your exodia pieces or wait for final countdown(whichever comes first ^_-). Metaverse and Demise of the Land will be your cards for getting Mystic Mine on the field. I have Terraforming(1) in the side deck if needed.  Metaverse(1) is a good trap to use on your opponent's turn and will allow you to search for Mystic Mine and either add it to your hand or activate it on your field. Demise of the Land is in my opinion the best card for getting Mystic Mine on the field. Demise of the Land is a Quick-Play spell. When your opponent special summons a monster(s) you can activate Demise of the Land and it will search out Mystic Mine and auto activate it on the field.  Obviously your opponent will try to kill off your field spell, as such I put in counters to protect it. Solemn Judgment and Dark Bribe. Solemn Judgment makes you pay half your LP but it can negate any Spell/Trap/Monster Effect/Summon and destroy it(this card is great to combo with Hope for Escape for more draw power!). Dark Bribe negates and destroys any activated Spell/Trap from your opponent in exchange for them drawing 1 card. There are other traps that can help(The Huge Revolution is Over and Starlight Road for one), but these work just as well.  Next, we have our draw power. Upstart Goblin(1), One day of Peace(1), Sales Pitch(1), Reckless Greed(3), Pot of Duality(2), Hope for Escape(2) and Legacy of Yata-Garasu(3). Another amazing card to use is Ledger of Legerdemain(2). This card basically banishes the top 3 cards of your deck facedown(you can view them) and on your 3rd Standby Phase after this card's activation, you can add those 3 banished cards to your hand. Basically perfect for getting some guaranteed exodia pieces to ensure your victory.  Besides Mystic Mine, we have other stalls: Spiritual Swords of Revealing Light(2) and Threatening Roar(2). Spiritual Swords allows you pay 1000 LP to negate an attack. This is also good to combo with Hope for Escape for more draw power! You can banish this card and it can prevent your opponent from direct attacking you for the rest of the turn! Threatening Roar prevents your opponent from battling on their turn, just make sure to use it before the Battle Phase!  Finally, we have Trap Trick(2). This trap allows you to banish one copy of a normal trap from your deck and you can set another copy of that banished trap to your field and it can be activated on that turn(even on your opponent's turn).  I have included 12 extra deck monsters in the deck more so to make use of Pot of Extravagance which can banish 3 or 6 cards from your Extra Deck to draw. If you banish 3 you get 1 card, banish 6 and you get 2 cards. I have a Pot of Extravagance in the side deck for you to make use of if you so desire.  I'll close by saying, this is a broken deck. You have 2 win conditions, you can stall your opponent and prevent them from playing yugioh with Mystic Mine and you have a decent amount of draw power for your exodia pieces/to get final countdown! This is a perfect troll deck to use, especially on the weekends!     Good luck and Have fun!

deck_description: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4ynO-7zPhWs

I present... my take on crusadia OTK!
  • This is a blind going 2nd deck, with a going 1st play of making Bagooska + 1 omninegate from Crusadia Equimax.
  • I love the addition of the parallel exceed! I think its perfect for link based strategies like this one (or salad e.g.).
  • I run 2 Crusadia Draco. Of course you can run 3 if you want, but any 2 card combo searches this card.
  • Formud skipper is a new addition, due to parallel exceed. Formud skipper + any Crusadia monster = Bagooska + Crusadia Equimax that can attack all DEFENSE (due to Bagooska) position monsters with 4000 Atk :)
  • In my opinion, 3x Cosmic Cyclone its really nice. You have the room (the monster line up is more or less 15 Crusadia cards and the rest what you play does not matter), thus Cosmic Cyclone seems like a good fit. Decks like Eldlich, Salamangreat, Paleozoic (even decks like Cyber dragon and other) have effects that activate when you destroy their backrow.
  • Monster Reborn, World Legacy Succesion and Living Fossil all serve the same purpose. Any of them + a Crusadia is full combo (thus reducing chance of brick hands).
  • Topologic Bomber Dragon and Topologic Trisbaena are nice, because they can be chain blocked by Crusadia Krawler.
I am curious to hear what you guys think! Cheers, Adriaan

deck_excerpt: A version of cyber dragon who can go first with tru king of all calamity!
deck_description: Hi!  Here a version of the cyber dragon deck with a 2 cards combo for summon true king of all calamity T1 and kill with anaconda and himeratech ramgage dragon T2. The deck can easily go first, and still very strong go second (still cyber dragon!).  With Cyber Dragon Core and machine dup we can make true king of all calamity, one of the big boss of all the game.  Normal Summon Core. Effet add cyber revsystem to the handmachine dup summon 2 cyber dragon from the deck XYZ summon, infinitrack river stromer, effect add anchor drill to the hand. Link Summon platinum gadget. Activate Cyber revsystem reborn cyber dragon. Effect of platinum summon anchor drill from the hand. Effect of anchor drill, heim and cyber dragon became both lvl 9. Special summon calamity.  that's the simpliest combo. Ohterwise, it needs on the board river storm, and 2 monsters. one to summon platinum gadget and one level 5 for xyz summon calamity. Galaxy soldier helps a lot. With a good hand, we can make infinity with calamity. With the perfect hand, we can have cybernetic overflow.  Now i explain my choices for my cards:  3 galaxy soldier because level 5 helps a lot for the combo. Cyber dragon infinity before normal summon cber dragon core is wonderfull. Nova can reborn a lvl 5 (very usefull!)  Only one cyber repair plant because you don't want it in hand when you go first, it's sometimes difficult to activate.  Three overload fusion beacause it's an extender when you go first (lvl 5, and can foolish 2 light machine, herz and core, effect herz and core to the hand!), and we need 3 because i play anaconda and pot of desires.  Two pot of desires only because i play 3 galaxy soldier, 6 lvl 5 in the main deck. don't activate it at the beginning of your turn if you want to summon calamity!  The other cards ratios are classics, You can change the stapples easily according to the meta.  Enjoy!

deck_excerpt: Going first Machina's with a Scrap engine.
deck_description: Going first Machina deck. I'm just going to jump into the choices here.  I have 9 slots dedicated to interaction. I've been testing with D.D. Crow, but I want backrow to send with Scrap Wyvern, so I'm trying Solemn Strike. The deck is seriously lacking effect negation, outside of Apollousa, and while it is not quite a Salamngreat Roar it does a pretty good impression most of the time. Called and Ash should be obvious. We have a lot of stuff to protect with Called, which is often a good offensive card as well, and Ash is just the most consistent hand trap in the format.  Machina Gearframe is one of the deck's main starters, and a combo piece. It's a highly depowered Stratos that is also a union monster. We're a largely main deck focused deck, and this helps find all of our pieces. I'm running 3, because we need to start plays.  Scrap Recycler is our other starter. You can use it to make Link 4s by itself, but it is at its best when summoned off of Platinum Gadget after gearframe. I've sent literally every machine in the deck except itself - there are reasons to. Often, the best monster to send is Machina Fortress. The Scrap engine requires Scrap Golem. We're running 2, because even though it is a total brick, I want to be able to use the Recycler when I see it. O-Lion turns this card into a 1 card Scrap Wyvern, and with Gizmek Orochi you can make Dingirsu pretty easily.  3 Citadel seems pretty obvious. This is simultaneously our main (recurring) boss monster and our main line of interaction. I'm also running 3 Fortress. Fortress is insane, being able so summon it repeatedly is excellent when your hand is full of monsters. Note that you can send monsters whose levels equal over 8, meaning you can pitch O-Lion with fodder to get a free token when you see that brick. 3 Air Raider and Irradiator are necessary - these are combo pieces that help get Fortress on the board while extending your combos. 2 Possesstorage are used in some of the decks combos and make some low-end hands playable. Between it and Irradiator, you have plenty of ways to use Machina Megaform as a searcher, as well as an extra floating effect on fortress (it can also extend combos).  Redeployment is excellent. While the deck doesn't always love pitching cards, it forms the core of so many 2 card combos. Machina Overdrive is also really powerful, particularly going first. If you send it to the GY you get an Upstart Goblin out of it, and it really helps get Citadel in a pinch, which is good, because that's a lot of the deck.  For Xyz monsters in the extra deck, I have 2 Dingirsu for Rank 8s, 1 Dracossack as a rank 7, and all of the Rank 10 Railcannons. Dingirsu is obviously awesome, but has some synergy with an archetype built around destroying itself. Being machine type is clutch in this deck. Dracossack hardly comes up, but it turns some low end boards into boards with an extra Link 4. It turns 2 monsters into 3. It can also help in the grind game, which is good because the deck's plan is grindy. Super Dora is pretty good to make off of Megaform into a 2nd Citadel. The other railcannons help Otk.  For links, we have Apollousa, Borrelsword, and Unchained Abomination. The Unchained Abomination is good against backrow decks, and gives us some spell-speed 2 interaction. It can also be made easily off of Triple Burst Dragon with 1 other monster. Borrelsword is there to OTK, and Apollousa is our one easily accessible way to negate monster effects. Wyvern is an essential combo pieces, while Platinum Gadget is a useful extender out of the extra deck, and good fodder for Wyvern. Qlipohort Genius gives us some generic effect negation that is really solid again Link Monsters, doesn't die to Lightning Storm, and is and Earth Machine monster, which is super relevant in the deck. I:P is used to give protection to your other link monsters, and also lets you combo off into link monsters on your opponent's turn, making Air Raider way stronger.  I like this main deck going first, so the side deck are options to become a go-second deck and OTK. I also threw in the D.D. Crows I pulled from the main. Urgent Schedule is by far the better card to Machina Overdrive when going second, and it seems worth it to switch between them depending on whether you think you're going first or not.

deck_excerpt: This is a non-meta, control, for fun deck. Ok, it won't be an OTK, but with its versatility once you get on the field Toadally Awesome or D.3.S Frog y
deck_description: [ MAIN STRATEGY ] This deck is made so that you can face different types of opponents with its versatily. However, your main objective is to play around Swap Frog. You can normal summon Swap Frog and activate its effect to send to the graveyard (from your hand or deck) one T.A.D.P.O.L.E. or Ronintoadin, or other frogs such as Treeborn Frog so you can use them from the graveyard. If your opponent prevents you from interacting with the graveyard, some magic cards or a Unifrog come to your help. But which card should I send to the graveyard? Well, it depends on the situation, if you have one Des Frog in your hand I would suggest T.A.D.P.O.L.E.. Anyway, after that you can activate the second effect of your Swap Frog and get it in your hand again, so you can special summon it for the second time in your turn (with a "Frog" tribute from your hand) and send another card to the graveyard. If your tribute is another T.A.D.P.O.L.E. and in one turn you manage to send three of them in the graveyard, you only need one Des Frog in your hand so you can get three of them on the field. If you have Polymerization you can fusion summon D.3.S Frog and play around power. Anyway, this is a control deck because the majority of time you won't be able to summon D.3.S Frog. This is not a problem since many cards can counter or destroy it. That's why, if you can early in the game, you can summon Toadally Awesome in one turn (which is very easy to do) and take control of the field with its effects. You only need one "Frog" tribute and you'll never run out of frogs since you can get them back from the graveyard. Toadally Awesome may look like a troll card (especially because of its name lmao) but it can deny every monster effect, magic or trap card when activated and it's not finished yet! If you want you can take control of that magic/trap card and place it on the field! Awesome! [ WHAT IF I DON'T HAVE SWAP FROG? ] Don't give up. If the situation is hard, you can try to play around Dupe Frog or Beelze Frog in combination with Wetlands and Aquarium Stage. Beelze Frog is not so powerful to combo with the rest of your deck alone, but its attack increases for every T.A.D.P.O.L.E. in the graveyard. Not bad! Also, if you need it, you can always count on playing defensive with Aquarium Stage, so that you won't lose Life Points and your frogs won't be destroyed in battle. If you don't have Aquarium Stage you can try by playing Dupe Frog in defense mode (if it goes to the graveyard you can special summon Swap Frog easily) and with trap cards such as Mirror Force to protect your monsters until you get the right cards. This is really common in the first turn if you don't have Swap Frog immediately, so don't give up until your LP goes to zero, you still have a chance! [ WAIT, NO SUBSTITOAD? ] Exactly. You don't need it. I feel like Substitoad is not necessary since all it does you can do it with other monsters such as Dupe Frog or Ronintoadin. I mean, you can add if you want, of course it's a banned card, but since this deck is not an OTK it doesn't really fit well. [ WHAT ABOUT THOSE TRAP CARDS? ] I put one Froggy Forcefield and two Mirror Force cards to show you how it's really up to you. Let's be honest, Mirror Force is stronger that Froggy Forcefield. Why? Well, let's say the enemy can directly attack your Life Points. Froggy Forcefield is completely useless in this case. Moreover, you need to control one "Frog" monster on the field, and since you can play defensive until you get the right card without taking damage, it can be a useless card to draw in most situations. That's why Mirror Force can be more useful in many situations, but some cards can counter it. That's also why I always suggest a different variety of cards, even if the final result if the same, such as Unifrog and Mystical Space Typhoon, even though Unifrog will be a tribute the majority of time. [ WHAT ABOUT MORAY OF GREED? ] I put that in the deck because I wanted to show you a non-banned deck. However, I never play Moray of Greed since I prefer Pot of Greed a lot and I don't care about tournaments. I just play for fun like playing against a friend, which is the main purpose of this deck: for fun. Moreover, Pot of Greed is useful when you only get magic cards and you don't have monsters, a situation where Moray of Greed lacks a lot. It can be also used when you want to find Polymerization faster. So, in the end, unless you are going pvp or you can't use banned cards, go with Pot of Greed. [ DES CROAKING ] This is a useful card to burst damage your opponent especially when you fusion summon D.3.S Frog. You can use it just before Polymerization to clear the field and burst your damage. It will be more efficient if you have 3 Treeborn Frog cards in the graveyard. Remember some frogs are considered "Des Frog" when on the field. [ THANK YOU FOR READING! ] Feel free to use this deck or to modify it according to your personal tastes, which I always recommend! This is my favourite version after trying different ones because I feel like it fits my playstyle and it can be very versatile in most situations. Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Trickstars have been vanish from popular consciousness since Light Stage and Engage were hit, but the engine cards are all there and on this upcoming
deck_description: While by no means i would affirm Trickstars can compete with meta decks, once this format is almost dominated by Adamatia and Eldlich there is always room for control decks to show their grace.  The win condition is take control of the game with hand traps and do your basic Trickstar plays. Summon Candina to add Light Stage, get Lycoris. Remember that Lycoris can dodge negates like veiler allowing your Candina to resolve. Lilybell can be summoned when bounce to hand by lycoris what allows you to push 1600 damage and recycle 2 cards. There's nothing really new that this format promotes to the deck and because we don't have tournaments i'm going to explain how this deck is intended to work against the most played decks of the internet meta.  Against Adamatia you have hand traps like Ash, Veiler and Imperm to slow them down, but while an Ash on Granite can stop their turn sometimes normally it won't happen that way. Your strong cards here are Crackdown and Reincarnation. Take their rocks before they can summon more monsters can end the turn. Banishing the hole hand can hurt a lot because the deck need a lot of engine cards in multiple copies. Going first you can Called by the Grave Block Dragon to avoid them to have follow up but is the type of card you will side out once it doesn't mean a threat to your opponent first turn. You can side in Sphere Mode, Nibiru and Summon limit to have a much more solid chance to win the second game. This logic apply to all the combo decks that the new master rule made possible.  When playing against Eldlich your goal is to banish all 3 golden lords. Either with Call by the Grave or Reincarnation. Enemy Controler and Crackdown are really good to bait your opponent's traps and take the Golden Lord so that his traps second effects are dead. Prohibition and Evenly Matched can very much win the game, or at least change for a Judgment or a Golden Land Forever! which puts you in an advantageous  position once this deck can burn for 4000 much quicker and he will not be able to negate your cards.  The Cyber Dragon 1 card engine is really good to out your opponent's Apollousa and gives you a 2400 body. It doesn't start a chain so that's nothing to negate. Honest can be unfortunate sometimes but you will run out of resources earlier so you need a bit of extra damage to push for game faster. Scapegoat, Bouquet and Enemy Controller are also there to help you finishing the game.  Finally some people run Extravagance over Desires, but i don't think that's a good idea. You have a 50% chance of drawing a starter turn 1 while you have a 0.1% of banishing all of them with desires and a 2.9% chance of banishing all Lycoris or all Reincarnation. While Extravagance will 100% banish your Extra Deck cards so you can't rely on them when needed. The chance of banishing an important piece to the Scapegoat Combo is 90%. The Extra Deck cards are indeed not that much used but don't think they are not important. Banish Chimeratech and your Cyber Dragon is dead, Banish Borreload or Ningirsu and you don't have an out to certain cards. There are a lot of Specific cards like Trisbanea that you would just use against backrow decks, but it doesn't mean they are not important.  When building a control deck that's based on a popular engine i feel like there's no sense on explaining how the engine works. It has been working the same way for years. The most important decisions are the non engine cards and how they relate to the new meta game. So, i don't recommend using Chain Summoning, this is not an FTK deck and that card is just a brick in most cases. I'm not using Solemns because Lightning Storm is really popular this format and you don't want to set a lot of backrow. Almost all our backrow is chainable and you can go second and rely on hand traps dodging Storm. Even Going First Called by the Grave can negate Ash or other hand traps that bothers you. The deck also doesn't have a lot of cards on the field, so Evenly Matched doesn't do a lot against it.  Overall, I think it's a really fun deck to play and it can perform better than people are expecting because they have no cards on side deck to counter your plays.

deck_description: A combo deck designed go plus with negates by tributing your own monsters. If you are interested in knowing why these specific tech cards were chosen or how the strategy works in practice, feel free to watch the video posted! This deck is part of a YouTube series called TRULY TRASH? - videos based around trash tier Yu-Gi-Oh! archetypes. Each video contains replays, analyses, and deck techs as well as the reasoning behind choosing such! deck_excerpt: Utilize the consistent Marincess link climbing engine with additional WATER extenders to unlock Synchro and XYZ summoning for your Marincess strategy!
deck_description:
Utilize the consistent Marincess link climbing engine with additional WATER extenders to unlock Synchro and XYZ summoning for your Marincess strategy! Pros:
  • Still has normal access to the consistent Marincess link climbing engine, able to end on Great Bubble Reef or Wonder Heart with 3 equips in one turn with most hands.
  • The deck only locks into WATER, thus you have access to many great WATER extenders such as Aqua Spirit, Crusadia Arboria, Fishborg Launcher, Crystron Halqifibrax, and more!
  • Capability to generate tons of card advantage due to the self recycling nature of Marincess and the draw power of Great Bubble Reef. As long as you don't get OTK'd, you can still rebuild a broken board!
  • Decent protection with the ability to easily make a towers-like boss monster, and good disruption with Marincess Wave, basically an archetype impermanence.
  • Strong recent WATER synchro releases that can easily be gone into, such as Adamancipator Risen - Dragite and Deep Sea Princess Prima Donna.
  • Many possible combo paths to get into Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier.
  • Turns out some of the best XYZs are WATER too, such as Abyss Dweller. The Bahamut Shark + Toad package is a good option too.
Cons:
  • Fragile deck, can play around a couple disruptions with the right hand but still easily stopped.
  • Relies heavily on managing your Link arrows, place things in the wrong zones and your combos can be cut short.
  • Gets absolutely dumpstered by Nibiru, as the standard Marincess link climb puts you way above the Nibiru threshold.
  • Relies heavily on the field spell. It's easily searched with Sea Angel and also easily retrieved when destroyed, but it'll be under fire quite a bit and hard to get back when banished (but not impossible due to Deep Sea Princess Prima Donna).
  • Has a hard time against an established unbreakable board going second, as the true extensions of the Marincess board going into Synchros and such are usually only doable on your second turn unless your hand is just that good.
Synergies to keep in mind:
  • Great Bubble Reef gets really big when you banish a lot of things. Many monsters in this deck banish as part of a cost, effect, or condition. Aqua Spirit and Scrypton banish a target to summon themselves, Mandarin and Sea Archiver banish themselves upon leaving the field after their extension, etc. Also, banishing your opponent's cards counts too, hence Trishula immediately buffs Great Bubble Reef by up to 1800 ATK.
  • If you use backrow removal in your deck, use Cosmic Cyclone. Not because banishing spells and traps makes them harder to get back, but because it gives you higher chances of Deep Sea Princess Prima Donna's ability to summon from the deck to be live.
  • Deep Sea Princess Prima Donna can get back something you banished with Pot of Desires upon leaving the field, at least according to how EDOPRO rules it.
KEEP IN MIND: This version of the deck focuses on the combos of the deck. In order to make it more competitive and replacing some of the cards with hand traps and the like, replace copies of extenders that are heavily reliant on having another resource to extend off of, such as Pascalus, Aqua Spirit, etc. Good things to sub in are Called by the Grave, Infinite Impermanence, and your favorite hand traps.

deck_excerpt: An Orcust-like variant of Megalith that actually does something.
deck_description: I wanted to turn Megaliths into Ritual Orcusts, but because we don't have a searchable counter trap (yet), we need to run more than our fair share. The main combo I wished to achieve was set 2 pass, with portal and a properly-summoned Phul in grave, and to do so, all we need is a Hagith summon. Scrapping bad cards, we're left with 12 main-deck archetype cards, not running any more megaliths than absolutely necessary to facilitate the combo every time. The Godo engine with 2 Glove and Onomatopoeia alongside 3 Magileine and 1 Petingcessoeur allows us to summon Gallant Granite with 80% of hands. A small Dragma package allows us to extend upon these plays, getting a negate, a search and/or a pop depending on what you send.  We pass to our opponent, watch them develop their monsters, using traps if under dark ruler, or using Phul to summon Bethor to pop, and depending on how broken your hand is, I:P'ing into either Apollousa or Unicorn for further disruption. Once they've failed to build a formidable board, we summon out father Phaleg and hit face for lethal.

  1. The best way to make a combo is if you have the recommended cards: Yosen Training Grounds, Fire Princess, Dark Room of Nightmare, Spring of rebirth, and another yosen or spirit monsters that can return to either your or the opponents hand.
  2. Next, when your monsters that are return to your hand, you would be really vulnerable to attacks so that is why mirror force and other protection cards are in there (it is okay if you had more protection)
That is basically the strategy: Gain Life Points and while you gain life points,  your opponent is dealt damage while your life points are climbing. This is my first deck I have built and published here

deck_excerpt: Use fusion and and quick play spells to adapt and overcome to whatever your opponent throws at you.
deck_description: Fairly self explanatory HERO deck. Fuse your HEROes into the one that's going to save the day and strike down the villain. The wide range of monster effects and spells means you can constantly mix up and change strategies. Opponent got a high powered monster beating you down? Not to worry, with your wide range of HEROes, use Super Polymerization to take their monster and fuse it into your own powerful warrior to beat them down. You also have the Masked HEROes ready to swap in to bring in their own effects. Don't forget your change and super poly cards are all quick play, meaning you can summon numerous monsters at almost any phase of the game! Try it out and find what combinations work well for you, a couple recommendations: Summon Elemental HERO Absolute Zero, and then play Mask Change to summon Masked HERO Acid to completely wipe your opponents field. Use a light monster to summon Elemental HERO Sunrise, then play Miracle Fusion to summon Elemental HERO The Shining, giving you two  monsters on the field, which each get a boos from Sunrise, and The Shining gets a further ATK boost from your banished monsters. If that wasn't enough, when the Shining is destroyed you can add the cards you banished back to your hand. If your opponent has summoned numerous monsters, fusion summon Vision HERO Trinity. Trinity is unable to attack directly but can make up to three attacks on monsters and on the turn its summoned his attack doubles to 5000. Combine this with Elemental HERO Honest Neos to raise up to 7500, then if you have The Warrior Returning Alive you can repeat the process to boost up to 10000, and attack for massive damage.

I personally liked prediction princess at first and wanted to run them with cyber angels but that didn't work as good as i hoped because i realized prediction princesses have been power creeped like a lot, which is why i thought "hey, the way it looks the only way to run this is with shaddolls" so then i realized people already was playing prediction shaddolls recently and i got bummed about it, now i know i'm not entitled to a deck but i think it makes my deck "less original" so i'm still bummed about it. i want to think i made it less prone to brick but you can still get a few bad hands, so good luck fighting meta decks that can clean your field on their first turn because yeah, that doesn't get any less frustrating and most of the time you're going to be kinda defenseless against that, but if you can get it running you can probably keep fighting for a good while.

deck_excerpt: Make Dingirsu, Crystal Wing, 3 Apollousa, and Utopic Future Dragon.
deck_description: Spit out half your deck with Lightsworns then use the recurring zombies to get multiple monsters on board. Double Plaguespreader to for Halquifibrax. Always, Always make Chaos Ruler first because he dumps 4 and gets a search that can be utilized with Popperup. Popperup can get cards out of hand and Uni-Zombie is a great opener. Best normal summon is probably Lumina since she can discard herself and revive herself while also setting up the graveyard. Mezuki is always graveyard fodder. Small Block Dragon engine to allow for going into Dingirsu to give the negations some protection. Long combos but it's not like a specific line because of Lightsworns so it's more like just discard and see what happens. Plaguespreader plus any level-4 for a charge warrior which is a free draw then that gives you an easy Crystal Wing. This deck has next to no recursion, loses to Nibiru, Ash Blossom, and heavy negate boards so feel free to use the side deck for cards like Dark Ruler No More and Super Poly. Have fun spitting out heavy negations. Even with brick hands during my testing the worst board I came out with a  3 counter Apollousa so there's defenitely choke points but the deck is very very conistent due to Block Dragon's existance. Side Deck is all going second cards and anti Hand Traps. Revival Golem is just Block Dragon food and potentially a free summon off of any Lightsworn Card or could even be used with Plaguespreader if you have no cards in hand.  I am very open to suggestions and differences to the extra deck. I personally think it's tight but the only cards that aren't preforming are Curious and Saryuja, while Saryuja has gotten me to special summon Zombie Master for more extension.

deck_excerpt: One of the reason why Toadally Awesome got limited, Deadreef the Ephemeral Fish can easily dump Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth and reviving it w
deck_description: Fish will be viable once Rise of the Duelists card hits the market (TCG is still missing Number F0: Utopic Future Dragon tho). Combo is kinda consistent, because its only Deadreef+any lv4. So we play 3 Deadreef (dumps "big fish"), 3 Beautunaful Princess + 1 One for One, 2-3 Summoner Monk (searches Deadreef and fulfilling the combo but needs spell in hand), therefore we play roughly 9 Deadreef and the rest is just lv4 water extender. The combo is we summon Dugares (on extra zone) with Deadreef (after sending big fish) + any lv4, use Dugares revive big fish, use big fish discard 1, ss 4 fishes from deck (preferably every copy of Deadreef in our deck as it provides us draw from GY), make Bahamut Shark ss Toadally, make Gallant Granite search Adaman Researcher (or Nibiru if we draw Researcher), ss Researcher, make F0 with Gallant + Bahamut, make Halqifibrax with Researcher + Dugares, ss O-Lion, make Crocodragon with O-Lion + big fish, use Crocodragon draw and chain O-Lion ss lv3 wind machine token. Now you can use Deadreef draw from GY, making us draw 2 in total from our combo. On opponent's main phase, we can banish Halqifibrax for any synchro tuner (can be anything, depends on you) while having the lv3 wind machine token as the non-tuner for synchro summoning during your opponent's turn. Some synchro tuner can be used during your opponent's battle phase (like Crystron Quandax). Expected board: Replay: https://bit.ly/3bwIc9o (you can replace Dragite with any synchro tuner play) Pros: Good consistency, multiple negations and disruptions, able to run Deepsea Minstrel to see and snipe opponent's hand, can run bunch of handtraps. Cons: 2 cards combo, follow up play aint too good, Dugares effect skips your next main phase 1, Beautunaful Princess misses timing if summoned with White Mirror. Cards to think of: Silent Angler (good lv4 water extender but conflicts with Researcher), other sharks (most of it aint too good), other synchro plays (I put the example on side deck).

deck_excerpt: Tier - 1 Deck. It is Consistent and Durable against the Meta.
deck_description: This is a version of Salads (Salamangreats) that doesn’t have Apollousa for those that can’t afford to buy a card(s) that expensive. This deck is very consistent and it’s durability is crazy good.  The main strategy is to set up a defensive board first turn to help with disrupting or going for the OTK on your next turn. If you’re going Second, You can play still play defensive, still go for the OTK, or remove their board and have some offense but not an OTK.     Depending on who you are facing and/or what you have in your hand determines what 1 of 3 ways that you can will set up your board. Regardless of either, always try to get the Rage or Roar if You did not draw into them.  1) Get Bagooska our in defense mode. Yes this will effect you as well, but you can easily work around it because most of your Salad monsters effects activate in grave and once you have your Links, you don’t have to worry  2) Bring our Abyss Dweller to disrupt your opponent from activating effects from grave.  3) Bring our Transcode Talker and co-link with Wolf. If you send Roar or Rage to grave, don’t Reincarnate Wolf until you bring him back out with Transcode Talker. If you are getting Roar, use Wolfs effect not Roar’s so that it doesn’t get banished yet. I would only use Roar’s effect if I reincarnate a different Salad Link or if I have both Rage and Roar in grave. Which in that case, get Rage with Wolf’s effect and then Roar via reincarnation.  I have Knightmare Unicorn for those monsters that can’t be destroyed by battle/card effects.  As for the side deck, use what you have that is good against the meta. I’m gonna place what I am able to use.  I don’t use Knightmare Phoenix or Hiita because I found myself barely going into them. Sometimes it wasn’t helpful or it would’ve disruptive to me to bring them out, so I took them out and don’t regret it.

deck_excerpt: This is an invoked kaiju deck that is based on fusion summoning. The spellbook engine improves the consistency of the deck and the kaijus can eliminat
deck_description: This is an invoked kaiju deck that is based on fusion summoning. The spellbook engine improves the consistency of the deck and the kaijus can eliminate big threats on the board. Mystic mine is used here to stall when you don't have a good play and handtraps to control the board. There can only be one is a useful trap against many matchups like pure Blue Eyes or Dark magician.  My rating:  Attack: 3/5  Defense: 5/5  Consistency: 4/5  Strong Against: Decks with only 1 or 2 types, Gren Maju, Dark Magician  Weak Against: Virus Control, Nekroz  Small combos:  Normal summon Aleister (or use Magical Meltdown to search him)  Activate his effect, get an invocation into the hand  Link Aleister into Almiraj  Link Almiraj into Gardna  Fusion summon Purgatrio with Aleister and Almiraj in the GY, banishing them  Add Aleister from the banished zone to hand by shuffling invocation into deck  Spellbook combo:  Activate Spellbook of secrets, bring blue boy into hand  Normal summon blue boy, bring Spellbook of knowledge into hand  Send blue boy to the GY with Spellbook of knowledge's effect and draw 2 cards     This is a really fun deck if you play it correctly. Have fun!

deck_excerpt: My last, and most successful, attempt to break Genex synchro.
deck_description: After 5 or 6 decks, I decided to give them one last try by focusing entirely on there main gimmick, searching by normal summons. As result this deck doesn't include usual Genex staples like Genex Blastfan, Genex Ally Duradark, or allure of darkness. However, the deck does function way better than other Genex decks despite this.  So the main focus of this deck is to build a board with a few negates, and the way it achieves this is through double summon and the symphonic warrior engine to give you an extra normal summon and get more monsters on the field while maintaining a good had advantage, such as through searching Genex monsters with Genex monsters and T.G. hyper librarian. Things to keep in mind about this deck is that it's combos end on Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon almost all the time, it fills up the board fast, and it summons Mecha phantom beast O-lion a lot, so be careful when you use Mecha Phantom Beast O-lion's token effect because using it early may mess up your plays.  You can use Genex Recycled to copy a name of a Genex monster in the grave, preferably Genex turbo, then use Machine Duplication to summon two of those monsters from the deck, which if you copied Genex turbo, you can instantly make Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier.  Genex power planner is there only if you have an additional normal summon, to easily synchro summon Martial Metal Marcher with phantom beast O-lion, or if you brick and have no combo starters in your hand, which happens on occasions, but not nearly as often as one might think.  Genex Turbo can search out Genex Oracle which can then special summon itself, allowing you to link summon Crystron Halqifibrax.  Genex Ally Birdman can allow you to get an extra tuner on the field and allow you to re-use the effects of Genex Turbo, Undine, and Power Planner, increasing hand advantage, especially if you have an additional normal summon sense Genex monsters don't have hard once per turn effects.  And to get the most out of Genex Undine if you can only normal summon once, follow this guide: Normal summon it to send Crystron Phoenix to the grave and search for Genex controller. Banish Crystron Pheonix to summon a token and special summon link spider with it, then use link spider's effect to summon Genex Controller and link summon Crystron Halqifibrax to special summon a tuner. You can further extend this combo by special summoning Mecha phantom beast O-lion with Halqifibrax to synchro summon Accel Synchron and special summon a token, then send Jet Synchron to the grave to decrease it's level by 1 and synchro summon F.A. dawn dragster. then you can summon Jet Synchron and link summon for Auroradon, tribute one of its tokens and itself to summon another phantom beast O-lion from the deck, and then synchro summon Borreload Savage Dragon and equip Auroradon for a total of two negates on the field and a 4050 beater.  Pot of Avarice is probably the deck's only form of recovery, so use it wisely.  The side deck is pretty open, but most of the cards in there are for going second sense this deck dies off of a single negate, so feel free to add cards you feel are better suited for it.

deck_excerpt: Let's face it, most of us have played with Legos at one point: now, you can do it in Yugioh!
deck_description:
Lego Adamancipators focuses on the Board Building and recursion potential of Earth Monsters, using Block Golem and all Earth Main Deck monsters (besides Nibiru, but that's a hand-trap anyway) to create card advantage through the Excavation mechanic.
  1. Alongside the obvious triple copies of each Adamancipator Tuner, I use half the GoGoGo engine, Gigas and Dwarf, for their natural ability to recur themselves from the grave when combined, coupled with their rank 4 status to not only make a Gallant Granite, but also pitch to Doki Doki to cheat Analyzer from the Deck. They can also be used to make Abyss Dweller, which can come in very handly against certain decks such as Eldlich.
  2. I use two Block Dragon, because it's a strong card to open with, possibly getting all 3 Tuners from the deck (though most often, grabbing Seeker and Researcher, plus a Gigantes to extend), and running two takes into account a Called By or DD Crow, allowing a possible Union Carrier or Gallant to fetch the second if it fails.
  3. Another staple, Gigantes is just a very good card for extending, or getting a second level 4 to make Gallant Granite and begin my plays, but it's also a brick on Excavation, so I only run 2.
  4. 2 Koa'ki Meiru Guardians allow for an early protection from Nibiru, if they're excavated. I'm playing around with running 3, but deck space is relatively tight, given how important it is to open with a Tuner.
  5. Block Golem, my own little pet tech and one of the focuses of the deck, turns an excavation from a +1 into a +2, which is absolutely incredible, turns Adamancipator Signs into a "bring back 2 monsters from your grave", and matches the Tuners for a +1 when cheated out by Doki Doki: even better, if both Gigas and Dwarf are in the grave, by resurrecting only one of them and another monster, the other can also be brought out by it's effect, becoming a +3, so I run 3, to maximize the chance of excavating it. The card does come with a caveat, however: in order to use Block Golem's effect, all monsters in the grave MUST be Earth Attribute. Because of this, zone placement becomes important, as I don't want to send any of my Link Monsters to the grave until I'm ready to commit to my final board, or have enough resources that Block Golem is no longer needed. With the current build, that isn't a terribly difficult thing to pull off, but it's something I always need to keep in mind while starting a combo.
  6. Barrier Statue of the Drought is part of an interesting combo, which can not only be excavated, but also be searched at the end on a combo by resurrecting an unused Tuner with Signs (usually a Researcher or Seeker that Halqifibrax brought out, and couldn't activate). The best example of this is a line of play I shoot for when I've opened an Adamancipator Signs, Researcher, and one other rock monster (Seeker also works here, if you open a Doki Doki along with it to bring Analyzer out.) At minimum, by starting with the Rock Monster, then specialing Researcher, so long as I hit the excavation, I'll have 3 rock monsters on the field. I can link Researcher and one of them off to create Halqifibrax, summoning Seeker from the deck (or Researcher, if Seeker was first), then link Seeker and the normaled monster into I:P, and link those two into Mekk Knight Crusadia Avramax, who now cannot be destroyed by card effects because it was link summoned with I:P Masquerena. Finally, I use Signs to bring back Seeker (or Researcher), putting Barrier on top, and excavate Barrier to the field. This line of play locks the opponent into only Special Summoning Earth Monsters, and they can't just normal summon and attack the barrier to lift that restriction, because Avramax protects it, and Avramax cannot be outed by any Kaiju except Kumonga (who is not normally played), so long as Barrier is on the field. This board can end on far more, as well, as that was considering the bare minimum of play: with skillful and careful play, one can viably create a board of Avramax, Block Dragon, Dragite/Savage (Dragite only if you think your opponent may have a Raigeki effect, so that your spell/trap negate is protected by Block Dragon), Barrier Statue of the Drought, and an Apollousa. Given, one or more of those may be missing, depending on excavations and the strength of the opening hand, but I've managed to assemble that board several times.
  7. 3 Cosmic Cyclone, because in the situation that I go second, I don't like scooping to Zombie World/Rivalry, Summon Limit, There Can Only Be One, etc.
  8. Double Summon is another contentious tech, and one I haven't fully committed to as of yet. I only run two, at the moment, because I never want to see two of them, and many times, the card will not be needed: however, when I do open it, it can be a life saver after my opponent stops my starter, and can also unbrick hands that completely lack a Doki Doki or Tuner, because most of those hands are mostly level 4 Rocks, which I can summon two of the make a Gallant Granite, search Block Dragon, then banish two in my hand and the one that was dumped into the grave for Granite to summon Block Dragon. Then, I link the two off for I:P, grabbing Researcher, Seeker, and any level 4 I'm fine with banishing in order to bring Block Dragon back out, banishing Gallant, its other material, and the level 4 in my hand, so that Researcher can special herself, followed by Seeker, because Researcher is out. Then, it's into the combo, with a hand that had effectively 0 combo pieces.
  9. Yes, I will still effectively lose to Dark Ruler No More, but that's just how Adamancipator is.
  10. Finally, just getting into a small bit of math, the deck runs 15 excavation targets. Given that 12 of those cards- all of them except Doki Doki- are suboptimal to open with, it's a decent ratio, at a soft 30% of the deck, probability putting it at 1.5, or 1-2 cards average per opening hand. Meanwhile, using that number, after taking 5 cards for the opening hand, there'll be a roughly 38.6% chance to excavate one of those monsters on my first excavation (13.5/35), running roughly 1.93 excavatable monsters per excavation, a very balanced ratio that, most times, will allow me a choice between two of them. So far, this ratio has kept my hands and excavations relatively consistent, but it's still an ongoing process to perfect it.

This is a budget friendly version of the Yosenju Pendulum Deck, it works just fine, but if you you have more money there are cards in the deck that you should definitely change like instead of three Pot of duality, play Pot of extravagance and swap out the two Called by the Grave for two additional copies of Pot of desires.  Additional you should play with a convertible Side deck because people will make you go first if they know what you are playing so put some Solemn Jugment's and Strike's as well as Torrential Tribute's and Summon Limit's or Gozen Matches.  Another thing that you can do is swap out the one Yosenju Izna and the two Yosenju Secret Move for three copies of Superpolymerization and obviously put some targets for it in the Extra Deck like Starving Venom Fusion Dragon, Mudragon of the Swamp, World Chalice Guardragon Almarduke and Diplexer Chimera.
