deck_excerpt: A Cyber Dragon deck, good going first or second, can OTK easily and control the board.
deck_description: Hi guys! Just wanted to propose a Cyber Dragon deck more "Meta Friendly", not only a pure Second Turn FTK, because going first, nowadays, can be a better option if you can control the board.   It keeps its power to OTK but with just more control.   If you're going first: Try to discard ASAP Herz, so you can get a Cyber Dragon. You can use galaxy soldier most of the time (prior) or Nachster (but be carefull with this one cause you won't be able to summon predaplant verte nor pleiades). Summon Nova, bring back cyber dragon, try to get a third lvl 5 on the board (Nachster for exemple, when you special summon it, you can special summon a cyber dragon from GY). If you're T1 with overload fusion, get Rampage Dragon, use its effect to send Turtle to the GY along with Herz if you hadn't already, and then summon Pleiades with Cyber Dragon + Rampage dragon. If you haven't overload, summon predaplant before using Herz first effect (which you should not use T1) or Nachster effect, and summon Rampage Dragon last, sending Turtle. Try to get Cyber Repair Plant fast, so you can get another Light Monster (most of the time Galaxy Soldier, or whatever monster your hand is lacking, like Nachster or Cyber Dragon or even Herz for discard effect). If you haven't any Cyber Dragon monster in the GY, summon Almiraj to send one. This last one, if you have no other option, can be kept on board to protect one of your monster on opponent's turn, but it's not a priority move. If you have a Core in hand, it will be your prior normal summon, to get Revsystem or Emergency or Repair Plant.   Next, it's all about surviving the opponent's first turn without loosing too much. HT like Ghost and Ogre can help, Infinity, Pleiades, and you can skip the Battle Phase with Turtle in the GY.   Next, try to summon another Rampage Dragon by any means (along with Sieger), so you can:   -clean the opponent's Spell/Trap board. -Sieger's effect on it -Attack three times with 4200 ATK.   Don't forget to use infinity to get rid of an opponent monster. You can use Pleiades too, to clean up a bit. Don't forget Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon, you don't need any Polymerization to summon him, and you can tribute an ennemy link monster (most of the time). Use Fortress when you're using Jizukiru if you can't do anything else (but normally, Infinity's here). Here are two replays showing a "good" going first match:   https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wyTuAC276Q0 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uJI0M5HT5C4&feature=youtu.be Going second, is the same as T3 before, Infinity to clean, Rampage Dragon to clean and burst, Sieger to help doing this. Here are three more videos showing a FTK (almost for one, he surrended at T3 :p) going second.   https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jx7x3khr5pM&feature=youtu.be https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hry65VGHXMc&feature=youtu.be (this one is against a player) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KB5i9QS_ajo&feature=youtu.be (against evil eye, he surrended :p)   Q/A: -Why three Galaxy Soldiers? Cause it increases the prob to draw it at the start, and the third one isn't a dead weight. -Why no Super Polymerization: Because i'm focusing on going first here, so this card isn't really helpfull, and i don't have monsters using this (i have overload and predaplant, it's enough) -Why no Ash and Blossom, and putting Ghost Ogre? I know that Blossom is better, but you can't discard it (fie monster), Ghost Ogre is a Light one so it can be used in multiple ways. -Why Reasoning? Well, this card is a gamble, but the deck uses a wide variety of monsters with differents lvl: they can all be usefull on board, and the chances that the opponent (especially going first) picks the good one are really low.   Try not to use it first, as it can discard usefull spells, but you have at least 2 copies of each, so it shouldn't be a problem.     So i hope you enjoyed this presentation, and that you'l enjoy this deck online, if you have any feedback, feel free to comment :)   Have Fun!   Updated 25/04/2020: -1 overload, + 1 Super Pol (TCG only), -1 revsystem, +1 evenly matched, -1 cyber eternity, - 1 auroradon, +1 earth golem, +1 mudragon,
3 quasar

deck_name: franksayngo's Pet Rocks|Adamancipator May MR5 UPDATED
deck_excerpt: This deck is extremely consistent, can survive multiple disruptions, and can summon 4-5 Negates/Disruptions in 1 turn. Have fun!
deck_description:
I have 2 main boards - Goal 1:
  1. End Turn 1 on Crystron Needlefiber/Halquifibrax, Borreload Savage Dragon, One LV2 Tuner monster, and either Block Dragon or Apoullousa
  2. During my opponent's main phase, I chain Needlefiber to synchro summon Formula Synchron.
  3. Wait for opponent to resolve an effect I can chain off of then activate Formula Synchron to synchro summon Red Hot Dragon Archfiend King Calamity.Activate Red Hot Dragon Archfiend King Calamity's effect off the synchro summon to lock them out of all card effects. <-- Resolving this effect is almost guaranteed a free win.(Make sure no other effect is resolving last or else RHDA King Calamity's effect won't trigger on Synchro Summon)
  4. Opponent has no choice but to to end turn.
  5. During Turn 3 (My 2nd Turn), I usually use Block Dragon + 1 other monster besides RHDA King Calamity as Link material for any Link Monster (Union Carrier or I:P Masquerena) at the the time and then resolve in the gy to fill my hand with combo pieces.
  6. I usually get out Union Carrier + Adamancipator Risen - Dragite/Borrelsword Dragon
  7. Activate Union Carrier to equip RHDA King Calamity with Dragon Buster Destruction Sword
  8. BP then attack with all monsters
Goal 2:
  1. 1st Turn end will usually with as many disruption/negation monsters as possible. Usually something like Apollousa + Borreload Savage Dragon and/or Adamancipator Risen - Dragite + Herald of the Arc Light/Koa'ki Meiru Guardian + Abyss Dweller + Block Dragon
  2. Disruption the hell out of my opponent during their turn.
  3. Turn 3 I send Block Dragon to resolve the GY effect if needed.
  4. BP and Attack
  Those 2 are my Main Goals. If I lose the dice roll and go 2nd, here is a video showing off a decent example of how the deck can survive multiple disruptions while still getting a decent board   I tested this deck a ton of times to make sure its consistent no matter what hand it is. Of course bricks are bound to happen no matter what but very very rarely. Enjoy it while it still has Block Dragon.       5/5/2020 Edit: Decided to add Avramax and test it out. Its definitely an amazing card to tech in as protection. Here are some videos showing off the board with Apoullousa + Avramax + Borreload Savage Dragon equipped w/ Dragon Buster Destruction Sword Combo Example: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qkt_hXD-qHQ In a duo match: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xdJ7dgfic8g

deck_name: BLACKWING APEX INFINITY 2020 (POST APRIL BANNED LIST)
deck_description: The main strategy is very simple: you swarm the field with dark winged beast monsters in order to being able to summon:  Step 1: Wise strix and the you special summon (usually Zephyros the elite) from you deck  Step 2: then you special summon Raidraptor Force strix using Zephyros the elite, then detach Zephyros to use the effect of Force strix which makes you add to your hand from you deck a level 4 Dark Winged Beast monster (usually Bora the spear). At this point you triggered  the second effect of Wise strix that makes you set a Rank up magic spell from your deck, so you set Rank up magic soul shave force.  Step 3: Now you use the effect of Zephyros from you GY by returning one card on your field to your hand (usually Black whirlwind, Pinpoint landing or Bora the spear) and special summon Union carrier  Step 4: Special summon Simorgh, bird of sovreign using Wise strix and Force strix as materials.  Step 5: Use the effect of union carrier to equip the Simorgh with myst valley Thunderbird from your deck and then use the set Rank up magic soul shave force to summon Cyber Dragon Infinity. Attivate its effect and absorb union carrier.  Step 6: In the end phase use the effect of Simorgh to special summon Myst Valley Apex Avian from you deck in a zone Simorgh points to and entry your opponent becomes Angry while you negate everything he does!  This was the basic guaranteed combo, but you can also end your turn with mother addizionale monsters like Borreload Savage Dragon and Time thief redoer to improve your negation power. I've also put 3x of Lightning storm to prevent disadvantage by starting second and to put out your opponent' spell/traps cards in order to have the conditions to use Simorgh's effect in the End Phase. Obviously, you can substitute it with other cards from you side deck like Crossout designator, ash blossom and/or Nibiru As Wells. The motivativation because I pur 2x of Pinpoint landing is quite simple: draw power on your turn and the opponent's turn when you attivate the effect of Myst Valley Thunderbird and because it's a continuos spell that you can make go black to your hand by the effect of Zephyros.

deck_excerpt: A deck mixing Eldich and Invoked archetypes, working well second or first, with really good control and powerfull monsters, also really fun to use.
deck_description: A deck using the new Eldlich archetype, using a lot of control, and adding powerfull fusion monsters thanks to invoked.   Things you can do going first: -If you can get Aleister the Invoker, summon it, get invocation, summon Almiraj, summon Secure Gardna, fusion summon Mechaba, get Aleister back in the hand with Invocation GY effect (so you have at least a monster for Mechaba effect or using the HT boosting Mechaba, in case of the opponent forgot about him). -Try to send Eldlich the Golden Lord to the GY with Invocation. Get him back on the field by destroying Cursed Eldland (and sending a trap to the GY, using the End Phase effect to set an Eldlixir on the field) or a trap card (and effect in GY for this trap).   Most of the time, you'll have Eldich 3500 ATK almost invulnerable and some negates with traps/Mechaba/HT.   Going second is almost the same.   Tips: If you have two Eldlich and the opponent has no trap or HT (or if you're almost sure), you can Summon Rail Canon Gustav, effect (-2000), summon Rail Canon Juggernaut, effect (6000 ATK) and ending (it can attack 3 times on ennemy's monsters.) Juste check this vidéo against Sacred Beasts, going second, impossible win: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cgOCeRsNIOg&feature=youtu.be A vidéo against Salamngreat (and a bad start with no Invoked on board): https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IU8PJ06-lhU&feature=youtu.be Another one going second (not the better start) against Hamon, tough win: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MEa66YfkXBY A last one against Mermail, he couldn't do anything: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=REbBSf_fT9Y Hope you'll enjoy this deck :) Feel free  to ask some questions, i'll try to help, or adding suggestions!

deck_excerpt: Utilizes the power of The Dark Magicians to overwhelm the opponent through constant DM summon pressure, overpower them with strong fusion archetype mo
deck_description:
(v3.0)

So basically the deck relies on draw power to dig deep into your deck and set up your field as consistently as possible.

Use cards like Magicians Soul, Apprentice Illusion Magician, Foolish Burial, Armageddon Knight, and Dark Grepher (if main decked) to dump 1 of each of the Dark Magicians (DM, Girl, Mahad, Mana) to the GY in order to power up Soul Servant's draw power. Spell-book engine, Circle, Dark Magicians (fusion) and Wonder Wands (if main decked) also help supplement draw power (chain Servant with them for better effect).

When using Servant, use its first effect to top deck whichever essential card (Rod, Souls) is currently not in your hand and then use your support draw cards (Wand, Knowledge, TDMs fusion) to draw it. This will ensure you get a normal summon and special summon same turn for maximum efficiency.

Use Rod to search out Circle, Eternal Soul, Navigation, or Soul Servant if it's fully powered up. Normal Summon Armageddon Knight or Jester (if main decked) if you don't have Rod on hand. Knight will aid in dumping DM, Girl, or Rod (to set up grave effect) to the GY, and also serves as fusion material for Dark Calvary. Jester combos well with Apprentice, allowing you to normal summon her same turn by tributing Jester, which will let you add 2 DM from your deck with their combined effects.

Special summon DM to the field using Magician Soul, Eternal Soul, or Navigation. You can also add DM to your hand using Apprentice and Jester float effect to have him ready for special summoning (Eternal Soul, Navigation) or fusion summoning (Timaeus, Secrets).

Get DM Girl on the field using Bond, Navigation, Mana (float effect) or The Dark Magicians (fusion) float effect in order to make use of Dark Burning Magic for offense and/or Magicians Combination for Defense.

Once you have your Field set up with Circle, Eternal Soul, Combination (optional), and your DMs out of the Deck, look to go into DM the Dragon Knight to have him protect your back-row while also being protected by them.

Other win conditions are getting Bosses like BLS (link) or Dark Calvary (fusion) on the field, endgame burn with Red-Eyes Flare Metal, or Quintet Magician via Predaplant/Magicalized Fusion once you fulfill its summon requirements.

deck_excerpt: I enjoy playing this deck, it is anti meta, and it beats decks of course.

deck_excerpt: A control setup deck that aims to limit your opponent's options through the use of disruptions and floodgates, granting enough time to get out the pow
deck_description: A control setup deck that aims to limit your opponent's options through the use of disruptions and floodgates, granting enough time to get out the powerful Cyberdarkness dragon! Yes, yes, I know. Cyberdarks are infamous for being real bad for many reasons. Upon further inspection, however, one would notice that its speed and overall playstyle are the main offenders to its bad reputation. This build aims to patch up these problems by incorporating play stoppers and disruptions to slow the game down a bit, as making the archetype faster would just hinder its consistency and performance. The use of a small Shaddoll engine does synergise well with the deck, and offers a lot of value for resources. If you are interested in knowing why these specific tech cards were chosen or how the strategy works in practice, feel free to watch the video posted! This deck is part of a YouTube series called TRULY TRASH? - videos based around trash tier Yu-Gi-Oh! archetypes. Each video contains replays, analyses, and deck techs as well as the reasoning behind choosing such! If you want to know more, here is the link to the playlist: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLxNK1GOQn2ED0CyDr1M_l6zUSyt4XpTKe

deck_excerpt: A Semi Budget Rokket Build with a great end board going First or Second
deck_description:
Going First Strategy with directions in chat and follow ups
  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=489400-17655486
Going Second OTK with directions in chat(If you go uninterrupted and if you're opponent somehow doesn't lose you have the going first end board as well) 
  • https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=489400-17655934
My two other builds have Starliege Seyfert and World Legacy Guardragon, those we're the two major cuts in this deck that made it "Semi-Budget". Borreload Savage Dragon is in the deck list as well, it's almost 100% needed but its expensive so you could replace a few Rokkets with Rokket Synchron and replace Savage with Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss which can simulate the Negate situation although slightly harder to pull off. Hopefully both combo replays reflect how strong this deck is with its end boards going first or second. This obviously isn't my first Rokket list as i'm always adjusting and adapting it to what i feel is good or is needed against the meta. Like all combo heavy decks you can very easily be interrupted by Nibiru or have all you work come to naught by Dark Ruler No More which is sadly something you can't really work around. Knightmare Phoenix is your closest out to Mystic Mine without the Side Deck, hoping you can use enough materials to have the same amount of monsters as the opponent to get the Phoenix effect. Expect a few more Rokket Deck Lists in the future as Eternity Code brings a new card in Noctovision Dragon which is a great extender for this deck and its only a Common.

deck_excerpt: Abuse the Rikka engine to quickly fill the board with Princess Plants that punish your opponent for destroying your plant type monsters; And then fuse
deck_description: I use Princess Plants ability to flood the board on T1 and abuse sunflower and autumn leaves synergy to punish my opponent for attempting to break my board. I accomplish this using a Rikka engine with petal, glamour, and snowdrop I can easily fill my board T1 and survive until T2. On my T2 I use my non-rikka plants' effects to fill my board and bring out an untargetable Chaos BLK.     If I have solemn judgment in my hand T1 xyz summon Rikka Queen so that I have a way to break my opponents board via her effect to tribute an opponents monster(quick effect) and solemn judgment being able to negate just about anything else.     The weakness of this deck is that the only protection it has, from spell and trap cards that target and remove a monster, is an effect monster and requires 1 tribute.

deck_excerpt: This deck is very good at both stopping your opponent from playing the game and also killing your opponent. This deck can brick a lot, as with any dec
deck_description: If you are like me, than you like fusion decks, combo decks, or top tier decks. Invoked Shaddoll is kind of a hard deck to play well, seeing as how there are so many options you can choose from depending on your starting hand (if you don’t brick, of course). The deck is also very good at stopping your opponent from playing the game, going first or second. For going first, your main goal is to end on a board of Apollousa for three, Mechaba, Winda, and either a Raidjin or Caliga (preferably Raidjin because than you can’t get super-polyd, if I’m not mistaken). But if you brick, which is easy to do with this deck, your secondary goal is to at least bring out Winda, as it is unaffected by your opponents card effects, and they can only special summon once per turn. For going second, you can do one of two things (from what I’ve learned with the deck): 1. If you have Aleister, which is by far the best card in the deck, you can normal summon him, activate his effect to add Invocation from your deck to your hand, than link him off for Almiraj, than use Invocation to fuse Aleister in the grave and Almiraj (both get banished) to summon Purgatrio, which gains 400 attack for each monster and can attack all monsters once each, and 2. Do the standard combo (Aleister + Wendi/Squamata + Damage Juggler), but instead of Apollousa, you end on a Borrelsword instead, which is a lot riskier, but will more than likely kill your opponent.

deck_excerpt: This is a infernoble deck that ends on 2 negates + buster lock
deck_description:
Deck focuses on ending on God phoenix Gearfried, Dragun and Buster lock. Isolde + Renaud or any way to get Renaud to hand is full combo. With 2 extenders you can summon Charles to discard a card from opponents hand with Smoke Grenade and to also get a pop during opponents turn.   Deck is still in testing so ratios could change or some could be replaced. If you know any cards that can help the deck please comment.     Combo:
  1. Sublime Knight - Expaladin effect to Equip and summon Squeaknight.
  2. Make Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights with  Sublime Knight - Expaladin and Squeaknight.
  3. Isolde Search Infernoble Knight - Roland (You don't need to add roland he is simply discard fodder for extenders or Dragun discard.
  4. Use Isoldes second effect to send Phoenix blade, Smoke Grenade of The Thief, Infernoble Arms - Hauteclere and Infernoble Arms -Joyeuse to summon Infernoble Knight - Oglier.
  5. Ogliers effect will activate to send God Phoenix Gearfried from deck to GY.
  6. you have 3 Different ways to get to Infernoble Knight - Renaud. Renaud, Infernoble Knight - Durendal, Heritage of The Chalice
  7. If you open Heritage search Durendal or Renaud
  8. If you open Durendal Equip it to Oglier activate effect to send it to GY to search Durendal.
  9. Special summon Renaud and activate effect to add back Gearfried.
  10. Banish any Equip from GY that isnt Phoenix Blade or Smoke Grenade.
  11. Banish Sublime + Squeaknight to add back Phoenix Blade.
  12. Equip Phoenix Blade to Gearfried.
  13. Use Renaud + Isolde to make Crystron Halqifibrax.
  14. Use the effect of Halqifibrax to summon Jet Syncron from your deck.
  15. Use Halqifibrax to link summon Linkross and summon 2 tokens.
  16. Use Jet synchron and 1 token to synchro summon into Formula Synchron.
  17. Use the effect of Formula to draw 1 looking either for a extender or discard.
  18. Use the Formula and last token to make Martial Metal Marcher
  19. Use the Effect of MMM to bring back Formula 
  20. Use Oglier + linkross to make Predaplant Verte Anaconda.
  21. Use MMM + Formula to make Union Carrier
  22. Activate Union Carrier to equip Dragon Buster Destruction Sword
  23. Use Vertes effect to summon Dragun.

deck_excerpt: Rainbow Dragon, Zenith makes Sapphire Pegasus a 1 card combo either for Rainbow Neos or Utopia Double for OTK and Dark Rainbow Dragon easily allows th
deck_description: Rainbow Dragon, Zenith allows the Pegasus play to be more useful (Zenith can ss itself from hand if your Crystal Beast involved in an attack and you also can special summon Zenith from s/t zone with Crystal Promise to complement the rank 8/chaos play together with Chaos Dragon Levianeer, and both are searchable through Melody of Awakening Dragon). Pegasus places Zenith on s/t zone as continuous spell, use Zenith in s/t zone ss another Pegasus, ss Verte for Rainbow Neos or Utopia Double for OTK (you can play 2 Double or Nothing because our win condition is very limited). Crystal lineup: Rainbow and Rainbow Dark Dragon (for chaos play, since you need to play 2 so your Zenith always can activate from s/t zone), 3 Pegasus (your main starter, a wind too for Miracle Fusion play), 1 Crystal Beast Tiger (another fodder if u run out of Pegasus), Crystal Promise (ss Crystal beast from s/t zone), 3 Crystal Bond (adds Pegasus and can place Zenith on s/t zone like Pegasus), 3 Rainbow Bridge (adds Bond or Promise, not once per turn), that's all mainly just to turbo Pegasus out, making us running roughly 9 starters. Neos lineup: 1 Neos (material), 3 Neos Fusion (Verte target, can be Rainbow Neos fodder to spin backrows too while giving it protection ), Miracle Fusion (Verte target, luckily Great Tornado works with Pegasus to complement our go 2nd strat). The rest are just handtraps and kaijus (with light/dark attribute, kaiju can be free lv8 too) with some breaking board cards. Pros: Super consistent 1 card starter, able to break most of the meta board with non-destruction non-targeting play, can put in big damage and even OTK, strategy is not very well known among player. Cons: Red-Eyes Dragoon play is better than Rainbow Neos, cant always put lethal damage in 1 turn, going first is very bad (needs side deck or more extra deck choices). Cards to think of: Ruby Carbuncle (good extender, but not a starter and needs another card to be online), other Crystal s/t (most of them are bad and have ridiculous requirement), Effect Veiler (good light target for chaos play but we can easily send another light like Neos to GY, Imperm is better too).

deck_excerpt: Choo Choo! Board wipe loop AND OTK, with a scrap package, and True King of All Calamities.
deck_description: Machina Trains. A stupid OTK deck with a solid grind game and a good (if not amazing) plan for going first. The deck is still a blind second deck. I ended on 41 cards, which feels all right. It might help reduce seeing bricks like Scrap Golem, but more importantly, the deck is refined to the point that all of the cards feel truly essential.  We're running 0 hand traps. Instead we have a 9 going second cards, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 3 Kaijus, and 3 Lightning Storm. Dark Ruler is now in the main deck. It makes sense, and since other people are doing it I might as well, you need to be able to break through Adimancipator somehow. The Kaijus are notable, since we're running Level 10 Machine monsters. That means you can search Kaijus off of Urgent Schedule when using it as fodder in the scrap combo going first, you can use Anger Knuckle if it's in your GY to special summon it or a level 10 from your hand, you can send it to the GY for the special summon on Machina Fortress, and most importantly you can use multiple copies to make Rank 10s, important in trains.  We have 8 different starters, and a strange variety of them. Going first, Machina Metalcruncher is the most important. You can use it to make True King of All Calamities while searching a Bullet Train, which is already better than Night Express. It can also search different combo pieces (with luck). We need 2 so we can search a second copy with Megaform to make Ranks 9s, but you can also use Flying Pegasus to make True King. Notably, the effect still works if special summoned by Flying Pegasus.  Flying Pegasus is technically a starter, and is an okay normal summon to help make rank 10s and start combos. But its real purpose is to be searched off of Revolving Switchyard. The second copy just means you can still use Switchyard to pull it out of the deck if you see one in your hand but have a better normal summon. We still need 1 Night Express Knight, to search off of the Switchyard and start plays.  The last 3 are Scrap Recycler. Recycler is insane with Machina Citadel and Urgent Schedule, going first or second. With Gizmek Orochi and Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion he's a one card Borrelsword Dragon with Gizmek Orochi as def position fodder and extra damage. Going first he's an easy Apollousa. Going second, you have Urgent Schedule for that board, plus Machina Citadel. This is lower end for the deck as well. You can play through multiple negations and still pull this off as well, since these are 1 or 2 card combos in the hand. This is the main starter of the deck, and generally our want to use him to send Machina Fortress.  All 6 of the Trains special summons are here. You need 3 each of Derricrane and Bullet Train so that you can find easy level 10s with Machina Metalcruncher. Derricrane is my favourite, put that under Super Dora... Mmm yummy. But my favourite Train, by far, are the 2 copies of Machina Citadel. This is a combo piece, a free-floating effect for your rank 10s, and a reasonable line of disruption all at the same time. You need at least 2 copies, for 2 reasons. 1 is so that you can loop Citadels, forcing players to banish your Citadel or destroy it twice in one turn to get rid of it, and giving you a board wipe every turn. The second, more important reason,is so that if you've pulled a Citadel out of the GY with its effect or Flying Pegasus, you can use Machina Megaform to pull out the second citadel and make a Rank 10 (with a cool floating effect to summon Citadel on destruction).  2 Machina Fortress are necessary. You can make rank 7s with Flying Pegasus, but being able to make Rank 7s with Machina Megaform and Fortress on the field is essential to ending with more than just a Fortress on the field. Don't get me wrong, its a reasonably obnoxious beat stick, but by making Dacossack you can go into Auroradon to make Borreload Savage Dragon. The fact that this card is not once per turn is insane, so long as you have machine monsters with lots of stars in your hand you can keep summoning it, which is how you make some of your link plays, and part of how you set up Anger Knuckle.  Machina Irradiator and Machina Megaform are a combo that grabs any machina out of your deck, and are common targets for Machina Redeployment. Megaform is the more impressive - it gives a Fortress you're using as a beatstick a cool floating effect, helps make Dingirsu with 3 Materials going first, and actually has applications so long as you've got access to Fortress, whereas Irradiator is basically just used to destroy your own cards for Citadel, and to pull Megaform out of the GY to make Xyz plays.  The last 9 cards are card advantage engines. Machina Redeploment is a free citadel on the field, and lets you set up hands with more Machina cards for Machina link combos. Switchyard is free special summons, and can even do it on your opponent's turn, though limited copies of Flying Pegasus does hamper its usefulness slightly. It also serves as another way to fix you hand and start combo, like Redeployment. I've already talked about the insane advantage you can get off of Urgent Schedule. The card is busted.  You can add a Halqifibrax combo with Jet Synchron, Deskbot 001, Halqifibrax, and Herald of the Arc Light. This just gives you an alternative route out of Scrap Recycler, which is good going first. I tried the package, didn't like it, and now I'm back to this list.

deck_excerpt: A deck featuring both an archetype made from an old card and revamps of older cards. Who says you can't teach an old dog new tricks?
deck_description: Pros:  -Strong blowout effects  -Decent grind game  -Explosive strength  Cons:  -Can brick  -Don't have too much choice over which gameplan (Metaphys or Thunder Dragon), unless you open really well  -Can be slow to get going     The deck overall is quite fun. It's an updated version of my prior variant, except with a heavier focus on the Metaphys portion. It makes use of cards like Aloof Lupine, Lightray Grepher, Crossout Designator and Gold Sarcophagus to banish the cards it wants from the deck to access different gameplans. I'm also utilizing Crystrons, since both Quan and Citree work rather well with the deck, since they can either banish monsters from gy to get their banish effs, or get monsters out of the hand and into the gy. This variant isn't nearly as explosive as other Thunder Dragon decks, but it makes up for that by having power Metaphys boardwipes.

deck_description: Here is some deck i'm working on, works well online. Be carefull with your summoning order. You can easily finish with a Borreload Savage Dragon + Crystron + another synchro monster + apo and/or Block Dragon. If you summon apo tributing I:P, it will prevent destruction by cards effects. Summon I:P first and then Crystron. Your main goal going first is to get Block Dragon ASAP but without skipping Raptite (or making the summon impossible). Link summon using Block Dragon to trigger effect. Usually, i get Gigantes + Seeker + Researcher (gigantes will be easily Special summoned).   Missus Radiant is just here for a T3 if your ressources are low. It can trigger Block Dragon, boost Earth Monsters and can get back a monster from GY. Never play it T1.   Try to play this link order! I:P => Crystron => Apollousa (if you can).   On opponent turn, you can disrupt monster effects and some spell cards (with Savage and/or Dragite). Don't forget to use Crystron effect ASAP, and decide which monster to synchro after (Sattelite, Crystal Wing  or Final Sigma (only in extra monster zone for this one if possible).   Here are some videos going first or second, and some combos.   https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H1Q9q7codG0 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QOgP9KAU-a4   Going first, you're very weak against Nibiru, really, or Kaijus. Going second, it can be alright if you have multiples effects to play, if you just have one, there's a high chance that you'll be countered...   Have Fun!

deck_excerpt: Destruction Sword Is my favorite archetype in Yugioh. This deck that utilizes Guardragon combo to super charge destruction sword combo and cause compl
deck_description: Okay so this is the final version of this deck tried, tested and true. So the strategy is advanced since the last posting and is more consistent.  Special summon (using dragon shrine or pendulum call to send it to the graveyard) Darkwurm to bring Gate zero to your hand. ( if you use darkwurm as a discard for pendulum call, it’s an easy plus 2; bringing harmonizing and white wing to your hand).  Normal summon summon a level 4 or lower dragon monster. Buster welp’s effect adds dragon of the destruction sword or memories to your hand. But if it dracoslayer that’s fine too. Link summon into Romulus, adding dragon ravine to your hand. Discard a card (mermories) and send tempest to your graveyard  use gate zero and any 8 scale apart from harmonizing magician for your pendulum scale. (harmonizing is to valuable when pendulum summoned but if it has to be done it has to be). Pendulum summon the harmonizing, darkwurm from your extra deck and dracoslayer if you have it, white wing magician if you have it and leave a zone open.  Upon pendulum summoning harmonizing special summon dragoncaller from you deck. And sychro summon Star eater. (Due to dragoncaller a effect if it attacks a dragon monster then it’s attack becomes 6400). Or special summon celestial to sychro summon beleeze.  link summon Elpy and pisty using darkwurm and other level 4 or lower dragon monster. Special summon another darkwurm from your deck. Sychro Summon Buster dragon in defense using white wing and darkwurm. (This turns all opponents monster to dragons). Then special summon another dragon from your grave yard using pisty.  link summon skull dread using pisty, Elpy, Romulus and dragon to break guardragon lock. Drawing 4 cards (if you haven’t got a buster blader in your hand already that’s the card you need.) If not add level 7 monster. Skull dreads effect to special summon buster blader and activate tempest effect banishing Elpy and pisty to special summon itself. Xyz summon odd-eyes absolute then link summon into protector welp of the destruction sword using absolute and skull dread. Which special summons odd-eyes vortex. Now if memories or dragon of the destruction sword are not in your graveyard use protector welp effect to send which ever one isn’t to the graveyard.  Now that buster blader, any dragon monster, dragon of the destruction sword and destruction sword memories are all in the graveyard, activate memories banishing buster blader and a dragon monster (not dragon of the destruction sword) and fusion summon dragon destroyer. ATTACK  if you did not attack with dragon destroyer upon ending your turn protector welp then does damage to your opponent equal to dragon destroyers attack (which if there’s dragons on the field or graveyard then that’s quite a lot).  If you did not end the duel upon your opponent next turn activate buster dragons effect equipping dragon destroyer with dragon of the destruction sword locking your opponent from special summoning from the extra deck.  dont forget that in situations where this combo gets negated or you get a brick hand (in aspects to this combo) Big Eye can come in real clutch just remember to bait any negate first. Flare metal can also come in handy if your in a position where burning their life points is needed. UPDATE: so I added mystic mine prevention, my main strategy against this is MIND CRUSH. It’s an old card and has gone under the radar as far a prevention of this scorn of a card. Just make sure you bait the negate first. Dust barrier is also an older card that can come in real handy in this situation if you have multiple normal monsters on the field they are unaffected for 2 turns which can end the duel. And if all else fails dark hole all your monsters they are pendulum after all and have mystic mine destroy itself.  but that’s it, get your game on and high five the sky
Just fun Zarc

deck_excerpt: Morphtronic Link deck with Power Toll Dragon equip support
deck_description: The main purpose of this deck is to get out a number of control extra deck cards that shut down your opponent such as Naturia Beast or Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon if you went first, or any of the Knightmare Link monsters that can destroy their cards and change out cards in your hand if co-linked. Your main first plays will usually get trying to get out Morphtroninc Celfon and using either Where Arf Thou? (to pull out a Morphtronic Smartfon from your deck) or Machine Duplication to get two more Celfons.  If you don't have a Celfon in hand, you should be able to still add it with a Where Arf Thou? Or One For One.  Celfon is also a great target to use for linking into Linkuriboh and you can either get it back right away with Junk Box, Morphtroninc Repair Unit, World Legacy Succession, or Monster Reborn allowing you to use its special summon effect all over again to get out more. Morphtroninc Smartfon is a great card that can special summon itself by banishing a Morphtronic monster from your graveyard. While in attack position he can add any Morphtronic card (monster, spell, or trap) from the excavated cards to your hand. While in defense Smartfon can let you change the order of cards on top of your deck according to the die roll, or even just put them on the bottom of the deck.  Smartfon is also a tuner and being level 1 is fantastic because it allows you to synchro him with a Celfon for a Formula Synchron, or with a Staplen or Boomboxen for Naturia Beast, or just use him in any Link Summon. Morphtronic Lantron is another level 1 tuner but will mainly be used as a Where Arf Thou? To get Smartfon or One For One to get your Celfon. Morphtronic Scopen is a level 3 Tuner that can special summon a level 4 Morphtronic monster from your hand in which you will either Link Summon or Synchro Summon a Power Tool Dragon to search out a equip spell, Either D.D.R. Different Dimension Reincarnation, to Special Summon something banished from Smartfon or Morphtronic Repair Unit to Special Summon something from your graveyard, such as your Celfon, to use all over again. Scopen can also be used to synchro summon into an armory arm using a Celfon. Morphtronic Slingen allows you to tribute another Morphtronic monster you control to destroy one card your opponent controls. This can also fuel your graveyard with a target to banish for Smartfon or any of your revival Spell Cards. This deck is still a work in progress and I would very much appreciate any feedback. And as I don't have a Side Deck yet I would very much appreciate it.

deck_description: This is a going 1st Deck.  you want to see Rescue Rabbit and World Legacy "World Chalice" in your start Hand.  You start with Rescue Rabbit and summon 2 Andals, Link summon Amduk, Tribute summon Amduk for World Chalice, Link summon Test Panther, add Attorix (or Comeback, depends) to Hand, special summon Lee and Guardragon by World Chalice, Link both away for Lib, set Succession from Deck, Banish Guardragon from Grave to Special Andal from Grave, Activate Test Panther's effect to tap out Andal for Augustus, Special Attorix from Hand activate her effect and chose Augustus from Deck, Fusion Summon for Tamer Editor, Special Domitianus, link Tamer Editor and Test Panther away for Cross-Sheep, Activate Succession and special summon Tamer Editor from Grave in Cross-Sheeps Arrow, special Andal, special Heraklinos by Tamer Editor, Link summon Union Carrier for Andal and Cross-Sheep, activate Union's effect, choose Domitianus and equip him with Destruction Sword, activate Lee from Grave and put Union Carrier in Grave to add Lee to Hand.  Now you have Heraklinos with 4 spell and trap negations, Domitianus with 1 Monster effect negation, and your oponnents Extra Deck is locked down.     The Main Threats for this Deck build are Kaijus and especially Nibiru, but Crossout Designator will get rid of this problem someday.  The Psy-Cards aren't important, you can switch them with whatever suits you the best.  Apollousa fits in the Deck very well, but this cheap version is very good on its own.

deck_excerpt: A consistent Rokket Dragon Link deck with both budget options and upgrade options as well as combo videos.
deck_description: Index: 1 Intro 2 card choices 3 Combos 4 Budget options 5 seyfert upgrade options 6 Side Deck   1 Intro This is a semi-budget Rokket Dragon Link deck that I’ve been working on since the structure deck was released in 2019. The list has a lot of similarities to Shunping’s but I’ve also made changes to make it cheaper (I don’t own Seyfert) while maintaining a similar level of consistency and resilience. I also think this variant is easier to play personally. That said it is still a very challenging deck to play overall. The deck can pump out strong first turn boards but also has a fair bit of flexibility to play through challenging situations going second. Edit: note I have made a few additions to sections that I have included as italicized "Edit:" comments after the original section. I have not changed any original text or the deck itself. 2 card choices I’m not going to address every card in the deck but will address a few odd picks in the deck. Black Metal Dragon: This card saw usage as a 1 of in Shunpings list. I’ve been using it as a 3 of because it makes a 1 card combo into a full board. It might not be as good of a 1 card combo as seyfert but at a fraction of the price I think it is well worth it. Keeper of the Shrine: There are some specific combo purposes for this card such as with Black Metal Dragon but it is also in large part in the deck as a backup target for dragon shrine and foolish burial if you drew background dragon and Absorouter and/or have already sent them to the graveyard. Background Dragon: This card is bricky if you draw it but makes dragon shrine and foolish burial into amazing starters. You can complete a whole combo without committing a normal summon assuming no disruption using this card. Autorokket Dragon: So Cosmic Cyclone is a natural out to cards like Mystic Mine but doesn’t work against things like Secret Village of The Spellcasters or Imperial Order. This card gives the deck a natural out to spell and trap cards which block the deck from playing spells. Alternatively, you could substitute Knightmare Phoenix but the deck’s extra deck is very tight and also: Tracer, Elpy, Pisty, Rokket Synchron, and Quadborrel are all liabilities for locking the deck out of playing the Phoenix. Hibernation Dragon: This card struggles to fit into the deck but at the same time has crazy effects in my opinion. It is a +1 for just summoning it while you have a level 4 or lower dragon in your GY. It can also summon Borreload/Borrelsword Dragon from the GY by banishing itself. Most of the combos don’t have room to summon search it though. I usually find this card makes a good backup Hieratic target if you don’t want to summon Brotaur because you already like your hand as is or Drew Brotaur. If you don’t like this card feel free to replace it with another Absorouter Dragon or whatever you want. 3 Combos Here are some Youtube videos of different combos you’ll be looking for in this deck and how to perform them (Each video is about a minute long). Notably these combos are all done with minimum resources and can end on stronger boards with more resources invested. I also demonstrated some different boards you could choose to end on when using Romulus while Dark Locked. Edit: I've created a playlist with all the combos in it here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL4wvY6W8_poYB0amunwwgUjIXYmFBELs- 1 card combo with Black Metal Dragon https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPMmi7bVSt0 2 card combo with any Rokket and Dragon Shrine https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U__fPt-FiVI 2 card combo with any Rokket and Absorouter Dragon https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wuGkXOpp7fY 2 card combo with any Rokket and Quick Launch https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cdo4q2Z9O5I Dubious Hand. Sometimes you get a hand that has no clear combo but can still make an awesome board. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hCT_rcTkUJY 4 Budget Options While I’ve tried to keep this deck cheaper for my own wallet’s sake, some cards have gone up in price since I bought them. Below is a list of cards you can cut and potential substitutions for them: 1x Striker dragon -> whatever you want. The third is a luxury for turn 3 if you use 2 turn 1 but most combos only use 1. Edit: I've considered Barricadeborg Blocker before for the deck but there is no room to include it. may be a good substitute for a third striker dragon due to the decks tendency to shoot Boot Sector for Combos. 3x Dark Ruler No more -> Effect Veiler is a good budget handtrap 3x Called by the Grave -> D.D. Crow. Doesn’t protect your combos but is a really strong affordable hand trap right now. 1x Borreload Savage Dragon -> Draco Berserker of the Tenyi is much weaker but still provides a strong level 8 synchro disruption to end on. 1x Borrelsword Dragon -> Draco Berserker of the Tenyi also is kind of a much weaker Borrelsword. If you aren’t looking at running two Draco Berserkers because really there is no reason to, you can throw whatever other dark boss monster you want in this slot. Borreload Excharge Dragon and Borrelguard Dragon are both really cheap alternatives that fit in easily. Edit: Topologic cards also may make good replacements and are widely considered better than Borrelguard and Excharge Dragon. Edit: Other budget options for the extra deck with their own pros and cons each include: an additional Borreload Dragon, Galaxy Satellite Dragon, Saryuja, Wee Witch's Apprentice, and Booster Dragon. 5 Seyfert Upgrades If you own Seyfert or have no qualms spending the money for him and the Black and White Dragons to go with him. You can cut: 1 Silverrokket, 1 Magnarokket, 2 Black Metal Dragons, and Hibernation Dragon to make room for that 5 card package. Edit: Since the Black Metal dragons are being used as 1 card combos, removing a Cosmic Cyclone and a Dark Ruler No More over the Black Metal Dragons may be better a better choice. 6 Side Deck There are so many options for the side deck at the moment at so many different price points I felt that I didn’t want to hold the deck back or make it really expensive by trying to recommend a specific side deck. Feel free to use whatever tech cards you think are best for current meta.

deck_description: An aggro deck that aims to get as many powerhouses on the field as possible to overpower your opponent, swiftly ending games! This deck is part of a YouTube series called TRULY TRASH? - videos based around trash tier Yu-Gi-Oh! archetypes. Valkyries are an archetype with relatively low attack power but, what they lack in offense, they make up for in their ability to swarm the field.  They can go first or second - just make sure not to use Ride of the Valkyries if you go first.     They aren't super reliant on the Extra Deck, meaning Pot of Extravagance is actually a great draw power card for them. They can afford to play 1 of everything (except the obvious 3-of) because losing any particular one still allows for their typical lines of play.  Being a Fairy-type based archetype means they potentially have the ability to lock special summons with Archlord Kristya.  Their new "boss" monster, Valkyrie Sigrun, has the ability to special summon any other Valkyrie monster from the hand or GY making it an excellent combo extender/starter, and is also, for some reason, a level 9 which means boards can end with True King of all Calamities.     They also have 3 incredibly strong spells; Final Light, the aforementioned Ride of the Valkyries, and Mischief of the Time Goddess.  Final Light is essentially an archetype specific Soul Charge.  Ride of the Valkyries allows you to special summon as many Valkyries with different names as you want from your hand at the cost of bouncing your entire board back to the decks during the EP. Once it's in the GY you can activate its second effect to search a Mischief of the Time Goddess from your deck.  Finally, Mischief of the Time Goddess is a quick-play spell that you can activate at the end of your BP as long as you only control Valkyrie monsters. It skips the turn clock ahead to the start of your next BP allowing you to skip your previous MP2, EP, your opponent's entire turn, and your current DP, SP, and MP1 as though they never happened. This allows for some interesting things. 1, it means you can avoid the negative effects of cards such as Ride of the Valkyries and Celestial Transformation. 2, it also means you can essentially OTK your opponent regardless of the Valkyries low attack power weakness. 3, "hard once per turn" effects can potentially be activated again during the MP2 after your second BP.     All in all, it is a rogue archetype that I truly feel hasn't been explored enough.     I'm mostly uploading this to see how much the deck would cost. I have had success with it on EDOPro and am considering purchasing it irl now that Valkyrie Sigrun has been released in the TCG.

deck_excerpt: Orcust in 2020 is still consistent! Go first and setup your negates so you can kill your opponent in the next turn.
deck_description: This is an Orcust deck with a scrap and a Danger! engine. The scrap cards will start the combo off and the Dangers to improve consistency. sometimes you need to take slight detours to start the combo off but with enough skill (and memory), you will always pull it off.  My rating:  Attack: 4/5  Defense: 4/5  Consistency: 5/5  Strong against: Shaddoll, Blue Eyes  Weak against: Gravekeeper, Nekroz  Main Scrap Combo:  Normal summon Scrap Recycler  Activate and send O-Lion/Jet Synchron to the grave (You need to send a card to the GY for Jet to revive it)  Summon a token with O-Lion's effect, or use Jet to SS itself  Link them into Wyvern  Activate Wyvern's effect, summon Recycler and send it back to the GY, then SS Golem from the deck, then destroy a card on the field. (Note: if you are going first you will need a card on the field to send to the GY, like a spell or a Danger)  Activate Golem's effect, SS Recycler  Activate Recycler, send World Wand to the GY  Link Golem and Recycler into Ib  Activate Ib and set World Legacy Succession  Activate Succession, summon Golem from the GY  Activate Golem again to summon Recycler, the send Knightmare to the GY  Link Ib and Wyvern into Apollousa (Don't use the other cards!)  Activate Knightmare from the GY, buff up any card (it really doesn't matter) and send Cymbal Skeleton to the GY  Activate Wand to SS Knightmare  Link one of the Scraps with Knightmare to make Galatea, then shuffle Wand from the banished zone into the deck, setting Orcustrated Babel  Activate Babel  Activate Cymbal Skeleton, SS Knightmare  Link the other Scrap with Knightmare to make Verte Anaconda  SS Dingirsu using Galatea, attach Cymbal Skeleton to it  Activate Anaconda, send Instant Fusion to the GY and SS Winda  End your turn. Winda will stay alive if you detach a material from Dingirsu (Preferably Cymbal Skeleton), so it will stay alive in your opponent's turn. Don't keep her for 2 turns because she will just lock you out of special summoning too!     Overall, this deck is pretty high skill because you need to time your negates and create big combos. Have fun!

deck_excerpt: SPAM OUT BOSS MONSTERS AND COUNTER YOUR OPPONENTS PLAYS EASILY
deck_description: This is a pretty straightforward deck that can counter most, if not all, of your opponents plays. You'll always want to see boss stage in your hand because it's one of the main win conditions in the deck. You'd also want to start with Aleister so you can use him as a onecard Mechaba. If you have Mechaba on the field and Monstrosity in your hand, you can activate Monstrosity to summon out two more level 9s and use those two for true king of all calamities to lock out your opponent in their turn. Then once it's you opponent's turn, use boss stage's effect to summon out preferably either hoarr or nidhogg to completely sut out your opponent. This could reach up to 3-4 negates in one turn. You can also use kaiju slumber either as bait for spells/traps or to wipe out the field and just make your plays from there. Lots of boss monsters and negates mean easy win.

Use the effects of "Plunder Patroll" monsters to accomplish this by Summoning them during your opponent's turn. In addition, cards like "Goldenhair" and "Piwraithe the Ghost Pirate" have effects that can Summon themselves out to be used as material, mainly for the Link Summon of "Blackbeard". "Plunder Patroll Shipyarrrd" can power up your pirates, while your crew can also board your "Plunder Patrollships" to power them up by equiping themselves using the various Spells/Traps in the archetype, and also "Necroquip Prism" can equip a "Plunder Patroll" from your Graveyard while also Summoning another pirate from your hand.

I Don't know why people don't use this deck more often. The surrounding of necrovalley shuts down almost all of the current decks, such as Eldlich, Sky Striker Recursion, Orcust, Borrel, and Salamangreat, while also giving you protection to use handtraps freely. This variant also includes the ability to go super poly into starving and mudragon. This also has an interesting tech against Altergeist, where you can take their monsters for Quintet Magician, then wipe the rest of their board. But basically, the best thing to do search Spiritualist as quickly as possible then go into Supernaturalist with Necrovalley up. Also a good tech is Almarduk to use against Link Spammers.  My favorite thing is to set Spy with backrow floodgates and necrovalley, flip spy to summon recruiter, link into Witch's Apprentice, get the search from recruiter for whatever you need(Spiritualist or other Gravekeeper for fusion) Then go into Supernaturalist. Lowest it can be in this situation is 3700 ATK.

deck_excerpt: Predaplants, Competitive, Going Second, Still being worked on.
deck_description: *This is My Actual Build*  After many tests, i finally reached the conclusion that my Plants are best when synergic with Superpoly, as my natural Extra Deck is full of targets.  This build excels on breaking boards, and by going first it can easily set up a Winda lock via Cherubini and Instant Fusion, Verte Anaconda really helps this deck on mantaining a reasonable amount of threat and by bringing out my ace monster, Starving Venom.  Ultra Poly is Strong because it turns my basic combo into a Chimerafflesia+Verte Anaconda, however, it does not simply bring good as it can brick, fortunately you only need one copy of it on the deck, and because this deck "branches" a lot on its combos, you can live without searching it.  Now on the card review:  Kaijus: As a going second deck, we have to deal with some powerfull monsters, and Verte simply turns any of them into material for Starving Venom, Greedy Venom or even Triphyovertum.  Heliamphorhyncus: Searchable easy Greedy Venom material.  Pankratops: A good Versatile threat.  Drosophyllum Hydra: Searchable "Kaiju" under the right conditions, and can activate its effect to drain 500 Atk from an opponent's monster, i know, conditional, however useful.  Spinodionaea: Good card paired with Predapractice and a target for Scorpio's effect, can put counters.  Edge Imp Chain: Part of the Patchwork Engine, can search Patchwork itself by being sent as a cost by Scorpio.  Edge Imp Sabres: Part of the Patchwork Engine, can be revived via its own effect to easily put bricks back onto the deck and be used as a material for Verte or her Effect.  Ophrys Scorpio: Bread and Butter of the deck, main enabler, allows for many of the deck's branching combos, you always want it on your hand and alongside the edge imps.  Darlingtonia Cobra: Allows for an important search, such as Ultra Poly, Instant Fusion and Superpoly.  Lonefire: Unfortunately, we need consistency, this isn't a bad card by any means, but it isn't a good card either, being easily "Hand Trapped", Called, "Impermed" and such, it does best when you don't have any more options.  Chlamydosundew: Fusion Enabler, combos with Spinodionaea and Ophrys Scorpio.  Sarraceniant: Enables search and sometimes used in a pinch via its own effect by being used as a "Hand Trap".  Cordyceps: Ok, this is new, i don't like this one that much,enables the closing of some games via its powerful effect and can trigger Darlingtonia, useful on the grind and allows for a powerful follow-up.  Predaponics: Basic revival for more material or for a lost Sarraceniant for more search.  Predaprunning: Revives the big Fusions.  Frightfur Patchwork: The engine enabler itself, allows for Poly Searching, Half Chimerafflesia Searching and Scorpio Cost Search, while also maintaining card advantage.  Instant Fusion: Allows the Winda lock and for you to play safe when going second, useful card.  Mind Control: Grab some Apollousas :>, Seriously now, it lets you grab something to make Verte.  Polymerization: Enables the best summoning method :).  Pot of Desires: Consistency.  Predapractice: Helps with combos, consistency and such, allows Spinodionaea and Sarraceniant to be more productive.  Ultra Poly: Card Advantage, allowing Verte to come onto the field more easily.  Predaprime Fusion: Allows for Otk and substitutes Verte in case of Predapractice before the link summon.  Super Polymerization: Board Break, Mind Break(not the actual card) and usually people forfeit easily after this card, allows for your Fusions to easily access the field, while looking at your crying opponent, combos with Verte.  Evenly Matched: See Superpoly until the Fusion part, allows Spell/Trap dealing.  Impermanence: Hand Trap and being a "Must Negate" on board breaking(sometimes).  EXTRA DECK  Greedy Venom: Evolution of my dragon, allows OTK and Threatens the opponent, but be careful as it can nuke everything including your own field.  Triphyovertum: Negates Summons, High Attack, can be Revived easily.  Starving Venom: My Ace, easily eats opponent's monsters by absorbing their ATK, can copy effects and nukes opponents's boards.  Dragostapelia: Puts Counters, Negates effects, can be revived easily.  Chimerafflesia: Can topple almost any monster, Banishes low level monsters, Search Superpoly or any fusion card for the next turn(your opponent will keep that in mind).  Earth Golem: Superpoly target.  Winda: Superpoly target and enables her Lock.  Mudragon: Superpoly target and can be used by instant fusion to protect your monsters against target.  Millenium-Eyes: Protects against almost any monster effect, can be used as a material for Dragostapelia, just like Mudragon, Winda and Earth Golem.  BLS Link: Easily allowed by Scorpio, sometimes wins games.  Cherubini: Winda Lock.  Verte Anaconda: Allows for Superpolying on your opponent's board, sometimes for a second time, makes your own kaijus not threatening anymore(as if they were in the first place) and makes Gameciel an enabler for Greedy Venom.  SIDE DECK: Still working on one as it is format dependant, probably some going first cards.  Q&A  "Why don't you run Lightning Storm?"  Too Pricy, can't have it for now.  "Since when do you play around with this archetype?"  Since they were announced, played with them physically with only INOV cards, basically Starving Venom Turbo OTK.  "How many builds of Predaplant do you have?"  I'm around 340 builds rn.  "Why do you keep playing with this archetype as there are more competitive decks running around?"  Well, i'm a mostly competitive player and i like the archetype a lot, as i had a very lonely infancy so i played with plants, i have a Dionaea Muscipula, Stapelia Grandiflora and some others since those times.  "Will you keep making builds for this deck and posting them on here?"  Well, i will probably post some builds here, as i don't have that much time in my hands for now, i will probably keep building more of them though as i want to top with them at least once.  END OF THE LESSON  This build isstill being worked on, so i might upload a slightly different one later as i am testing it against meta.  Hope you liked, like and share the build if possible.  With regards, Joeri.

deck_excerpt: Scrypton gives major boost to Marincess making Formud Skipper a starter equal to Blue Tang. With Cynet Mining, it makes us play 9 starters. Add those
deck_description: With Scrypton added to TCG (idk about OCG tho), it makes Formud Skipper a must use in Marincess. Not only it acts as extender itself, Scrypton recycles the banished together with Marincess Great Bubble Reef. I will explain both Blue Tang and Formud route (both still needs extender tho). Normal summon Blue Tang, dump Sea Horse (or Mandarin if you alrdy have Sea Horse), make Blue Slug add Sea Horse from GY, ss Sea Horse make Sea Angel add Battle Ocean. From here we need another extender to continue with applied Crystal Heart. Ss the extender, make Coral Anemone (if you wanna recur your Marincess in GY or if you wanna make a link 4) in extra zone, make Crystal Heart, place field spell (always place field spell when you're about to make your last big monster with Crystal Heart), ss any big link Marincess monster (Marbled Rock if first turn, battle protection, and can recur your resource too; Great Bubble Reef to recur banished or in GY Marincess; Wonder Heart to OTK if locked to water; Accescode via Splash Mage - Transcode route for optimal OTK). The Formud route, normal summon Formud (or via one for one), use Formud choose any Marincess in extra deck, make Sea Angel, add field spell then Scrypton from Formud, ss Scrypton make Coral Anemone, use Coral ss Sea Angel. From here we need extender to continue. SS extender, make Blue Slug (you can choose not to use its effect so the big link will have more equip later), then make Crystal Heart so we have enough material for link 4 (Marbled Rock is preferred despite it's a link 3). I only run 2 Pascalus because we run many other extender which are not its target, 1 Mandarin because its condition is kinda situational. The rest is just extender or staple with the trap lineup to turbo out Marincess Wave since Blue Tang cant search it consistently enough while still running another great target for Trap Trick. Pros: Super consistent, big immune body, great recursion, bunch of handtraps, and can even run Deep Sea Minstrel (to snipe oppnent's handtrap). Cons: Standard board is just big immune tower with no interruption, sometimes water/cyberse locked Cards to think of: Frog lineup (Marincess is a 2 cards combo, so adding another 2 cards combo engine conflicts with each other), Mermail Abyssteus-spike engine (it searches Sea Horse, but needs 2 water discards, at that point we could combo with those 2 cards instead of running this engine), Kaiju (Gameciel is a must for side deck), Abyss Dweller (great card, but needs consistent Pascalus to make it, and most deck can still play around Dweller easily).

deck_description:
https://youtu.be/7vHJ93-VT4U Deck in action

Hello I would like to present my take on Adamancipators

What makes my version special:

  • No Fiber, Auroradon, Block Dragon, Linkross (Altho I do present Morph scopen fiber combo)

  • Focused on getting to excavate as much as possible in the first place rather then having 99% chance to reveal a rock as every list is (percentage is still high as fk). (I am long time morphtronic player and know how to threat excavate cards better then others)

  • 1 card synchro engines (some lock you into synchro summon) make the deck non normal reliant (Imagine a deck flooded with terrortops, tour guides..), This adamatia version handles going second well.

  • I am overall having a hard time seeing how is auroradon turbo version better... Best of it this version should be cheaper, and it is a definite future list (might be a secretly optimal list even today) once fiber x linkross x aura combination dies.

I individually edited Each Excavate to be faster Because EDOPRO excavates take 6-7 seconds each (Also accelerated phase shifting and BP attacks). So it should be enjoyable 17 mins to watch.

Questions are welcome: Yes I am running Crescent its almost a wind veiler, if format fits one can run Droll (Just dont find droll to good atm)
youtube link - https://youtu.be/rMVhINWWpsc

I present: my take on pure Crusadia post Eternity Code! I really like this build, hopefully so do you. Please leave feedback and help the Crusadia community out :)! Some comments overall: ** General comments / Main Deck **
  • I think Chaos Dragon Levianeer is just an insane card (you will see later on in my combos why). Multiple copies of it are live with any 2 starters/extenders in opening hand. You always have the option to use its Monster Reborn/pop 2 effect. If you dont like this card you might want to opt for multiples of Pot of Avarice, serving a similar purpose (that is, this deck can spam extra deck monsters like crazy).
  • This is a going 1st deck. The main strategy is a 1.5 combo with Formud Skipper (leave a comment if you want a more detailed description) that ends on Bagooska + omni negate from Equimax + Crusadia Krawler. If you survive the 1st turn, then turn 2 you activate Crusadia Krawler, search World Legacy Succesion, combo off (including a search for Crusadia Leonis for piercing damage) and you should have at least 8k damage on board. This combo can also be achieved by Chaos Dragon Levinaar + lvl 4 Crusadia + any Crusadia monster.
  • Crusadia really is a 15 card engine. This allows for the inclusion of a bunch of handtraps (no coincidence they are light and dark monster ofc, wink wink Chaos Dragon) and cards like Cosmic Cyclone. I have always been a fan of this card against pretty much any deck (e.g. Salamangreat, backrow, even decks like Cyber Dragon), but it is particularly good this format ofcourse.
  • Parallel Exceed is why this deck works (hence the post ETCO). You run 3 + 2 + 2 copies (Formud Skipper/Cynet Mining) of this card. Any Crusadia monster + this card is full combo. Also note the Linguriboh in the extra deck for the easy link climb/backrow matchup.
** Extra deck **
  • Crusadia Magius is nuts. Really. Any 2 cards allows you to bring all of them on the field/in the GY, making room to abuse Chaos Dragon Levianeer or similar cards.
  • Link Spider for when you get Nibirud! They Nibiru you, you link into Link Spider and you can extend with the Crusadia Monsters :).
  • Crystron Needlefiber is new too! When you have Crusadia Arboria on the field + any link monster, you can do the ``standard'' link climb, but have an intermediate Needlefibre in between. This results in 2 Arboria in GY, which means better grind game. Seems pretty good to me!
  • Topologic Trisbaena is NUTS! Its super easy to make in this deck, not OPT, and can be chain blocked with Crusadia Krawler. Is pretty much an instant win against any backrow heavy deck.
** Side Deck **
  • Kaiju package for going 2nd (I mean, it is Crusadia after all...).
  • Heavy Storm Duster is nice for backrow/Mystic Mine matchup ofcourse.
  • TCBOO because this deck can play it.
Leave suggestions and comments below! Crusadia players are STRONG!

This is just a pure version of madolche. I like to make decks that specialize in pure/mono archtypes. This deck looks like it bricks, but honestly, its bricked once in like 20 games.  Combo is as follows (turn 2 otk):  Magiline>get madolche petingcessoeur>Special it out, summon puddingcess>xyz magiline and pudding into souffle, use souffle to detatch magiline (but don't shuffle in)> xyz A-la-mode> shuffle in magiline, detatch puddingcess to summon anjelly> sack anjelly to bring hootcakes>hootcakes banishes souffle>bring out gellato, search field>play field, detatch puddingcess from a-la-mode to summon a second gellato>get ticket, play it>make tiramisu, bounce some stuff>can summon another gellato if you still have hootcake/want more spell traps, or you can summon puddingcess which is quite strong on her own>if you brought out gellato/any other 4 star, you can make another tiramisu if need be, you can make her into another chocolate a-la-mode,  between two ala-modes, sistart+whatever is left on your field you can OTK easily.  There is variants to set up defensive walls and prepare for another turn if you go first, you can make a nice wall. Madolche lesson is quite live in this build, but it becomes a bit of a win more card since your field is probably already OTK worthy, though I've had times where a well timed lesson bumps all my monsters when opponent thought they could clear some of them. Nobody ever expects lessons, cus nobody plays it, even though it works so well in this deck. I don't wanna go through more stuff, cus this is my favorite deck, and I won't be heart broken if it stays as a personal gem of mine.

Another pure deck, since I love them. I was disappointed in other "pure lightsworn" decks as...well they weren't really all that pure. The strategy with this is about the same as it always has been with lightsworn, win by turn 5 or lose. You can save yourself some grief if you wanna add beckoning light(s) to the deck, also people are afraid to have lightsworn at 40, but you don't really have to fear much. If JD gets negated/dies/etc. your other win condition is the actual lightsworn dragon which gets really beefy in this build. Shira does too for that matter. Just be careful not to charge of the brigade judgment traps, as they won't work then, same thing if you mill them with celestia's effect.

deck_excerpt: A very pure crystal beast deck
deck_description: Following my theme of making pure decks, this is one of the first "pure" decks I made. This is (no pun intended) a very special gem to me, as I don't think a lot of people realize just how strong this deck is with its own archtype. People keep adding cards outside the archtype, throwing in unnecessary traps or spells and it actually slows the deck down a lot. I used to shock people that I could even get out rainbow dragon as consistently as I did, and that was well before cards like crystal bond, conclave, ultimate magic (I had a high speed version that utilized advanced dark). Point is, there is a surprising amount of synergy in the cards alone, I can't say this can keep up with meta decks these days, but its still way faster than it used to be and really consistent. Getting out a turn two rainbow dragon is not hard, by turn 4+ you definitely have a few ways to win, whether its rainbow dragon, ultimate dragon, or abundance OTK. This is only going to get faster with Zenith coming out, although I'm hard pressed to figure out what to cut from this since the ratios are super perfect as is. (maybe one ruins, one bridge?)
Have fun

deck_excerpt: Do your best to end on a rank 4 and back it up with either rage or roar
deck_description: This deck makes use of a few new tech available in ETCO: Parallel Exceed and Accesscode Talker. Exceed allows you to easily make a rank 4, which can be vital vs Adamancipator and Eldlich, but it also gives you Accesscode Talker, a wonderful new link that you can climb into for a nigh unstoppable new OTK. Some new additions to the deck are Formud Skipper, and One for One to summon it. Formud Skipper acts as your way to search Exceed thus increasing its consistency. I'm running 3 copies of exceed since you want to see it every hand and im running desires so we dont want to risk banishing the other copy. Due to Adamancipator and Eldlich, hand traps are not very recommended due to their low impact. The 2 best ones to main deck are Ash Blossom since it can block all of the Eldlixers as well as both Gallant Granite & Block Dragon. We also main deck Lancea to stop Eldlich's advantage engine and to deny Adamancipators the chance to summon block dragon.

Plunder Patroll originated in IGAS. the yugioh player base was excited and hoped for a TCG exclusive that wasn't a disaster. they hoped that the deck wont become another abusable deck or engine like Danger! and wished it didn't flop like Vendread and F.A.  after the second wave of support the deck looks hopeful. it is a fun deck, it wont tear up the meta but sometimes all we need is a fun deck.  this is a control varient of the deck due to the lack of cards for the deck, you could use it as an engine or core for a control deck.

This is an edit on the Giant Skyhawk's list. using the powerful survival's end card and oviraptor to overwhelm the opponent with card advantage. if that doesn't work you could use UCT for an otk. if a paleo card is in the gy activating survival's end and chaining the paleo gives you the extra pop and summon of the effect.

deck_excerpt: Nostalgia GX deck made competitive. Able to summon both Evil Hero Dark Gaia/Malicious Bane and Fossil Fusion with only Stratos + 1 earth lv4 monster,
deck_description: Happy Revenge of the Fifth day! Who would have thought that both Evil HERO and Fossil still have synergy in 2020 and is viable? Reminsicing the time we were playing in GX Tag Force or watching the anime, Supreme King was a tough guy to beat with his big Evil HERO Dark Gaia, while Jim Crocodile Cook was having his Fossil Fusion exclusive in the game and anime only, until now. Also so many new cards printed, making this build consistent and able to put big damage or break board in one turn going second. I will explain the combo and lineup here. What we need is Elemental HERO Stratos + any earth lv4 monster, so we play E - Emergency Call, Solid Soldier (or Heroic Challenger Assault Halberd, pretty good if going second), and RotA to make it consistent. Combo is very simple, we search Addusted Gold via Stratos, use Addusted search Dark Calling, make Gallant Granite add Gigantes by detaching earth material, ss Gigantes make Verte (now we have 2 rocks in GY, Gallant and Gigantes). We can use Dark Calling to fusion for Dark Gaia or Malicious Bane if we have lv5+ in hand and we can use Verte to copy Fossil Fusion since we have rock in GY (some Fossil monster needs opponent's monster in GY as material). HERO lineup: 3 Stratos, 2-3 Solid Soldier, 2 Addusted Gold, 1 Shadow Mist (Foolish Burial target, to search), 3 Emergency Call, 2 Dark Calling (can add Dark Fusion too if you want), and RotA. Assault Halberd has hero too in its name being Heroic Challenger (lol jk, its just free lv4 earth monster). Fossil lineup: 2 Weathering Soldier (Foolish Burial target, searching Fossil Fusion), 2-3 Fossil Fusion (I only play 2 cus we have Verte and many other searchers), 2 Miracle Rupture (2 cus once per turn, dumps Weathering Soldier to GY), 1 Time Stream (Weathering Soldier target, super reliant on Fossil monster). Other Support: 2 Nibiru 1 Kongrade (Running 3 Nibiru is an overkill and most combo deck can play around it; Kongrade is just another useful big atk and lv rock monster, despite being situational), 2 Radian Kaiju (useful big atk and lv fiend monster), Gigantes (combo piece while being a lv4 monster, can be replaced with Adamancipator Researcher), Nemeses Keystone (recycles banished card and itself while being rock monster, you can cut it since it will rarely used), Foolish Burial (self explanatory), Extra-Foolish Burial (to trigger the Fossil monster GY effect, utility card), Double or Nothing (OTK if has the opportunity), and the rest is just breaking board card or handtrap. Extra Deck: 2 Skullgar (playing 2 cus its the easiest to summon while can be sent to GY for searching Fossil Fusion), 2 Malicious Bane (best Evil HERO). Pros: Nostalgic, consistency is "acceptable", able to break board or prevent opponent from building board, big monsters, and can even OTK. Fossil Fusion is free against Adamancipator. Cons: 2 cards combo, super fragile, recursion is almost nothing, sometimes unable to put lethal damage (esp. when we use Malicious bane effect making us unable to atk except with HERO monster). PS: the 1 card missing is Nemeses Keystone
ATAQUE

deck_excerpt: Arcana Fore XXI: The World + Frog the Jam FTK/OTK
deck_description: This deck uses the Six Samurai loop to summon Arcana Force XXI: The World while you have Light Barrier on the field. The reason it is a Frog the Jam FTK/OTK is because you use him to get the final blow. Make sure you summon The World, Frog the Jam, and Grandmaster of the Six Samurai under Saryuja's arrows so they get the attack boost. Tribute both Legendary Six Samurai Kizan on the end phase of your turn to skip your opponent's turn with The World's effect, then summon them back on your next turn. Make sure the two Kizans don't gain Saryuja's ATK boost. Attack with the two Kizans to do 3600, The World to do it 3400 (with Saryuja's boost), then attack with Frog the Jam to do the last 1000 (he also has Saryuja's boost).  NOTE: Use Saryuja's 2nd eff to summon The World and Frog the Jam. If you run out of Saryujas in your extra deck, use your current Saryuja to make a Cross-Sheep, use two Kizans to make an Emeral, then shuffle the 3 Saryujas back with Emeral's effect. The side deck is completely optional.
