deck_excerpt: A Cyber Dragon deck that revolves around the synergy between Jizukiru, Chimeratech, and handtraps to make room for an OTK with Rampage Dragon. Can fal
deck_description: So basically the goal of this deck is to OTK, while opening up cards that can either OTK your opponent straight out or enough cards to stun your opponent while you set up. Jizukiru is a must because of the interaction to Kaiju your opponents biggest threat and contact fuse to get a free Sieger. Effect Veiler/Impermanence are the other cards you'll open up with to disrupt your opponent during their setup. I really don't know if this is meta-worthy or meta-killing but I have something good here that I want to share and get advice to make this deck even better. I'll go through each card choices, this list is by no-means end-all. I just took the best Cyber Dragon builds I saw on YouTube and took what I liked from all of them and made this. EDIT: By the end of this guide I modified the deck a little bit, I took out Stardust for Volcasaurus and   Main Deck x40 Monsters x23 3x Jizukiru - A Kaiju. Main decking 3 because it' s a machine to go into Chimeratech with only 1 normal summon of any of your Snakes (I call the little Cyber Dragons this) 3x Cyber Dragon - Released in Cybernetic Overload, he is a welcome support card and is a must-run to run at 3. Fans have been asking about this for YEARS and we finally got it. 2x Galaxy Soldier - Honestly wanna run 3 but I don't want to see him that much, 3 feels like it limits what I can do with my other cards I draw into. 3x Cyber Dragon Vier - Super good to get you into your links and get more bodies on the board. Weird interactions with this card, beware. You normal any Snake that you wanna Machine Duplication, hold this in your hand. He will boost the ATK of your Cyber Dragons and lock you out of Machine Dupe. Go right ahead and use him after using Machine Dupe since you already resolved it. Doing so will net you an Infinity with the 2 Cyber Dragons straight outta the deck and a Verte Anaconda/Sieger to do whatever. He's super useful and good discard fodder as well. Can fuse with Jizu and be dumped with Rampage Dragon if you want to minimize drawing into him later. 3x Cyber Dragon Core - Little snake here techs you into Cyber Repair Plant (Which with your link 1's, you can send him to the graveyard and immediately use it now since you meet the requirements of the card, searching your Kaiju (seriously this thing being Light AND Machine is stupid synergy) Galaxy Soldier, or anything else you need that's Light and Machine). Nova lets you search Cyber Emergency, Revsystem, or if you have a board you can search Cybernetic Overflow which is one of the few traps that might actually be decent to even set on the field. I'll explain this later. He also searches Cyberload Fusion but you wanna keep that in the deck for Verte Anaconda. 3x Cyber Dragon Nachster - Can ditch another card from your hand to summon itself from the hand. If you ditch a Cyber Dragon you summon Nachster and revive Cyber Dragon. You just summoned two Cyber Dragon monsters for free. You can ditch Herz to trigger his effect, a useless hand trap, an extra kaiju, whatever. He's deceptively bad but his interactions let you set up the graveyard for the next card. 3x Cyber Dragon Herz - His 2nd effect (Hard Once Per Turn) where if it's sent to the graveyard you can add a "Cyber Dragon" (hard quotes, the named monster) from your GY or Deck to hand is really good. Beware, none of your Snakes are treated as "Cyber Dragon" in the deck, but the ones we run are treated as such in the graveyard. So if you dump him you can get back Nachster, Core, OG Cyber Dragon, or a Vier for whatever you need at the time. He can be dumped via Rampage Dragon. Specifically, Rampage Dragon lets you dump 2 Light Machines so you can send Herz and then a Snake you want to add to your hand that you can't search from your deck otherwise. Rampage, dump Herz and Vier/Core/Nachster and add that to your hand with Herz' effect. 3x Effect Veiler - Recently I threw out Ghost Ogre for this. So when I open up with Impermanence(s) and Veiler(s) I get multiple field negates from hand on my opponents turn. You basically run 6 field negates, and odds are in your favor for opening up with this or a Kaiju to start ruining your opponents board. It's also a tuner, but the only synchro I have in the extra deck is Stardust when I ran Ghost Ogre in the extra deck for the sided Ghost Ogre because Infinity + Stardust comes up a lot. Spells x12 1x Overload Fusion - Running the 1-of I got the idea from a video, I can't remember but I give credit for whoever came up with the 1x Overload and Cyberload and 1x Verte Anaconda. You run the 1 so you don't draw it and can use it from the deck using Verte Anaconda. 2x Cyber Revsystem - Good combo piece when establishing a board. Searchable and Protects whatever you just summoned. Bring back a Sieger. If this card could bring back Infinity (I wish) easily a 3-of. 3x Cyber Emergency - This card is searchable by Nova due to it being a "Cyber" card. What this card does is search for a "Cyber Dragon" monster. Specifically, Cyber Dragon, Vier, Nova, Nachster, Herz. 3x Machine Duplication - Only works with Core/Nachster/Herz, but you can summon out 2 Cyber Dragons from your deck due to the name interaction. Beware of summoning out Vier before using this card. Vier, like I said before, boosts your monsters and disables you from using Machine dupe since your monsters need to be under 500 atk. Vier boosts by 500 atk/def and the lowest atk is Herz at 100, totaling at 600 atk. So, use machine dupe and spit out the 2 Cyber Dragons AND THEN summon Vier. This is important since you have 4 monsters on the field by having a snake, dupe, and vier. Which can go into Anaconda/Sieger/Infinity/whatever you wanna accomplish. 2x Cyper Repair Plant - Good amount because it's searchable. Both of it's effects are good, but it's first effect lets you search for Light Machine monsters. Which counts Jizukiru, and Galaxy Soldier. 1x Cyberload Fusion - Never really want to use this first unless you can make an Infinity through Rampage being level 5 for an XYZ. Your 2nd Fusion card for your 2nd copy of Rampage if the first one doesn't secure the OTK. Recycles your Field/Banished cyber dragons to fuse, and is a Quickplay. Usable from the deck by Verte Anaconda. No matter where this is, it's live. Except first turn, oh well.   Traps x5 3x Infinite Impermanence - It's Impermanence. Useful from hand if you have to go 2nd, disrupts your opponent who's setting up their board going first. Makes this deck win no matter what turn we go. This and Veiler give you 6 negates in the deck. 2x Cybernetic Overflow - Extremely good removal effect and even lets you set up for Cyberload Fusion. If you brick you can at least search this card to have a Nova and this set to disrupt. AND, and, if it's popped you can search for a Cyber Spell/Trap. So you are f*****g your opponent when this is set regardless.   Extra Deck x 15 (ohohoho here we go) 2x Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon - They really released Chimeratech Fortress Dragon that can contact fuse with 1 or both Extra Monster Zones. Absorb your opponents Apollousa or whatever the hell they put and contact fuse with a little snake, granted you can still normal summon. If not you should lose, but regardless, this thing is really good. 1x Cyber Twin Dragon - Rarely sees play but is there when needed. Can attack twice and if it's boosted with Sieger, turns into a 4900 double swing for a total of 9800 damage. 2x Chimeratech Fortress Dragon - Honestly the whole reason I even started this deck was because the Jizukiru/Snake/ChimeraFort interaction. Every monster in your deck that's named Cyber Dragon on the field can absorb Jizukiru. As Seth from Street Fighter would say, "Become a part of me!" cause your opponents board is your 7th monster zone. This is also just a good card if you just wanna contact fuse in a huge Beater and boost it further with Sieger, or just BM and absorb it with Infinity. This deck is deeply synergistic with itself. 2x Chimeratech Rampage Dragon - You get 2 chances tops to OTK your opponent, so run 2. When it's summoned you can pop backrow up to the number of monsters used to fusion summon this guy. Overload/Cyberload can allow you to pop multiple BOARDS worth of backrow TBH, so this card is busted in the hypothetical situation where you're in a 2v1/3v1 or Free For All duel. Also allows itself to dump Light Machines from the deck to gain additional attacks for each monster sent to the GY (dumping a Herz and another snake you wanna search from your GY to your Hand, or just dumping Viers/Galaxy Soldiers/Kaijus just sitting in your deck). That's all it does, and all it needs to do. It's also a Dark Level 5. Go into Infinity if you couldn't finished them off for a board, or make Volcasaurus to pop their board and their lifepoints. Rank 5 cowboy. 1x Stardust Dragon - I honestly had this in when I was running Ghost Ogre, since Cyber Dragon and Rampage were level 5 and can make a Stardust with it. But you can run a Volcasaurus instead for 2 good reasons. 1, if you couldn't finish off your opponent or they had too many monsters, make this and burn them more MP2. 2, it's a rank 5 cowboy and live more often than making a Stardust, that's IF you side in ghost ogre. Do whatever you want. I changed this card as I was writing this deck build guide. 1x Cyber Dragon Infinity - Negates 1 effect per turn and can Honor Ark your opponents monster. This is it's deck that it will get it's most potential brought out, being it's the archetype it comes from. Now you can not feel like a jerk for using this card, cause you're running it's archetypal deck haha. 1x Cyber Dragon Nova - Has actual interaction with the deck because it was made for this deck. Nova wasn't invented to go into Infinity in meta decks, silly. (1) Can Special Summon a Cyber Dragon from your GY by detaching 1 card,(2) can also banish a "Cyber Dragon" card from your hand or field (your little snakes on the field) to boost NOVA another 2100 atk until the end of the turn. (3) if it's sent to the GY from the field by your opponents card effect, you can just bring out any machine fusion monster from your extra deck. I even forgot about this effect as I was writing this guide TBH, throw in a Barbaroid, The Ultimate Battle Machine for the LULZ. 1x Cyber Dragon Sieger - My friend Siegfried here is treated as a Cyber Dragon face-up or in GY, so it interacts with a lot of cards notably Revsystem to revive OTK potential. Busted. If it hasn't attacked in the BP yet, you wanna boost your Rampage another 2100 attack so it can swing 4200 x3 times. We don't play nice in this format. Nobody takes damage involving Sieger, which isn't good or bad but useful to know. This is bad if you wanna swing directly with Sieger, because neither player takes damage. If you attack a monster and you maybe boosted itself or another card, you don't take damage from Utopia the Lightning or Honest. So it works both ways. I think. Double check this. 1x Predaplant Verte Anaconda - It's so busted it can make any monster on the field a Dark Monster. It can also use "Fusion" or "Polymerization" normal or quickplay cards from the deck at the cost of 2000 LP too. Jokes aside, you can't special summon for the rest of the turn after using this, so get whatever monsters you wanna get out before using this effect that turn. It's really good. 1x Linkuriboh - If you open up a hand where you only have Herz or another level 1 cybersnake, you can summon it and send it to link summon into this so you can get a cyber dragon in the grave for maybe Repair Plant, or to get Herz on the field into GY to get a search. It helps bricks. Which is really good. 1x Salamangreat Almiraj - Super good protection, easy to bring out. Beware you have your <1000 atk monster be normal summoned. 1x Gravity Controller - Decent option, can't be destroyed by battle from main monster zone monsters, also bounces your opponents extra monster zone monster if it battles it.   Side Deck x ?? 15x Whatever - I don't know what to put in so whatever best gets you out of lockdowns should your opponent ever side for Cyber Dragons for some reason. IDK.
haha

Now you can not feel like a jerk for using this card, cause you're running it's archetypal deck haha. 1x Cyber Dragon Nova - Has actual interaction with the deck because it was made for this deck. Nova wasn't invented to go into Infinity in meta decks, silly. (1) Can Special Summon a Cyber Dragon from your GY by detaching 1 card,(2) can also banish a "Cyber Dragon" card from your hand or field (your little snakes on the field) to boost NOVA another 2100 atk until the end of the turn. (3) if it's sent to the GY from the field by your opponents card effect, you can just bring out any machine fusion monster from your extra deck. I even forgot about this effect as I was writing this guide TBH, throw in a Barbaroid, The Ultimate Battle Machine for the LULZ. 1x Cyber Dragon Sieger - My friend Siegfried here is treated as a Cyber Dragon face-up or in GY, so it interacts with a lot of cards notably Revsystem to revive OTK potential. Busted. If it hasn't attacked in the BP yet, you wanna boost your Rampage another 2100 attack so it can swing 4200 x3 times. We don't play nice in this format. Nobody takes damage involving Sieger, which isn't good or bad but useful to know. This is bad if you wanna swing directly with Sieger, because neither player takes damage. If you attack a monster and you maybe boosted itself or another card, you don't take damage from Utopia the Lightning or Honest. So it works both ways. I think. Double check this. 1x Predaplant Verte Anaconda - It's so busted it can make any monster on the field a Dark Monster. It can also use "Fusion" or "Polymerization" normal or quickplay cards from the deck at the cost of 2000 LP too. Jokes aside, you can't special summon for the rest of the turn after using this, so get whatever monsters you wanna get out before using this effect that turn. It's really good. 1x Linkuriboh - If you open up a hand where you only have Herz or another level 1 cybersnake, you can summon it and send it to link summon into this so you can get a cyber dragon in the grave for maybe Repair Plant, or to get Herz on the field into GY to get a search. It helps bricks. Which is really good. 1x Salamangreat Almiraj - Super good protection, easy to bring out. Beware you have your <1000 atk monster be normal summoned. 1x Gravity Controller - Decent option, can't be destroyed by battle from main monster zone monsters, also bounces your opponents extra monster zone monster if it battles it.
Side Deck
Thunder Dragons are maybe meta again?
Just have fun

This archetype is full of powerful fiend type pendulum monsters with their respected monsters waiting within the extra deck and was used, and not to mention mastered, by none other than Leo Corporations Leo Akaba. (I honestly have a D/D deck myself but I do not have the full series)  Now... Here are a couple of boss monsters that I decided as this decks respective boss monsters:  D/D/D Doom King Armageddon:  This bad boy here is one that is to believe the most powerful pendulum card of its series (excluding the extra deck monsters.)  It has a grand total of 3000 attack points but a low point total of 1000 defense points.  However, the loss in defense points can be greatly protected by its special ability (Which is why I put three.)  When it or other monsters are destroyed (either by battle or card effect), you can choose one of the destroyed monsters and add its attack points to the rest of your monsters. This is specifically why I put three of these guys in.  Extra deck boss monsters:  It was a four-way-tie between D/D/D Super Doom King Bright Armageddon, D/D/D Super Doom King Purple Armageddon, D/D/D Super Doom King Dark Armageddon, and D/D/D Oracle King d'Arc.  For the Super Doom King's, each one of them tends to protect each other (like Declan said during his last duel with Yuya) and especially against non-pendulum and pendulum type monsters. The only reason why I added d'Arc in was for its special ability in which it can convert damage you would have taken into life points from the Dark Contracts.

deck_excerpt: New Meklord supports coming made this build possible. Easy Emperor Wisel equipped with Dragon Buster or Winda, super consistent, great recursion, and
deck_description: Being quarantined makes Konami print good cards (loljk). Theres not much to explain in this combo as it's only a short one, and we have to work based on what's in our hand. Most of the times, we're trying to resolve Nucleus + Meklord Assembly for Emperor Wisel while having extender for Union Carrier (example, Obligato + Fortissimo field) or Winda via Dragma engine. The Dragma engine synergizes well with this deck, it contains Magicians Souls fodder while we can still recur it with Nadir from GY, great recursion and removal thanks to Shaddoll Ruq, Bastard, and N'tss. But while its combo is easy, we need to to pay attention to card interaction and restriction, making this deck prone to misplay and needs practice. Pros: Easy setup with spell negation, summon prevention, big monster, and possible protection. Great recursion thanks to Ruq and the new Meklord trap. Good going  second with removal and/or big damage. Cons: prone to misplay, main deck is super tight without handtrap/breaking board card (can be adjusted tho).

deck_excerpt: Dark Magician Control Deck for 2020 Format
deck_description: The Decks Simple stragery combined with cards for more consistent plays. Below are the reasons i run certain cards, The norm cards, i dont need to explain them like Rod, Dark Magic Circle and Eternal Soul.  Apprentice Illusion Magician is not as useful as it once was, however it still has its uses being a search for Dark Magician aswell as being a Honest for Dark Spellcasters. I also Run Kaijus because i prefer to be able to break down a players end board rather then stop single combos. If I wanted to run a second copy, id probably Drop Apprentice Illusion Magician.  Dark Magic Veil is a personal favorite of mine. it can extend your boar by summoning a Dark Spellcaster from either the GY or your hand!? All for the cost of 1000LP. For a more useful Monster reborn to either start, extend or recover your board, cant argue with that.  The Spellbook draw engine is used over other cards like Allure Of Darkness because i dont like the banishing requirements for allure. Aswell as Foolish Burial Goods, Upstart Goblin and Metalfoes Fusion for more deck thinning as well as draw power.  Along with Dark Magician Girl being included to utilize The Dark Magicians floating effect, Bond Between Teacher And Student is played for a added bit of spice and fun. However if you didnt wish to run them, you can always swap out for a 3rd copy of Super-Polymerization or other control cards.  Skill Drain in a Dark Magician Deck is a MUST! it has single handed won me a lot of games, so i cant recommend it enough.  Magicians Combination is one of those mar-mite cards, some like it, while others dont. I personally like it as it gives Dark Magicians a negate it needed. use it along side with Eternal Soul and even to protect Soul.  Beat Cop is another card used to protect your decks best and worst card. By tributing itself, (so even Skill Drain doesnt effect it) place a counter on Eternal Soul, now when ever it would be destroyed, you can remove the counter instead.  Hope you like the deck profile!

deck_excerpt: This is quite an easy deck to use. This deck is doesn't OTK often but has a far better board after a few turns with 1 to 2 behemoths set and and 3 to
deck_description: This deck is quite easy to use, here is what you do with each main card  Hidden city/Terraforming : (Search Hidden City), Activate Hidden City, Add Guru with effect (if already have Guru in hand add Fiendess (if already have Fiendess in hand add a Behemoth)), next Set Guru, Use Hidden City effect to flip guru to DEF, with guru add Fiendess (if already have Fiendess in hand either 1. Add another Fiendess 2. Add Final Battle (Better earlier game) 3. Add Cave Clash (Better later game)) If added spell or trap, activate or set it.  Fiendess : Fiendess can be discarded to negate an effect or activation (NOT a summon) of a card (Spell, Trap or Monster) while you have a face-up subterror during either players turn. It can also be Summoned to use its second effect to set 1 monster you control to Special Summon 1 Subterror from your GY or hand in either DEF position.  Guru : Guru's FLIP effect is to Search a Subterror CARD (Monster, Spell, or Trap) from your deck. He also has an effect to set another monster (on either field) and himself, this becomes a quick effect if you control another "Subterror" card (it must be a face-up card though but activating a Subterror trap then chaining Guru's effect does work).  Behemoths : When you use Guru's, Fiendess's 2nd effect, Final Battle, Hidden City, or another Behemoths effect to set a card you can Special Summon them from your hand (During either players turn) But you can't Summon them when Fiendess 1st effect sets a monster because it is a cost.  The Extra Deck : You don't have to use this combination of cards, you should just use your extra deck for banishing by the effect of Pot Of Extravagance, but it like this for that it can still be useful.  Handtraps and Solemn cards : These are pretty basic to use but here is a list of what is in here and what else you could use  Ash Blossom : If a card is moved from the deck to the GY, hand or Summoned to the field, you can discard this card to negate the activation, it can also negate effects that draw.  Ghost Belle : If card card is moved from the GY to the hand, deck, banished zone or Summoned to the field, you can discard this card to negate the activation.  Droll and Lock bird : If your opponent adds cards from their deck to their hand (drawing counts) EXCEPT during the Draw Phase you can discard this card to stop them from doing this for the rest of the turn (It does NOT stop them from adding the card you activate) Remember that this Also blocks YOU from doing the same for the rest of the turn.  Sauravis : If an effect TARGETS a monster a monster you control you can discard this card negate the activation, it also has the effect that while its in the GY, when your opponents Special Summon a monster(s) you can return this card to your hand to negate the summon and banished the would be Summoned monsters.  True King Lithosagym, the Disaster : This card can be summoned by by destroying 2 monster on your field and in your hand including a EARTH monster and if they were both EARTH monster you can banish 3 monsters from your opponents Extra Deck (you choose which monsters are banished), this can heavily disrupt your opponents plays.

Hello YU-GI-OH! community! Today, we will be taking a look at a deck that isn't as great, but has potential, what I mean, is Machina.   The Machina archetype are a group of machines that love discarding themselves to summon big beaters onto the field, here is a deck list that does provide less budget options   Budget Breaking options:  
  1. Put Pot of Desires for Iron Draw, since Iron Draw isn't as consistent at all, having a requirement that isn't hard to achieve, but, come on, Pot is a LOT better than Iron Draw
  2. Scrap engine. Since we run Scrap Recycler, 1/3 of the Scrap engine, why not splash in the rest of the bunch? I didn't include Scrap Golem because it is over 5$ per copy, being at either $11-$18 right now. Scrap Wyvern would be good extra deck for this deck and is just here for the Scrap engine.
  3. Mecha Phantom Beast O-Lion is a great extender and over all a great card you could include with this deck, since if you send it to the graveyard, it will give you a token, which is somewhat decent since Scapgoat got limited by just giving your four of those tokens.
  4. Jet Synchron is a decent budget card, not on the list for those cheap buy 3 and leave players in YU-GI-OH! Jet Synchron has the effect to special summon from the graveyard by sending one card in your hand to the graveyard, but its banished at the time it leaves the field.
  5. Interrupted Kaiju Slumber and any other kaiju (mainly Dogoran and Gameiciel perferably) would slip into this deck without a problem, maybe being your side deck since we have no side deck, go crazy with it!
  6. Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring with Twin Twisters and any other staple would make this deck have a decent competitive edge, since Ash is probably the best handtrap of the game's history and Twin Twisters for the backrow removal
    Well I hoped you enjoyed this decklist, thanks for looking at it, and I will see you card players next time!

deck_excerpt: A CyDra deck for Master Rule 5, taking advantage of Predaplant Verte Anaconda and built for the current Meta.
deck_description:
Posting this for the dual purpose of putting this deck out there for critique and to assist others in building a Cydra deck. This deck is built primarily for going second, however as this can't always be guaranteed, some cards have been side decked which would maximise the deck's potential.  <!--more--> Monsters: Cyber Dragons: Cyber Dragon - Run at three for the benefit of Machine Duplication, which remains the deck's win condition. Seeing this in the opening hand when going second isn't an issue given it's effect, however it can brick if going first and you have no other cards to assist in bringing it out. Cyber Dragon Core - The deck's main starter and MVP, ran at three. When summoned, this will, if uninterrupted by your opponent, will add 1 "Cyber" spell/trap to your hand. This card's secondary effect (activated in the Graveyard) can also help reconstruct your board if your opponent has cleared your side of the field monsters, by bringing a Cyber Dragon monster from your deck to your hand at the cost of banishing Core from the Graveyard. Target #1 for Machine Duplication. Cyber Dragon Herz - Again, ran at three as this is a Machine Duplication target. Both effects are useful, although you are far more likely to get mileage out of Herz mid-game when special summoned for Rank 5 XYZ plays. This card also synergises well with Galaxy Soldier, given Galaxy Soldier's special summoning condition of discarding a light monster, this card brings a "Cyber Dragon" to the hand to facilitate the special summon of the second Galaxy solider - instant XYZ summon into Cyber Dragon Nova. Cyber Dragon Nachster - Ran at two, as this is the only Machine Duplication target that can brick on turn 1; without another monster (preferably a Cyber Dragon) or Machine Duplication in hand, this is as good as useless. This card really shines when your Graveyard is filled with Machine monsters with the magical 2100 ATK or DEF value, however be wary that once activated you can no longer special summon non-Machine monsters for the remainder of the turn. Cyber Dragon Vier - Suprisingly useful link-fodder and a helpful chain-blocker for Cyber Dragon Core. I've heard of people running this at more than one for these reasons, however if this was the sole monster in my hand on Turn 1, I'd be very disappointed. Given that this is also not a Machine Duplication target, I would not advise having more than two in the deck. Other monsters: Galaxy Soldier - A Cyber Dragon in all but name. This is the go-to card to make Cyber Dragon Infinity as it leaves your ordinary Cyber Dragons available for other uses. Synergises with Cyber Dragon Herz very well and is searchable through Cyber Repair Plant. In addition, if you have already summoned Chimeratech Rampage Dragon and these remain floating in your deck (a brick waiting to be drawn), these are ideal cards to discard to grant Rampage the additional attacks. Ran at two, as three increases the likelihood that multiples could be drawn and bricking on turn 1. Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju - Ideal for removing a troublesome opposing monster (think Apollousa) and is easily removable thanks to Chimeratech Fortress Dragon. Searchable through Cyber Repair Plant. Ran at one, however this is a very good candidate to increase to two. Chaos Dragon Levianeer - Easily accessible beatstick in the mid-late game, 3000 ATK is not to be sniffed at. The banishing summoning condition synergises with the deck very well and comes with a built in Monster Reborn-effect for additional link-fodder. As it is 8 stars, this also can be used as material for the XYZ summon of Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star. This card can brick and therefore is ran at one. If you are not running Dingirsu, I would suggest replacing this with another copy of Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju. Handtraps: These are primarily a reflection of the current meta and can be adjusted accordingly without affecting the engine.
  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring - Ran at two, due to the 'once per turn' condition.
  • D.D. Crow - Can be increased to three, if you can find the space
Spells: Cyber Emergency - The ROTA of the deck, with built in protection at the cost of a discard. Ran at three. Cyber Repair Plant - An extender that relies on you having at least one "Cyber Dragon" in the GY. Searches the majority of the monsters in the Main Deck (excepting Levianeer and the Hand Traps), however is a hard once per turn and given the prerequisite, I wouldn't advise increasing to three copies. Cyber Revsystem - Another useful extender; Monster Reborn for "Cyber Dragon" with the bonus option of allowing you to special summon a Cyber Dragon from the hand. Not particularly useful for your Extra Deck Monsters (barring Cyber Dragon Sieger), however you have Nachster to bring them back from the GY. Could increase to two, however I prefer having a copy of Monster Reborn. Machine Duplication - Your win condition. Target one "Cyber Dragon" with less than 500 ATK, special summons two Cyber Dragons from the deck. If this resolves, it's usually game over. Having this at three does make the deck very bricky, however given the risk/reward involved, the benefit outweighs the cost. Overload Fusion - Facilitates your OTK. Ran at two because although you want to see this card, having multiples in hand at the cost of an extender is not fun. The only target is Chimeratech Rampage Dragon, however it's the only one you really need. Cyberload Fusion - Quick play fusion card that also can facilitate an OTK, for the purpose of bringing out Cyber Twin Dragon or Rampage. In terms of using it, this is best activated during the battle phase, after all other monsters have attacked, bring out Cyber Twin Dragon for 5600 points of damage. Foolish Burial - Staple for seeding the GY and activating Repair Plant. Monster Reborn - Useful as an extender and to bring back boss monsters in a pinch. Upstart Goblin - Consistency boost. A small boost, but one worth having. Traps: Cybernetic Overflow - Great card. Maximum 4 cards popped on your opponent's side of the field and if destroyed by card-effect, you can search another "Cyber" Spell/Trap from your deck. Sided an additional copy for going first. Banishes Cyber Dragons to set up for Cyberload Fusion. Red Reboot - Wins you games! Evenly Matched - A particularly nasty way of clearing the opponent's board. It might stop you from OTKing on Turn 2, but it's definitely worth running at three! Extra Deck: Chimeratech Fortress Dragon - Useful to dispose of your Kaiju, and wiping the field clean in mirror matches or the occasional Orcust deck. Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon - Snatches opponent's monsters out of the Extra Monster Zone, what's not to love? Chimeratech Rampage Dragon - Insanely powerful card. Has the potential to act as a Harpie's Feather Duster (depending on the number of monsters used for its Fusion Summon) and can attack three times. Ran at two as I'm running two Overload Fusions. Cyber Twin Dragon - No matter how tempted you may be to cut this card from the Extra Deck, don't. This card is a game winner if brought out with Cyberload Fusion during the battle phase. Artifact Durendal - My personal preference over Constellar Pleiades. Cyber Dragon Nova - Ran at one, as you only need the one thanks to Nachster. Cyber Dragon Infinity - Best card to bring out when forced to go first. Can suck up an opposing monster and provides a negate. Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star - Provides a negate where your cards would be destroyed and can pop an opponent's card upon its Special Summon. Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess - Potential 3200 ATK and provides four negates, a budget alternative would be Borrelsword Dragon. Cyber Dragon Sieger - Built in Limiter Removal, best used in conjunction with Chimeratech Rampage Dragon Knightmare Phoenix - Because I hate backrow, particularly floodgates. Predaplant Verte Anaconda - Searches Overload Fusion and Cyberload Fusion! Salamangreat Almiraj - Turns on Cyber Repair Plant and provides protection for Extra Deck Monsters Side Deck: Heat Wave - Cyber Dragon hates going first, however this card shuts down most decks by stopping Effect Monsters from being summoned until your next draw phase, giving you an opportunity to OTK on turn 3 Different Dimension Ground - For mirror matches and to really mess with decks that rely on the GY Lightning Storm - Going second staple, Harpie's Feather Duster + Raigeki. Budget alternatives: Dark Hole, Cosmic Cyclone, Twin Twisters Dark Ruler No More - Going second, helps break boards by nullifying monster effects. Fantastical Dragon Fantazmay - Sided in for when going up against combo decks to provide additional consistency and to provide an additional body for life point protection/link fodder Cyber Network - Interesting and underrated card, banishes LIGHT machines from the deck and returns them to the field on the earlier of Turn 3 after activation or once destroyed. Cybernetic Overflow - An additional copy to be sided in when going first.
D/D/D

deck_excerpt: Bald kommt ein neues Structure Deck heraus, wir schauen die Karten auf unseren Youtube Kanal an und machen daraus ein spielbares Deck.
deck_description: Bald kommt ein neues Structure Deck heraus, wir schauen die Karten auf unseren Youtube Kanal an und machen daraus ein spielbares Deck          Hier fehlt noch ein Raviel Heaven Crushing Fist er wird von der Website nicht richtig angezeigt.

Well, for sure the Asgard gods will be pleased with this build. I searched all web trying to find a good one for this deck, i didn't, so i made my own. I think that's the most consistent "meta" you can get. Offerings to the Gods:
  • Almost any hand will open with one Nordic monster, you will almost always use him as material for Gullveig.
  • Alviss is the best target for Gullveig effect, so if you have one in hand, don't use him as material for the link but as offering for the effect.
  • Rescue Cat can summon 2 Nordic Beasts from your deck, if you don't have any in your opening hand. Summoner Monk is another alternative aswell.
  • But what if i don't have it? Well you can easily abuse the tokens from Hippo Carnival. Simply chain Hippo Carnival to Gullveig effect and offer the tokens.
  • Make sure to dump the right Tuners in your GY! If summoning Odin, you want at least one Nordic Ascendant Tuner so go for Vanadis, if summoning Thor you want a Nordic Beast Tuner, so go for Guldfaxe.
Immortal Deities:
  • Gullveig offers protection from target effects to any Aesir god, if pointing to one, she can't be targeted for attacks aswell as long as it points to that god.
  • Mound of the Bound Creator will offer some extra protection if needed.
  • If any god goes to the GY while you have Alviss there, you can banish him to Summon another one directly from your Extra Deck.
  • And finally if destroyed by any opponent card and sent to the GY, each Aesir can come back during the EP by banishing the right Nordic Tuner.
Valhalla, Hall of the Gods:
  • The Extra Deck is very flexible, the only cards you really need are the Aesir Gods and Gullveig really.
Any suggestions just write down in the comments. You can also find my replays against some decks on my Dueling Book profile  _Theseus.   Now bring Ragnarok to your opponent, and make the gods smile with your victory!

deck_description:
Shaddolls are almost there with their strategies. Most may argue the best way to fix the deck is to slap in the invoked engine. Here I propose an alternative, not going into the expenses that are the invoked cards. The most annoying fact is not seeing enough fusion spell right out the gate, and this is where Vision Hero Vyon kicks in. Going first VARIATION 1 Step one: normal summon Vyon:
  1. Chain link 1: send shadow mist to GY;
  2. Chain link 2: search Honest Neos by activating shadow mist's effect;
Step two: activate Vyon to banish mist from GY to add poly to hand; Step three: fuse Neos + Wendi/Squamata to make Construct:
  1. Chain link 1: Construct effect, send Resh shaddoll Incarnation;
  2. Chain link 2: Wendi effect, sp. summon Ariel facedown or squamata effect, send wendi(chain link 3: activate wendi to special ariel facedown);
Step for: link construct for Gravity Controller:
  1. Chain link 1: Construct effect, add a Shaddoll fusion spell to hand;
Step five: Activate Resh, by banishing construct in GV to flip Ariel:
  1. Chain link 1: Ariel effect; sp. summon the banished construct in def. pos.;
Step six: make Abyss Dweller, by overlaying vyon and ariel; pass turn; opposing standby phase: activate Dweller to set GY negation;   Going first VARIATION 2 Step one: normal summon Vyon:
  1. Chain link 1: send shadow mist to GY;
  2. Chain link 2: search Liquid Soldier by activating shadow mist's effect;
Step two: activate Vyon to banish mist from GY to add poly to hand; Step three: fuse the Soldier + Vyon to make Sun riser:
  1. Chain link 1: Sun riser effect, search miracle fusion;
  2. Chain link 2:Draw 2 discard one by Soldier's effect;
Step four: make Absolute Zero with miracle fusion; Step four: make Construct with a Shaddoll monster + Sun riser; continue for additional plays depending on your hand...; pass turn;   Going first VARIATION 3 Step one: normal summon Mathematician;
  1. Chain link 1: Mathematician effect, send Damage Juggler (Step two: search trick colwn) or Hedchog (Chain link 2: search wendi/squamanta) to GY to add the missing fusion material;
Step two: fuse Light attribute + Wendi/Squamata to make Construct:
  1. Chain link 1: Construct effect, send Resh shaddoll Incarnation;
  2. Chain link 2: Wendi effect, sp. summon Ariel facedown or squamata effect, send wendi(chain link 3: activate wendi to special ariel facedown);
  3. *Chain link 3: pay 1000 to special summon Trick Clown on the field;
Step for: link Construct and Math for Verte Anaconda;
  1. Chain link 1: Construct effect, add a Shaddoll fusion spell to hand
Step five: Activate Resh, by banishing construct in GV to flip Ariel;
  1. Chain link 1: Ariel effect; sp. summon the banished construct in def. pos.
Step six: pay 2000 to activate Anaconda and send el shaddoll fusion to GY,  in order to make Winda with Ariel and Anaconda *or/and make Abyss Dweller, by overlaying Trick Clown and Ariel pass turn; *opposing standby phase: activate Dweller to set GY negation;

deck_excerpt: Negate and control your opponent's plays with Altergeists and floodgates.
deck_description: This deck is a stun control deck based on Altergeists. use spoofing to search anything you need and negate your opponent's plays. Use the floodgates to counter things that you can't stop with the main deck Altergeists. Occasionally you will come across the matchup where you need your extra deck. In that case, sub out extravagance for demise and the 3rd duality so you won't risk losing key cards to negate things the main deck can't. Be careful with when you activate Imperial order because you might drain too many life points to use the solemn cards. Sub in Waking the Dragon to get Raidraptor on the field to deal with heavy backrow removal decks. Also, if you have a choice, always go first because traps are slow and you should quickly setup your board before your opponent can react. My rating: Attack: 3/5 Defense: 5/5 Consistency: 4/5 Strong against: HERO, Mystic Mine Burn/Exodia Weak against: Harpies, Adamancipator Negate combos: Normal summon Meluseek Link it into 1 of  the link 1s (Linkuriboh, Almiraj, Anima) Linkuriboh will negate an attack so is preferable, however if you need to get rid of a troublesome monster you can use Anima. Activate Meluseek's GY effect, add Multifaker to the hand If you activate a trap during your opponent's turn you can do this: SS Multifaker with its effect (you can summon it even if you used a counter trap, see here) Activate Multifaker, summon Silquitous from the deck. if you would use Silquitous's effect bounce Multifaker Now you have an attack negate (if you used linkuriboh), a card bounce and a Meluseek in the GY, which you can then use Manifestation or Marionetter to SS it.   Set Spoofing facedown Normal summon Marionetter Activate its effect, set Manifestation End your turn. The real part of the combo starts during your opponent's turn. Activate Spoofing and shuffle Marionetter to get Multifaker to the hand. Activate Multifaker's effect, summoning itself from the hand. Activate Multifaker's second effect, summoning Silquitous from the deck. Basically most end boards are going to be Multifaker and Silquitous in the monster zones and a manifestation/protocol to be activated.   This deck is fun to play but very annoying to play against because of its disruptive ability to constantly negate your opponent's plays. I have played many online games with this deck and most of my opponents rage quit :P Anyways stay safe and have fun!

deck_excerpt: Fun combo deck made to play online because of the extra deck price. Incredibly consistent and suprisingly effective.
deck_description:
Main strategy The main strategy is summoning Borreload Savage Dragon while also having Crystron Halqifibrax and a level 1 tuner on the field. It doesn't matter if you didn't equip a link monster for your Borreload Savage because you might not even need it. On your opponent's Main Phase, banish the Halqifibrax with it's own effect to summon Shooting Riser Dragon, which on summon sends a D/D Savant Copernicus to the GY, making it's level 3. Then, you proceed with your combo by Synchro Summoning using Riser, a level 1 tuner and Borreload Savage to make the mistake known as Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity, which essentially locks your opponent out of playing Yu-Gi-Oh. Plan B, if something goes wrong Your goal should be putting up at least 3 negates on the field including a Borreload Savage Dragon, a D/D/D Cursed King Siegfried and an Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. Plan C, if your dreams get crushed Photon Strike Bounzer, Draco Berserker of the Tenyi, set random backrow and pray. Yeah that's cool and all but how do I even get to that? Basically 1 card. D/D Swirl Slime, the absolute star  of the show. It provides an easy and quick Fusion Summon, and an almost free special summon from your hand. You need other cards tho, and luckily they are easy to search out.
  1. If you have no Dark Contract With the Gate, normal summon D/D Savant Kepler to search it out.
  2. If you have Gate, search either of these cards, if you already don't have them: either of the two slimes, D/D Savant Copernicus or aD/D Lamia. Sometimes you'll fetch  D/D/D Chaos King Apocalypse, and I don't blame you for that.
  3. Fusion with the Swirl Slime into a D/D/D Flame King Genghis (or D/D/D High King Genghis if you can), then use the effect of Swirl Slime to special summon, triggering the Genghis effect to special summon a card used to fusion with the slime (prefferably a D/D Lamia).
  4. Link into either Cross-Sheep if you plan or going with the Fusion combos, or Halqifibrax for Synchro plays, prefferably both to set up a better board.
You can ask me the rest if you need help. WORST MATCHUPS
  • Necrovalley, you can't make a single play
  • Dinosaur, Lithosagym shuts this deck down, if picked the correct cards
  • Eldlich Invoked, only if they use Mechaba at the right moment, siding in those Cosmic Cyclones help with this
  • Mine/Sky Striker if sided inproperly

deck_excerpt: This deck was a mistake. I don't think there's much more to it. One of the most powerful meta decks combined with a 1-card Utopic Zexal and the abilit
deck_description: Out of all the previous adaptations of Yu-Gi-Oh!, Zexal is regarded as having one of the strongest monsters ever to be in the game. Not only in the anime - but even monsters of that period themselves, for example: Zoodiac. However, nothing compares to sheer base strength of Don Thousand's ace monster, Number C1000: Pneumonia....sorry, Numeronia. Nobody would ever dream that Konami would release a monster with base stat of 10,000! And well, they haven't. Yet. But as of now we just got a few other gate thingys from the anime (and boy are they strong). The four Numeron gate cards all allow you to summon Number S0: Utopic Zexal: and with them all being summonable off of just one field spell - Xyz Summoning, has never been better. I present to you: Numeron Eldlich. One of the best things about the Eldlich archetype as a whole is their ability to build up a board using a scarce amount of resources. With the Spells and Traps being able to switch between themselves, and Golden Lord using his effect to pitch them: you can still set up a competent board using the brickiest of hands, and have to enough to make a follow-up play the next turn. That's what makes this deck even better. This list allows you to end on your standard Eldlich board no problem. But what makes the new support cards worth it is the fact that - for almost 0 cost - you can lock your opponent out of activating effects for the rest of their turn. Having just the Utopic Zexal itself will give your opponent a hard time, but following that up with a pop from Conquistador and a Ash or Imperm will guarantee you victory. So now that the main strategy is out the way: here are some reasons behind why we play the cards we do. The focus of the deck is turboing out your four gate monsters as fast as possible. In order to do that - we have to run three copies of Numeron Network. You always want to see the card, so I'd recommend playing Terraforming and Set Rotation too for the added consistency. Another great card that allows you to really unclog your hand is Memories of Hope. Since all the gate cards are number monsters, Numeron Network followed up by Memories is a free draw four. That's incredibly good! The only possible downside is the card tends to brick in certain situations when you don't open one of the five copies of Numeron Network - but even then you can just use it as fodder for Golden Lord. The deck has that much consistency. The final thing I'd like to mention are the more situational cards you play. Since you don't run Extravagance - there are a few extra deck cards you can play. The obvious ones being the Rank 10 Trains and the Rank 5 removal monsters - but you also can run one copy of Chaos Gate Sunya. This is mostly a backup play just in-case your opponent somehow gets rid of Zexal with something like Lithosagym - but this could also just be a cheese way of OTK'ing your opponent. Its effect, in a few words, does a guaranteed 5000 burn damage on your next standby phase. Provided your opponent has 3000+ attack on field - you could kill them with just this card. Like I said, you most likely wont go into this, but it's just a fun play nonetheless. Overall: this deck drives forward with a strong 9.1/10. The fact that you can summon Utopic Zexal so freely and still make an Eldlich board is mind blowing. If we ever get these cards imported into the TCG - I hate to break it to you but Zexal will definitely be getting the ban treatment.  Its just too powerful of a card, especially paired with one of the strongest meta decks this format. One of the cards I never got to play test was definitely magicians' souls. I think that it could help unclog those bricky hands - but the only problem would be resolving your combo and getting it off the field. But since the ratios are perfect as they are and the deck already performs incredibly, I decided to leave it out. Apologies for my slightly long hiatus and the seemingly rushed deck discussion. I kinda lost the passion for deck building and focussed on studying and spending more time with family. To make it up to you though I'll be posting some spicy new lists for May 2020 that you could all try at home. Good luck playing yugioh as the new king of bling and don't forget to stay home. Happy Quarantine!

deck_excerpt: Mermail combo deck with Atlanteans, Deep Sea, and Frogs.
deck_description:
Focusing back on the Auroradon engine, since it's smaller and more powerful going first. I've freed up room for a bunch of combo plays you can extend with, and BLS for Eldlich. The main combo plays out like this
  1. Normal summon Deep Sea Diva, summoning Neptabyss
  2. Send Dragoons adding Dragoons and Deep Sea Minstrel
  3. Fire off Minstrel, discarding Dragoons to pull a card out of your opponent's hands and search Moulinglacia.
  4. Link into Needlefibre/Halqufibrax. summoning Jet Synchron. (This could be Deskbot 001. The plus is that you'd go +1 in the hand off of it, the minus is that it's a total brick if you ever see it)
  5. Special Moulinglacia. Hand loop is at 3.
  6. Synchro Jet Synchron and Moulinglacia into Ravenous Crocodragon, drawing a card. You can use it to help break boards as well going second.
  7. Discard a card to special Jet Synchron, then link it and Needlefibre away in Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon, summoning 3 tokens. Note that since we drew a card in the combo this is still hand neutral, and can be done off of 1 card.
  8. Tribute Auroradon and a token to summon Blue Impala
  9. Using Blue Impala and the tokens make Jaculuslan. This also makes Deep Sea Diva a 1 card 5 card hand loop. If you have 1 more water extender, you can tribute that instead of a token to hand loop your opponent for 4 at this point.
  10. Using your synchros, Xyz summon True King of all Calamities
You've now hand looped your opponent for 3-4, gained all the information you need, and set up a skill drain you can fire off in your opponent's standby phase. You can then use whatever other cards you have in your hand to extend into other plays. You can even link into Marincess Coral Anemone before making Auroradon in order to bring the hand loop up to 4/5 by summoning Needlefibre from your gy after the combo and banishing it for Desert Locusts. This uses only 5-7 cards in the extra deck to pull off (5 for the combo, plus Borreload Savage and Herald for additional Auroradon combos), freeing a lot of room up for old more traditional mermail combos compared to Linkross, which take 7-10 cards in the extra deck to do the same thing. This means Diva alone can end on 4 negates with Apollousa and Toad, or on Borreload Savage + Herald of the Arc Light, or True King of All Calamities (all taking cards from your opponents hand), or on a 5 card hand loop with Mecha Phantom Beast Jaculuslan.

deck_excerpt: Mythical Beast Endymion Pendulum Deck with tips.
deck_description: This deck is very versatile. It's very difficult to brick with it and the tuto is efficient. Made this deck because I love Endymion since his first release. Plan A : If you have Mythical Beast Master Cerberus in your hand, take a sit and it's winnable easily. Activate his effect in the pendulum zone to tuto Mythical Beast Jackal King. Activate his effect in pendulum zone and you got your Cerberus on the field. Try to activate magic card to feed him with counter and make him unkillable by using his effect. Plan B : Mythical Bestiary, use it like a booby trap. Plan C : Spell Power Mastery is a good tuto that can provide you counter on each magical/pendulum monster. Plan D : Endymion, The Mighty Master Of Magic can be summoned very easily when you set your field with 6 counter (mythical beast monster gain 2 per 2 counters on them), plus, his effect is truly a killing joke (I will loose some friendship if I continu to play it), indeed, you can banish 6 cards on the field of your ennemy. "Oh that's to bad" Last but not least : This deck can be played very easily, just seek what combo you want to do, is that pendulum summon with endymion's cards, is that tuto with mythical beast booby trap/mythical institution ? Or sacrifice your little magician to summon your beast from your hand ? Spellbook Magician of Prophecy is here to tuto some Spellbook or use the Magical Dimension card to summon what do you want from your hand. Little tips : If you were in a bad situation, don't forget your Xyz or Mystical Space Typhoon, Hey, Trunade! can provide you free counters by sending all spell, and save you from traps, in the hand. Spellbook of Secrets give you counters and Spellbook of Power, this is the most free counter tricks I saw lol. Don't forget to clean your pendulum side when you want to use mythical beast pendulum effect. Never forget your Magical Citadel of Endymion//Endymion's Lab, it's not a MUST HAVE, but it can give you rest for your counter. This is the first and only deck I really created by my own, I love how it works.

deck_excerpt: This deck attempts to appease the general issues with Evil-Eye by combining it with the immensely powerful Eldlich engine, while taking advantage of E
deck_description:
While the Evil-Eye engine has always been encroaching on viability it's particular weaknesses of being heavily normal summon reliant and resource intensive have kept it from relevance for a long while. Luckily, Secret Slayers gave us another control archetype, Eldlich. Eldlich has proven to be an extremely powerful and consistent deck that has an incredible grind game, and best of all-- it doesn't use it's normal summon what this allows us to do is essentially play two decks with one opening hand. The basic idea is that you will start off with your Evil-Eye plays and then follow up with Eldlich ones. Best case scenarios you're ending with a typical Eldlich board with an extra pop or negate, worse case scenario you baited your opponents hand-traps to secure your Eldlich plays. Pros:
  1. The Eldlixer cards are chain-able, so you can chain them to the activation of Serziel's maintenance cost to avoid losing advantage.
  2. Since after Domain's activation you do not really care if it stays on field, in fact very often, you want it in the grave to recycle Evil Eye of Selene it can be used as cost for Eldlich The Golden Lord's graveyard effect.
  3. Both deck's have a very similar play-style that boils down to: "Sit on a big monster with protection while putting up disruption for your opponent until you can pivot into your otk monster. " The decks hardly ever step on each other's toes, as they want to do similar things most of the time.
  4.  You get to play Eldlich.
Cons:
  1. Though the addition of Eldlich means the deck is wildly consistent, when it does brick it bricks pretty hard, typically when drawing too many Evil Eye's of Selene (hence the playing it at 2)

deck_excerpt: One card makes True King OF All Calamities, Herald Of Protection with four negates, and Utopia Double for OTKing. With Generaider as a backup strat, a
deck_description: So, enough people have been asking for the decklist of the one-Halq four-negates-and-VFD-and-OTK combo I came up with that I decided to upload the more refined version. Long story short: It's a very consistent lockdown that, once put up, could only be brought down with a SuperPoly... but because it's so weak to disruption, about half the deck is dedicated to a Generaider backup strategy and generic disruption of my own.  This is a more refined version of a decklist I posted about a month ago, with some big improvements in the decklist and none in the actual combo.  (Quick breakdown: 20 one-card combo starters, 9 generaider field spells, 14 bricks, 17 disruptions)  ----------------------------  Basically, the whole deck exploits that Halqifibrax is a pseudo-FTK from only one card, and there's so very many cards that do that. So:  -60 cards instead of the usual 39 or 40. Normally, you want small decks so that you draw your best cards, but when you've got several dozen 'best cards', you want as large as you can to avoid drawing the combo bricks.  -Because you don't need to have more than one card for all this, you only need to use half your deck on this, which makes a whole bunch of room for disruptions and backup plays.  -Outside of generic disruption, there's basically only two options for non-normal-summoning, non-ED-using archetypes: Eldlich and Generaider. The advantage with Generaider is that it's *also* a one-card-starter archetype, so it leaves room for a heck-lot of disruption.  Hence, you have a deck that in a 5-card hand has an 88% chance of a pseudo-FTK, and a 57% chance of a Genraider Stage as backup, with an average of 1.4 disruption/going second cards.

deck_name: Vanity Dragma Cyber Angel Lock May 2020
deck_excerpt: Lock your opponent out of special summoning with Vanity's ruler. I also put a dragma engine in to deal with threats from the extra deck.
deck_description: Using the new Dragma cards as a toolbox, this deck can lock your opponent out of special summoning pretty easily and swarm the field with cyber angels. The Herald of Perfection is used as an omni-negate. what's good about it though is that is isn't once per turn, as long as you have a fairy in your hand. I dislike running too many impcantations as they brick if you don't have a ritual card in your hand. The extra deck is purely used for the Dragmas to destroy (except Herald of Mirage Lights) so don't try to get them on the board!  My rating:  Attack: 5/5  Defense: 4/5  Consistency: 3/5  Strong Against: General decks that love the extra deck, e.g. Salamangreat, Invoked  Weak Against: Altergeist, Mystic Mine Burn/Exodia  Dragma combo:  Activate Disciples of the Nadir, search for Ecclesia, sending Bastard to the GY  Normal summon Ecclesia, add Dogmatic Nation to the hand  Activate Dogmatic Nation so your opponent will risk losing a monster if they attack Ecclesia  End your turn. At the End Phase Bastard in the GY will activate, allowing you to SS Maximus Dragma from the deck.     Vanity Lock combo:  Get any 2 impcantations onto the field, searching for Benten and/or Machine Angel Ritual if you don't have them  Ritual any monster using Benten as a tribute  Benten's effect now activates, adding a Vanity's Ruler to the hand  Normal summon Vanity's ruler, using the Impcantations as tributes.  Vanity's Ruler stops your opponent from Special Summoning completely, meaning he can't even use Kaijus to get rid of your monsters.     Also, if you want to add in a Dragma engine into your deck, here it is :  1 Maximus Dragma  2-3 Ecclesia  3 Disciple of the Nadir  1 Dogmatic Nation  1-3 Bastard the Ashen Dragon  1 Psy-framelord Omega (for recycling your cards)  Any removal/versatility that your deck lacks, like N'tss for targeted destruction or Wind Pegasus for a Knightmare Unicorn-like effect.  Hope you like this deck and the Dragma engine! Have fun!

deck_excerpt: A Consistent Dragon Link deck with a Red-Eyes twist which enables stronger boards. Combo videos, explanation of Red-Eyes engine, and budget options in
deck_description: Index: 1 Intro 2 Red-Eyes Engine/cards 3 Combos 4 Budget options 5 Side Deck   1 Intro This is a Dragon Link deck that does Dragon Link deck things but with a Red-Eyes twist added in. Namely, I’ve expanded the Red-Eyes engine in the deck to exploit Black Metal Dragon’s effect not being a hard once per turn. I’ve also updated the deck with Eternity Code’s Noctovision Dragon and found Room to add a couple Pot of Avarices. Pot of Avarice gives the deck a lot more recycling of resources to play longer games than a normal Dragon Link deck would be able to. I have also done an extensive number of test hands to determine that this deck is just as consistent as a conventional competitive Dragon Link deck while making stronger boards.   2 Red Eyes Engine/cards The Red-Eyes cards are present for the most part not to make a Red-Eyes board but to smooth out or slightly beef up conventional Dragon Link combos. The primary way the deck expects to acquire these cards is by sending Black Metal Dragon to the GY. Red-Eyes Malefic can be used to turn a Romulus into a Hieratic before the deck Dark locks itself. Red-Eyes Alternative exists if you draw the normal Red-Eyes or don’t have a field spell to play Malefic. Red-Eyes Fang with Chain can target Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon and add another disruption onto your board.   I took out Borreload Dragon for a Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon because it fit thematically and there are enough lvl7 monsters to summon him somewhat reliably. That said I’m not sold that this card is actually a good pick and can be replaced with another extra deck monster or the original Borreload Dragon if you aren’t sold on him either.   3 Combos Here are some Youtube videos of different combos you’ll be looking for in this deck and how to perform them (Each video is about a minute long). Notably these combos are all done with minimum resources and can end on stronger boards with more resources invested. 1 card combo with Black Metal Dragon https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3TDyHNmjLwA 2 card combo with Rokket and Noctovision Dragon https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tSwGUosIoAo 2 card combo with Rokket and Quick Launch https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-BUC_x_3lBU 2 card combo with Rokket and Absorouter Dragon https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ny6Rl6a24V4 Playlist with all Combos: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL4wvY6W8_pobhm2edgCy0rZypqEcJbtdX 4 Budget Options 3x Dark Ruler No more -> Effect Veiler is a good budget handtrap 3x Called by the Grave -> D.D. Crow. Doesn’t protect your combos but is a really strong affordable hand trap right now. 1x Borreload Savage Dragon -> Draco Berserker of the Tenyi is much weaker but still provides a strong level 8 synchro disruption to end on. 1x Borrelsword Dragon -> Borreload Dragon 1x Red-Eyes Fang with Chain -> another Red-Eyes B. Dragon or else any other card you so choose. This card should be reprinted in Legendary Duelists: Season 1 so it should come down in price (hopefully).   Other budget options: Borreload Excharge Dragon, and Borrelguard Dragon, the Topologic Monsters, Galaxy Satellite Dragon, Barricadeborg Blocker, Saryuja, Wee Witch’s Apprentice, and Booster Dragon.   5 Side Deck There are so many options for the side deck at the moment at so many different price points I felt that I didn’t want to hold the deck back or make it really expensive by trying to recommend a specific side deck. Feel free to use whatever tech cards you think are best for current meta.

deck_name: TIME MACHINE (not the Time Machine trap card)
deck_excerpt: Consistent access to Time Wizard and Time Magus or Auroradon/Accesscode to break board while using tuner combo for Borreload Savage + Herald Arc Light
deck_description: The slightly better than Time Wizard card, Time Magus, finally has been revealed. Both of those cards are super easy to fetch, Time Wizard by using Fusion Deployment and Time Magus by Instant Fusion (can be via Verte too, means you can wipe the board anytime with 2 monsters). Going first, we use regular Halqifibrax/Auroradon combo for Borreload Savage and Herald of the Arc Light, while the going second strat has many ways to break the board. The Scrap lineup is very versatile, not only it can go to Halqifibrax, it also provides backup combo while can fetch Time Wizard via Desperado Barrel Dragon for further grindy game. Mathematician, Scrap Recycler (free link 4 or Verte while searching Time Wizard), Jet Synchron, and Tuning are our starter, making us playing 11 starters. Ghost Ogre (Crossout target, can replace it depends on popularity), 2 )-Lion (ensures Auroradon effect), 2 Time Wizard (easily searchable, its effect aint that good too), Magicalized Fusion (free Time Magus for late game), One Day of Peace (prevents damage from both Time Magus and Wizard), 3 Second Coin Toss (for big brain gamble), Millenium Eyes Restrict (negate discarded monster handtrap), Borreload Dragon (non-targeting non-destruction monster removal), Auroradon (combo piece, non-targeting destruction), Scrap Wyvern (backup combo, non-targeting destruction), Secure Gardna (prevents taking damage, summoned via Linkuriboh), Linkuriboh (enables Jet Synchron to Halqifibrax). Pros: Super consistent, great going first or second while still have follow up play, have big slot for staples. Cons: Both Time Magus and Wizard are gamble.

deck_excerpt: This guide will offer you how to actually play correctly with the new Numeron cards, you can also bring Number S0: Utopic ZEXAL with just 1 card, extr
deck_description: When you play this deck, all you need is start first than your opponent, and have in your hand only 2 cards to set-up the lockdown, but be aware that this play is easily counterable; cards like Infinite Impermanence, Nibiru the primal being, etc. Combos: Your first combo is: use Numeron Network to bring the Numbers 1,2,3 and 4, (if you had in your hand Memories of Hope, you are allowed to use and draw 4 cards, that is absolutely insane!) if you can battle, do it, because of their effect that allows you to probably OTK your opponent. If you don't, just use them to summon our deck boss Number S0: Utopic ZEXAL, and force your opponent to quarantine. And if you had the Generaider Boss Stage, don't worry and use it, so in the opponent turn you can summon a Generaider Boss of your choice and up to 4 Generaider Tokens; you can use the tokens either to use the effects of the Generaider Bosses or to Summon the Trias Hierarchia, Tributing 3 of those tokens you are able to destroy 1 enemy card and also draw 2 Cards. Another useful combo is summoning Accesscode Talker, if you had in your hand the Effect Veiler, you can normal summon him, and if you already had a monster on the field you can Link Summon the Crystron Halqifibrax, and due to their effect you can bring another Effect Veiler, from you, deck or graveyard, and if you do, use them to special summon Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians, but be aware that you need at least 3 spell cards in the field or both players graveyard, so, you can bring back the Effect Veiler and use them to Link Summon the Accesscode Talker, active their effect in Selene' in order to gain 3000 atk points, and he is also able to destroy up to  2 cards on the field by banishing the 2 link monsters used in this combo. this is a generic combo, but very effective though. Deck: Numeron Generaider Boss. Type: Lockdown, OTK. Difficulty: 5/10. Handiness/Consistency: 6/10 (the first turn matter? yes. How many cards do you need to extract 100% of this deck? 2 initial cards. It is easily counterable? yes). Draw power: 4/10, Conditional (can I use pot of desires? no). Recovery: 2/10. Comeback: 4/10. "This deck is recommended for Medium duelists, Average final turn: 5". The perfect initial hand at the first turn: Numeron Network, Generaider Boss stage, Trias Hierarchia, Memories of Hope, and 1 bait card -like terraforming or planet pathfinder. The perfect initial hand at Second turn: Numeron Network, Generaider Boss stage, Dark Ruler no More, Nibiru the primal being, Lightning Storm, and Memories of hope. so, as you can see, all we need is Numeron Network and Generaider Boss stage, and both are field spells that can be easily searched, by cards like terraforming, planet pathfinder, numeron wall, generaider boss fight, etc. I hope everyone could enjoy this guide, I pretend to make more guides in the future, If you want to make constructive criticism or add more information, feel free to comment below! That is it, folks! my name is Randall and I see y'all on the battlefields!

deck_excerpt: An MBT inspired deck, a super reliable deck thanks to Crystron Halqifibrax, Deskbot 001 & 003, MPB Auroradon as supports to call strong Synchro and Xy
deck_description: Make sure to review of the cards individually to apply this steps, to, 'cuz it hards on explain through text y'know. Example, if you have of this card/2cards in your first draw: summons Deskbot 003, > 001 > Halqifibrax > 001> Auroradon >(3)token > (2)001> Coltwing >(2)token > 001 > Herald > Quandax > F.A > Borrel > Nekroz. (This combo can do negates a lot, it is recommendable if your turn is first) note: Herald is used to add Nekroz to your hand by tributing to the GY using the second effect of Auroradon to call Coltwing to the field. note: 001 is summoned from the GY if two machine type tokens is summoned at the sametime.   2nd combo: it's the same combo as the first one but a little different. You can only call Superdreadnought xyz monster in the end if you have atleast 1 lvl 4 Mecha Phantom Beast in your hand. (Best to use this combo if your turn is second and if your opponent haven't done right in his first turn because of your negates using of your handtrap) Halqifibrax's effect is use to special summon O-Lion instead, then:  special summon Auroradon > (1)token > (3)token > 001 > lvl7 synchro monster > Coltwing > (2)token > 001 > Borrel > lvl4 any MPB monster > Superdreadnought Rail > Superdreadnought Jugger. note: MPB O-Lion's effect can special summon 1 token when it sent to the graveyard. Also you can use the effect to normal summon 1 MPB monster from you hand by banishing O-lion to the GY. note: lvl4 MPB monster's level adjust depends to the counts of lvl3 token on the field. Two tokens on the field can make MPB monsters lvl10 to xyz summon rank10 monster. Other cards to access the combo: (note: once you have 1tuner and 1tuner or 1monster to special summon Halqifibax and having 001 or more to the GY, you can full access the combo. Scrap Recycler: use the effect to send Jet Synchron to the GY Jet Synchron: you can use this to link summon Linkuriboh. You can activate this card's effect in the GY and special summon to the field by sending 1 card from your hand to the GY(send 001 if you do have). Instant Fusion: to summon 1 tuner or 1 effect Fusion monster for summoning Halqifibrax purposes. World Legacy Inheritor: useful when you special summon Linkuriboh on the field and use this Spell card to special summon that link material to the field. Foolish Burial: you can send 1 Jet Synchron or 1 Deskbot 001 from your deck to the GY. One for One: use to discard 1 card to the GY then special summon 1lvl1 (001 or Jet Synchron) monster to the field. Ash blossom and Ghost Ogre: use this much cards to negate, and you can also use this for material in link summoning if there's no choice. Emergency Teleport: to call Ghost Ogre from Hand or Deck to the field for emergency only! O-Lion: is also useful in some situations. Once this card is sent to the GY, you can special summon 1token. And also can banish O-Lion to free normal summon 1MPB monster from your hand. Nibiru: not much use at all. If you have this on your hand and your opponent doing combos....BOOM Conclusion: In the mid game if your opponent manages to destroy your succeed summoning combo. 70% chance to summon Auroradon (also thanks to the 001's and O-Lion) that can make easy way to fill your monster zone and make a comeback. Many ways to be creative, 90%  ways to access the combo in your first turn that is why it is the best. Can also beat the current Meta...nowadays mr5 that's all thanks for reading.

deck_excerpt: A variation of my last Dragma Cyber Angel deck
deck_description: After playing my last deck i decided to make a variation of it that uses the all new card - Diviner of Heralds. That card is really OP in this deck because if you can't send Herald of the Arc Light to the GY, you can use your Cyber Angels instead. it will also benefit Cyber Angel Vrash, giving it a guaranteed negate. To see my last decklist (which is the original deck i modified from) look here. My rating: Attack: 4/5 Defense: 5/5 Consistency: 4/5 Strong Against: General decks that love the extra deck, e.g. Salamangreat, Invoked Weak Against: Altergeist, Mystic Mine Burn/Exodia Combos: (In hand: Diviner of Heralds, Machine Angel Ritual) Normal summon Diviner of Heralds Activate its effect, sending Herald of the Arc Light from the Extra deck to the GY Activate Arc light, add Cyber Angel Idaten to the hand. Activate your Ritual, summon Idaten using Diviner as a tribute. Diviner's effect activates as it was tributed; summon Cyber Petit Angel from the deck. Chain Idaten's effect and add Machine Angel Absolute Ritual to the hand. Activate Petit angel's effect, add Vrash to the hand. Ritual summon Vrash with Cyber Petit Angel, Idaten and Diviner in the GY. Idaten's effect activates, turning your Vrash into a 4k beatstick permanently. Note that adding 1000 atk to Vrash isn't Vrash's effect, so using impermanence or veiler won't remove it. one of the ways to stop this is by activating Called by the Grave to banish Idaten after the Ritual summon.   Dragma combo: Activate Disciples of the Nadir, search for Ecclesia, sending Bastard to the GY Normal summon Ecclesia, add Dogmatic Nation to the hand Activate Dogmatic Nation so your opponent will risk losing a monster if they attack Ecclesia End your turn. At the End Phase Bastard in the GY will activate, allowing you to SS Maximus Dragma from the deck. Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Ever wanted to play Adamancipator in trinity format? This is the deck for you.
deck_description:
Strengths: 

Union Carrier lets you play the grind game with many other explosive decks Block Dragon is a great advantage maker that lets you tool box your entire deck and its protection helps push through boards. Has a very high ceiling when you open power cards such as Brilliant Fusion, Last Will, and Adamancipator excavations Can stun very well with Ties of the Brethren and Koa'ki Meiru

Weaknesses:

Can open very bricky hands (Solid Bricks) Very GY depended deck; Called by and Cosmic Cyclone hurt the deck a lot

Trinities:

2x Last Will (Extra Unlimited Card) 2x Brilliant Fusion (Extra Unlimited Card) 2x Adamancipator Researcher (Extra Unlimited Card)

Comments:

Union combo is summoning Union Carrier while you still control a Rock-type Monster and equipping Block Dragon from the deck The deck can do unfair plays such as ending on multiple Xyzs/Synchros if you get luckly with the Adamancipator Beta The Electromagnet Warrior is a 1 card Berserkion the Electromagna Warrior with 1 pop on summon (takes 2 turn)
  1. Normal Beta, Search Alpha The Electromagnet Warrior
  2. On the opponent's turn use Beta to tag out into Delta The Magnet Warrior, use its effect to foolish Gamma The Electromagnet Warrior
  3. On your turn summon Alpha search Berserkion, banish Gamma, Beta, Alpha from the field/gy to summon him from hand and banish Delta to pop a card (not once per turn)
The Side decked rocks are all searchable with Gallant Granite and can be summoned with Super Team Buddy Force Unite! Doki Doki is also a recruiter that summons from deck, with a low cost and can be used as an extender Brilliant Fusion doubles as a free body as well as a foolish for all rocks/Painful Decision Ties of the Brethren works as a combo finisher (at the end of Union Combo) or as a stun option (worth spending Trinitys on if you want to toolbox) Last Will helps with Union Combo and toolboxing from deck Adamancipator Risen - Dragite is a blowout card that can break boards (and gains protection form Block Dragon) Barrier Statue of the Drought + Koa'ki Meiru Overload is to much for most non Earth decks to handle, and you can turn off your own Barrier by turning it into Gallant

deck_excerpt: Just a basic Crusadia Kaiju OTK-based deck
deck_description: Crusadia Kaiju Deck 2020 Basic Crusadia Kaiju deck, if you're wondering why I used the Sky Striker cards it's because in this OTK based deck you can't afford to experience interruptions. You can change out the Sky Striker cards, I just used them and they seemed like an extra utility just in case your opponent tried to stop your play. You can also change out Monster Reborn for World Legacy Succession because you can search for it with Worl Legacy - World Crown, but even though that's there, Monster Reborn seemed more versatile than Succession because it doesn't limit you to special summoning to a zone a link monster points to. Back to the Sky Striker cards, the links can be replaced with other cards like Borrelsword Dragon or another boss monster. But normally with this deck, you won't have a turn 3 because you will most likely OTK your opponent.

This Trickstar deck uses the OCG only card Trickstar Fez. It is a really good card that literally is an instant Holly angel because it provides 2 tokens. Otherwise it can be used for  more burning if you already have an angel on the field. You can use Set Rotation or Terraforming to get a mystic mine or Trickstar Light Stage to the field, whichever one you need. A play I like to make is using Set Rotation to set Light Stage to my field and Mine to the other when my opponent has more monsters. This way They will either have to activate Mine to get rid of Light Stage, blocking all attacks and monster effects from him, or leave the Mine set, not allowing him to destroy Light Stage.  My Rating:  Attack: 3/5  Defense: 4/5  Consistency: 4/5  Strong Against: Adamancipator, Exodia  Weak against: True Draco, Vanity  Combos:  Cards in hand: Trickstar Fez, Trickstar Candina  Activate Fez, summoning 2 tokens  Link summon Holly Angel with the tokens  Normal summon Candina into a zone Holly angel points to, allowing the 200 damage  Activate Candina's effect, add Light Stage to the hand  Activate Light Stage and add Lilybell to the hand  Chain Lilybell's effect to Special summon herself to a zone Holly angel points to, dealing 200 damage + another 200 Lightstage damage  Link Lilybell into Bloom, doing 400 damage  Link Candina and Bloom into Crimson Heart, dealing 400 damage  Activate Crimson Heart if you want to, but it won't yield 2 cards  Link them all into a Bella Madonna, then activate her effect to do 1000 damage + another 200 damage from Light Stage  Total damage: 200 + 400 + 400 + 400 + 1000 + 200 =2600 damage     This deck is a very fun deck to play. It can be hard to make some combos at first but you'll get used to it. Have fun!

Although the deck doesn't consist of incredibly powerful cards that can win the game in a single attack, it requires careful placement and an effective plan of attack to use effectively.  Atlantean Attack Squad and Mystical Space Typhoon are effective at keeping the board clean while you attempt to build your forces. In the event where Atlantean Attack Squad is destroyed, it can be recovered by using salvage.  A Legendary Ocean and Tornado wall are the driving point of this deck, protecting your weaker monsters such as Starfish and Jellyfish while you prepare to Xyz or tribute summon for Shark Drake or Hyper-Ancient Shark Megalodon.  Before battling take note that Hyper-Ancient Shark is a CRUCIAL unit as its ability to destroy a monster you opponent controls after dealing damage can deal with monsters that are a great deal stronger then it. if it can attack any monster on the field, fish depth charge can deal with them for you or you can power up Megalodon with aqua-jet
